<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Quayle     10-06 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Quayle,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Quayle's Debate Effort `Headed Off Picking On'
Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Thursday he believes
Republican Dan Quayle's performance in the vice presidential debate
``headed off, or should have headed off, all this picking on him
that has been going on.''
   ``I think he handled himself very well,'' Reagan told reporters
who questioned him at a state dinner for President Moussa Traore of
Mali.
   ``I really think that Quayle actually, just by the whole nature
of the event, headed off, or should have headed off, all this
picking on him that has been going on,'' the president said.
   Reagan also said that some of the points that the Democrats were
claiming were made by Bentsen in the debate were based on ``things
that were not factually true, such as who is responsible for the
deficit and so forth.''
   Reagan, who is making a campaign trip to Michigan on Friday,
said he will be picking up the pace of his involvement in the
campaign between now and Election Day.
   Asked whether he thought the issues were being addressed in the
campaign, he said, ``Yes, I do. At least by our side.''
   Earlier, posing for photographers before a private meeting with
Traore, Reagan was asked whether he thought Quayle would be damaged
by the exchange in which Democrat Lloyd Bentsen criticized him for
comparing himself with the late President John F. Kennedy.
   ``No,'' he said. ``I thought that remark was a cheap shot and
unbecoming a senator of the United States.''
   When asked if it was a mistake for Quayle to make the comparison
in the first place, Reagan said, ``No. The only comparison he was
making was that he was being attacked, I think unfairly, on the
basis of his age and his experience in government and he was
pointing out that John Kennedy, who sought the highest office and
won it, had actually less experience in government than he had and
was the same age.''
</TEXT>
