<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ChineseShip     10-06 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chinese Ship,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detained Ship Departs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military authorities allowed a
Chinese research ship to sail away today after they were convinced
the vessel had simply sought shelter from a typhoon and was not
smuggling guns to local communist rebels, officials said.
   The 3,324-ton Science Research Vessel No. 1 had steamed into
northern Luzon Island's Casiguran Sound late Monday and Philippine
Constabulary troops seized it early the next day after a boarding
party found guns and ammunition aboard.
   The Chinese Embassy said the ship was seeking shelter from
Typhoon Nelson, which skirted northern Luzon Wednesday, and the
arms aboard were for protection of the ship's 56 scientists and 45
crew from pirates.
   The arms included three machine guns, eight assault rifles, two
semi-automatic rifles, two hand guns and 4,850 rounds of ammunition.
   Maj. Julius Yarcia, a constabulary intelligence officer
inspected the vessel for a second time Wednesday, and told
reporters today he found no signs the ship or the people aboard had
violated any Philippine law. The ship's scientists were reportedly
aboard to conduct underwater research.
   Military officials are wary of ships with arms because of
frequent reports of smuggling to communist rebels waging a 19-year
insurgency. Casiguran is in an area known for years as a rebel
stronghold.
   China maintains diplomatic relations with the Philippines and
has consistently denied giving the rebels any material aid.
</TEXT>
