<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PlasticBullets     10-06 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plastic Bullets,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Ammunition Draws Outcry As Casualties Mount</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli army's use of
plastic bullets to break up Palestinian demonstrations is filling
hospital wards with casualties and prompting calls for tighter
controls.
   Victims of the new ammunition, including two teen-agers treated
for plastic bullet wounds at Ahli Arab Hospital in Gaza City,
complain that stones thrown by protesters do not warrant the
penalty.
   ``It's unreasonable punishment,'' said Mazul Abu Lail, 19, a
tailor who was shot in the ankle.
   In a nearby bed, 16-year-old Rifaat Massoud, a construction
worker, nodded in agreement.
   ``It isn't right and it isn't fair for the soldiers to shoot
innocent people,'' Massoud said, shifting uncomfortably with a
bullet wound in his left side.
   The plastic bullet was introduced in August to supplement rubber
bullets, water cannons, tear gas and clubs in dealing with the
uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the other weapons ``proved
to be insufficient to cope with stone throwing'' and that the army
needed something less lethal than lead bullets.
   The aim, Rabin said, is to reduce anti-Israeli violence in the
territories with a minimum of fatalities. Since the uprising began
Dec. 8, at least 280 Palestinians have been killed and hundreds
injured. Six Israelis have died.
   But Rabin has acknowledged that the introduction of the plastic
bullets may lead to more injuries.
   In the past three weeks, more than 325 Palestinians have been
wounded in clashes with Israeli troops, many by plastic bullets,
hospital officials and Arab sources say.
   The army says plastic bullets can penetrate the body, but they
are not supposed to be lethal if fired from at least 70 yards.
However, at least four deaths from plastic bullets have been
reported at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City.
   Last week, Dr. Rustum Namari, director of the Mukassad Hospital
in East Jerusalem, showed reporters fragments of a plastic bullet
removed from the brain of a critically injured West Bank youth.
Namari said the bullet appeared to have been fired at close range.
   ``If a plastic bullet enters the throat, chest or abdomen, it
has the potential to cause death,'' said a surgeon at Shifa
Hospital who spoke on condition of anonymnity. ``Remember, too,
that bullets respect no age,'' he added. Victims, he said, have
ranged in age from 7 to 90.
   The bullets, developed after Israeli officials studied use of
plastic ammunition in France, are produced in Israel.
   Similar plastic rounds have been used in Northern Ireland for
riot control since 1970, and at least 13 deaths have been
attributed to them there.
   The United States, Britain and Egypt have objected to the use of
plastic ammunition against Palestinian demonstrators, and
opposition has been mounting in Israel.
   A senior official of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which
provides humanitarian services to Palestinian refugees, filed a
complaint with Israeli military officials after casualties in Gaza
jumped from 19 in July to more than 130 in September.
   Last week, the Association for Civil Rights in Israel filed a
petition with Israeli Attorney General Yosef Harish, urging him to
issue legal guidelines on the use of the new bullets.
   The group contended that ``opening fire for purposes of
deterrence is an illegal act'' and called on Harish to block use of
the bullet for riot control.
   Until recently, Israeli soldiers were instructed to fire lead or
plastic bullets only if their lives were in imminent danger. In
recent weeks, however, firing rules have been changed so troops may
use the plastic rounds to break up demonstrations.
   The army chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, told a parliament
committee Tuesday that the army needed to stop riots before they
get out of hand.
   ``Arabs who deliberately choose to go out and demonstrate are
getting injured,'' Shomron was quoted as saying in Jerusalem
newspapers. ``Eventually they will realize that it is not in their
interest to get involved in riots.''
   But he insisted strict orders had been issued against misusing
the new weapon. In addition to a firing range of 70 yards, the
bullets are to be aimed only at legs, Shomron said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
