<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Fashion     10-06 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Fashion,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sexy Milan Gets Cute, Dainty And Debutante</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In just six months, Italian fashion has
experienced a radical mood swing from aggressive and sexy to
subdued and demure.
   Leaving the miniskirted, spike-heeled woman behind, the Italian
designers presenting their spring-summer 1989 collections in Milan
this week are courting a younger, at least outwardly more innocent
woman who loves pants, long skirts and flat shoes.
   Her favorite colors are tender shades of cream and pink or the
classic combination of white with navy blue or black. Her taste in
fabrics ranges from diaphanous georgette and chiffon to batiste and
linen.
   Crisp white blouses, always a sign of good clean living, pop up
throughout the collections. Some are man-tailored, others daintily
lace-collared, still others a feminine version of the bowling shirt.
   Gianfranco Ferre, Italy's ``numero uno'' shirtmaker, opts for a
wide collared, man-tailored silk shirt embellished by a giant
nautical motif.
   The entire Ferre collection, presented in Milan Tuesday, was an
ode to the sea, with navy blue and white stripes the dominant
pattern and anchors, compasses and life preservers printed
everywhere.
   At the height of the miniskirt mania last year, Ferre, known for
his staid fashion, shocked the fashion crowd with the shortest,
tightest look on the Milan runway.
   In keeping with the current search for lost innocence, his
spring-summer collection brings hemlines right down to the ankle
and softens the silhouette with wide tops and loose-fitting pants.
   Extra feminine touches were offered by the high sailor suit
waistline on skirts and pants, and enticing see-through,
star-sequined T-shirts.
   Evening at Ferre was all stars and stripes in long shimmery
evening gowns, the tightest seen thus far on this week's Italian
ready-to-wear runway.
   On Wednesday, the fourth day of the five day showings, Basile
and Ferragamo continued the trend toward calmer, more feminine
styles.
   Luciano Soprani, for Basile, picked dainty floral prints for his
super-soft long skirts worn under a neat tight waisted blazer or a
belted Safari jacket.
   Evening wear turned the fashion page back to the heyday of the
debutante ball. Dressed in their empire-waisted full-skirted
strapless evening gowns, they looked as innocent as a busload of
college freshmenn at their first mixer.
   Even when the rest of Milan was vying for the shortest look,
Ferragamo persevered in its classic tailored style, with a discreet
knee-skimming hemline. It took the sedate Florentine tailors little
effort to lengthen this look to mid-calf in slim unfussy skirts
worn under a simple short-sleeved linen blazer.
   The classic look continued in the Chanel-inspired little black
day suits with gold buttons worn with a Ferragamo logo T-shirt.
Ferragamo, famous for its shoes, capitalized on its own classics by
dotting the collection with little golden shoes as lapel pins and
charms on a bracelet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     10-06 0926</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0973</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Whoopi Goldberg wants to
end her two-year marriage to Dutch cinematographer David Claessen,
citing irreconcilable differences.
   Details of the divorce petition Miss Goldberg filed Tuesday
weren't disclosed by her spokeswoman, Lee Solters.
   Claessen, 29, and Miss Goldberg, 38, met during the filming of a
documentary on the homeless.
   The couple have no children. Solters said Wednesday that they
``have been separated for some time'' and that Miss Goldberg has
been living with cameraman Eddie Gold.
   Miss Goldberg, who won an Oscar nomination for her performance
in Steven Spielberg's ``The Color Purple,'' stars in Warner Bros.'s
forthcoming movie ``Clara's Heart.'' She will soon be seen on the
TV series ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The photographer whose car and camera were
damaged by Cher's boyfriend, 24-year-old Rob Camilletti, says
Camilletti is getting off the hook.
   ``I think he should have been charged with assault with a deadly
weapon. No, I'm not pleased with these charges,'' Peter Brandt, a
photographer for the entertainment tabloid Star, said Wednesday.
   Camilletti was charged Wednesday with reckless driving and
malicious mischief. The misdemeanor offenses are less serious than
the felony charge of assault with a deadly weapon for which
Camilletti was booked after the June 27 confrontation. Camilletti
was released on $2,000 bail.
   Camilletti had said he lost control of Cher's black Ferrari
while swerving to avoid photographers outside the home he shares
with the Oscar-winning actress. He said he hit Brandt's car and
then smashed his camera and telephone.
   Brandt accused Camilletti of trying to kill him, and sued the
couple for unspecified damages.
   Reckless driving carries up to 90 days in jail and a $1,000
fine; the two counts of malicious mischief could bring up to 18
months in jail and a $6,000 fine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WINTER SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheelah Ryan, winner of Florida's
record $55.1 million Lotto jackpot last month, passed up the chance
to claim another prize her extraordinary luck brought her: a
blender she won at a raffle.
   Her name was drawn for a door prize at an open house held for a
new office of Prudential Bowles Realty, where she used to work,
said owner Wil Bowles.
   By the time her name was drawn Friday, Ms. Ryan had left and
another name was selected for the prize.
   ``I don't think missing it will worry her,'' said Bowles.
   Her former boss also disclosed that Ms. Ryan has bought a
$260,000 house through the real estate firm she quit after winning
the nation's largest lottery prize.
   Bowles said Ms. Ryan paid cash for the house, the location of
which he would not disclose.
</TEXT>
