<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForeignOwnership Bjt   10-06 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Ownership, Bjt,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Investment Disclosure Bill Clears House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign investors with a ``significant
interest'' in American business or property would have to disclose
their holdings to the government under legislation approved by the
House.
   ``Give us the opportunity to have a basic inventory of ownership
of the American economy,'' Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, the sponsor,
said as the House approved the measure 250-170 on Wednesday.
   The measure now goes to the Senate, where its chances for
approval are dim.
   Those owning more than 5 percent of a business or property
valued at more than $5 million or that has more than $10 million in
annual gross sales would have to report their identity and holdings
to the Commerce Department.
   The measure also would apply to investors holding more than 5
percent of a combination of two or more businesses or properties
valued at more than $20 million or with annual gross sales of more
than $40 million.
   Foreigners with ``controlling interests'' in U.S. businesses and
properties would be required to submit more extensive reports,
including balance sheets and the identities of officers and
directors.
   The Commerce Department would establish a registry of foreign
interests owning American property.
   Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn., described the measure as
``election-year xenophobia'' designed to capitalize on fear of
foreigners among voters.
   Supporters retorted that foreign takeover of U.S. assets should
not occur in secret.
   ``The American people have the right to know who holds the
mortgage on America,'' Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, declared.
   The bill originally was included in the House's version of a
wide-ranging trade measure signed by President Reagan Aug. 23. But
sponsors, seeking to build support for the trade bill, dropped the
foreign ownership provision before it went to Reagan.
   The foreign ownership disclosure bill is now moving forward as
separate legislation.
   The measure's prospects are dim in the Senate, where it would be
vulnerable to a time-consuming filibuster with only days remaining
until lawmakers adjourn to campaign full time.
   Critics say the bill would bare business secrets that ought to
be private, thus scaring off foreigners whose investment helps to
finance the budget deficit and fuels the economy, creating jobs for
Americans.
   ``The issue is confidentiality,'' said Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y.
``This bill doesn't have adequate safeguards.''
   Data on foreign ownership of American property already is
collected by 17 federal agencies. But the information is often kept
secret, even from Congress, and in any case the names of the actual
owners rarely appear.
   Complaints persist that even those reports are often incomplete,
inaccurate and largely meaningless and that hundreds of billions of
dollars in new investment have simply fallen through the cracks in
recent years.
   Opponents also blasted the bill as discriminatory toward foreign
investors because Americans would not have to provide the same
information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-06 0839</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Consumers Likely To Feel Effects Of Wheat Price Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Agriculture Department analysis of this
summer's drought-induced rise in wheat prices says consumers might
feel some effect at grocery stores at least through 1989.
   ``Past movements suggest that the drought's influence on farm
prices of wheat will be felt for about a year at the industrial
(wholesale) level and for a year and a half or more by consumers,''
the report said.
   The study was done by Ronald A. Babula of the department's
Economic Research Service, and David A. Bessler, Texas A&M
University, and reported in the current issue of Agricultural
Outlook magazine.
   Babula said Wednesday in a telephone interview that he and
Bessler are not forcasting how food prices will behave in the
coming months. Prices of various items could decline but still
leave some impact from the 1988 drought.
   ``We're not predicting anything,'' Babula said. ``We're showing
how things have moved in the past ... and some of the things that
we might expect to see happen in the future.''
   A statistical computer model was used to show how prices of
wheat at the farm, wholesale prices and retail prices have moved
together in the past.
   The model was then ``shocked'' with an increase in the farm
price of wheat to simulate the 7.7 percent average monthly boost
during May, June and July, when the effects of the drought were
first reflected in the market.
   ``When the farm price shock occurs, processor (wholesale) prices
for wheat rise immediately, peaking a month after the rise in the
farm price,'' the report said. ``At their highest, processor prices
increase less than half of the 7.7 percent increase in the farm
price. Processor price increases are felt for about a year, but the
impulse generally declines in strength through time.''
   On the other hand, the 7.7 percent average increase in the farm
price of wheat ``generates gradual, not immediate, increases in
consumer prices of wheat-related goods,'' the report said.
   Delivery, sale and consumption of flour, bread, cake mixes,
pasta and other wheat-related foods occur throughout the year and
are not as closely tied to the wheat crop cycle as processing,
which includes the flour milling and baking industries.
   ``So, the consumer price effects last more than a year,'' the
report said. ``Consumer price rises peak at seven months, but
prices stay relatively high until 17 to 20 months after the
initiating farm price shock. The increase in consumer prices is
smaller but more enduring than the jump in processor prices.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some promising new biological weapons are
being used in the war against marauding grasshoppers, says the
Agriculture Department.
   In one development, two commercial firms _ Evans BioControl Inc.
of Broomfield, Colo., and Bozeman Bio Tech of Bozeman, Mont. _ have
adapted USDA technology for producing and storing a parasite,
Nosema lucustae. Department studies show the parasite kills 50
percent to 60 percent of grasshoppers in three to four weeks.
   The basic tests and development were done by the department's
Agricultural Research Service at the agency's Rangeland Insect
Laboratory in Bozeman by J.E. Henry and colleagues.
   Henry said the parasite is available to homeowners and ranchers
through regional agents and on contract to government agencies,
which use it on a large scale in the West. Grasshoppers cause an
estimated $400 million in damage to grass and crops each year, he
said.
   Spores of the parasite are put on wheat bran flakes to form a
bait. After the insects eat the bait, the organism ``attacks the
pest's fat cells and depletes its energy stores,'' Henry said in a
report issued here on Wednesday.
   The parasite remains in the grasshopper population because sick
females pass it on to offspring, and survivors eat dead relatives,
he said.
   Meanwhile, another development involves an agreement with Evans
Biotechnical to field test another natural killer, grasshopper
entomopoxvirus, the agency said. In laboratory tests, the virus
kills 20 percent to 30 percent of the grasshoppers right away and
stunts the growth of an additional 20 percent to 30 percent.
   Doug A. Streett, an entomoligist at the agency's Bozeman
laboratory, said Evans BioControl plans to produce the virus and
mix it with the parasite for tests on 1,000 acres in the West.
   Streett said that in combination the two ingredients may work
more rapidly to kill the grasshoppers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ice cream production in August was estimated
by the Agriculture Department at 87.7 million gallons, up 4 percent
from a year earlier.
   That didn't count 39.4 million gallons of ice milk, a 20 percent
increase from August 1987, or 5.21 million gallons of sherbet, up
13 percent.
   August production figures issued on Wednesday also showed butter
output at 74.2 million pounds, up 12 percent from a year earlier.
Production of American-type cheese, at 214 million pounds, was up 4
percent.
   Production of non-fat dry milk was reported at 66.6 million
pounds, down 17 percent from August 1987.
</TEXT>
