<1ST_LINE>r i PM-LatinRulers     10-06 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Latin Rulers,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet One Of Few Authoritarian Leaders Remaining In Latin
America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet is one of the few
authoritarian leaders left in Latin America, where elected civilian
government has returned to most countries.
   The nearest geographically is Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, who has
ruled Paraguay since seizing power in 1954.
   President Fidel Castro has governed Cuba since leading a
successful revolution in 1959 and installing a communist regime.
   In Panama, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega qualifies as an
authoritarian leader but is not technically the chief of state.
   Elected civilian governments have replaced military regimes in
the last few years in Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, Peru, Ecuador and
Bolivia.
   Military governments ruled Brazil for two decades until 1985.
Five generals took turns as president, chosen by their peers and
sharing power with them.
   Argentina's armed forces ousted civilian President Isabel Peron
in March 1976 and retained power until 1983, leaving in disgrace
after defeat in the Falkland Islands war with Britain.
   Governing was an act of the military institution in both
countries, but the regimes of Pinochet, 72, and Stroessner, 75, are
personal.
   Pinochet declared a few years ago: ``Not a single leaf moves in
this country unless I move it,'' and Stroessner probably could say
the same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PinochetProfile     10-06 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pinochet Profile,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet: Combative With An Anti-Communist Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Augusto Pinochet has been tireless in
what he sees as a mission from God to reconstruct a new,
communist-proof society.
   Shrewd and combative, Pinochet successfully resisted the
regional trend toward elected civilian rule that prevailed in many
Latin American countries in the 1980s. His right-wing authoritarian
regime, he says, is a bulwark against Marxism.
   Pinochet took power in 1973 in a coup that toppled the elected
government of Marxist President Salvador Allende. The takeover won
wide support because it occurred at a time of social unrest and
economic chaos. Few, however, could have predicted Pinochet would
remain in power this long.
   But Pinochet immediately banned all political activity and
purged the nation of tens of thousands of leftists. Most were
expelled, although hundreds were imprisoned and scores were
tortured and executed, according to human rights groups.
   Pinochet also outmaneuvered the commanders of the navy, air
force and national police, who were initially supposed to alternate
with him as the country's ruler. Using his muscle as army
commander, the most powerful of Chile's military branches, he
emerged as the sole leader.
   Born Nov. 25, 1915, in the port city of Valparaiso, Pinochet was
one of three children of a customs official. Ignoring parental
pleas to study medicne, he entered the military academy, after
twice being rejected as too young and physically weak.
   In the army he filled out to 185 pounds and earned a university
degree. Now, he boasts a boxer's physique and is said to lifts
weight daily. He is reported to drink little.
   According to a 1980 autobiography, he noted an international
Marxist threat while commanding a camp for Communist prisoners in
1948 and lectured on the dangers of communism while teaching at the
national war college.
   However, when Allende became president Pinochet remained
outwardly loyal and was named army commander a month before the
coup. Some participants in the takeover said he joined the
conspiracy opportunistically at the last minute.
   The political repression that followed the coup earned Pinochet
an image as a brutish dictator. Repression included the
assasination of critics in exile, including Orlando Letelier,
killed in a Washington car bombing in 1976. Pinochet has denounced
foreign criticism as interferring in Chile's internal affairs.
   He announced plans to reshape Chilean society and construct
safeguards against communism. A Constitution approved in a 1980
referendum bans all ideologies based on class struggle. It also
included a phased return to democracy and called for the
presidential plebiscite that occurred Wednesday.
   He launched a free-market economic program that, coupled with
heavy foreign borrowing and an overvalued currency, produced a
financial near-collapse in the early 1980s. Massive anti-government
protests threatened to topple his government. But he moderated his
policies, winning even the begrudged praise of his opponents with
five years of steady economic growth and stability.
   Pinochet preaches patriotism, family values and hard work. His
stern demeanor appeals to many common Chileans, but his behavior
bothers most educated citizens.
   He often appears in public with his wife, Lucia. They have three
daughters and two sons.
   In recent years, especially since a September 1986 assasination
attempt by leftist guerrillas, Pinochet has come to cite God. In
1987 he declared, ``God put me on the top.''
   Now obsessed with personal security, his motorcade routinely
includes four cars of heavily armed bodyguards, a van carry an army
commando unit, an ambulance and an army helicopter gunship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirlineScorecard     10-06 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Scorecard,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It Was a Pretty Good Summer for Airlines, Their Passengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's airlines did a pretty good job of
delivering their passengers on time this past summer, with more
than four of every five flights arriving near schedule, government
figures show.
   The Transportation Department said Wednesday that in August the
13 leading airlines had an on-time record of 83 percent, the second
best since monthly reports have been available. The only better
month was June, which had an 84.3 percent on-time record, the
government said.
   From April through August the airlines reported better than 80
percent of their flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule _
considered on time by the government _ each month.
   The summer months normally have delay problems because of the
heavy vacation travel as well as frequent thundershowers and other
weather problems, according to industry experts.
   Two years ago the summer travel months brought record flight
delays and loud complaints. The Federal Aviation Administration
reported more than 1,000 delays a day because of air traffic
control problems alone in the summer of 1986. That was an increase
of 25 percent over the previous years. No statistics on total
number of delays were available at that time.
   The delay problem eased a bit in the summer of 1987, but
congressional pressure and loud protests from air travelers
prompted the department to order the airlines to provide monthly
on-time performance reports beginning in September 1987.
   During the first year of the reporting requirement, the air
carriers averaged a 78 percent on-time record, the department said
Wednesday.
   Air traveler complaints to the department's consumer affairs
office have declined sharply, according to the figures provided
Wednesday.
   During September, the last month available, the department
received 1,897 such complaints, 20 percent fewer than in August and
66 percent fewer than in September 1987, when the department
received 5,618 complaints from air travelers.
   The on-time statistics cover the 13 leading airlines and do not
include delays attributed to mechanical problems, although they do
include delays caused by poor weather.
   In August, according to the department, Delta Air Lines had the
best on-time record among the largest air carriers, with 86.9
percent of its flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule,
followed by Continental Airlines (86.8) and American Airlines
(85.9).
   The overall best on-time record was given to two smaller Sun
Belt carriers _ America West (91.5 percent) and Southwest Airlines
(90.5 percent).
   Pan American World Airways and USAir reported the worst on-time
records, with one of every four flights arriving late, the
department said.
   The Salt Lake City, Utah, airport had the best arrival record in
August, with 91.4 percent of the flights landing within 15 minutes
of schedule. The Pittsburgh airport, where repairs on a runway have
contributed to delays, had the worst record, with 71.3 percent of
the flights landing on time.
   Hawaiian Airlines had the worst complaint record with 12.57
complaints for every 100,000 passengers flown in September,
followed by Pan American World Airways with 11.45.
   Meanwhile, in August the number of mishandled bags was down
slightly, averaging 7.03 for every 1,000 passengers, compared with
7.15 in July.
   TWA had the highest number of mishandled baggage reports, with
10.77 for every 1,000 passengers, followed by Piedmont Airlines at
8.93 per 1,000 passengers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Radon     10-06 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Radon,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Putting Final Touches To Radon Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is putting the finishing touches on a
campaign to reduce indoor exposure to radon, the naturally
occurring gas that health officials say is second only to smoking
as a cause of lung cancer deaths.
   Pending in the Senate is House-passed legislation that would
require inspections of public schools for dangerous levels of radon
and set a long-term national goal of having indoor air as free of
the gas as the air outdoors.
   Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., said he expects the bill to easily
clear the Senate in the closing days of the 1988 session and go to
the White House, where it already has been endorsed by the Reagan
administration.
   The broadly supported legislation, which won voice-vote approval
in the House on Wednesday, is moving toward the statute books in
the wake of a recent warning by the U.S. Public Health Service and
the Environmental Protection Agency.
   The agencies advised people to have their residences tested for
radon, an odorless, colorless gas produced by the decay of uranium
deposits found in the ground in many parts of the nation.
   EPA and USPHS estimated that nationally one of every 10 houses
could have dangerous levels of radon. They said they believe such
levels are present in about 25 percent of the homes in 17 states
where radon deposits are prevalent.
   Authorities have estimated that indoor concentrations of radon
are responsible for as many as 20,000 lung cancer deaths annually.
   The House-passed bill would require EPA to conduct a national
survey of school buildings and advise local education agencies
about ways of reducing high concentrations of radon.
   It would authorize $30 million over the next three years for a
matching grant program to help states set up their own radon
control programs. Less than half the states now have such programs.
   EPA would be required to set up training programs to teach state
and local officials proper techniques for radon monitoring,
assessment and mitigation. It also would have to set standards for
certifying radon measuring devices and rating the effectiveness of
radon-control contractors.
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, the bill's floor manager in the
House, said these provisions are needed to protect homeowners from
unscrupulous contractors and profiteers.
   ``New radon testing and mitigation companies spring up
overnight, and unfortunately not all of them are qualified or
scrupulous,'' he said.
   ``Contractors have charged as much as $4,000 when they could
have charged $1,000 and still profited nicely,'' Luken said. ``Even
worse, salespeople have tried to palm off fly paper and vacuum
cleaners as testing and mitigation devices.''
   The bill also would create a process under which state and local
building codes would eventually be revised to require the use of
construction techniques that would minimize the entry of radon into
structures.
   EPA has set 4 picocuries of radon per liter of air as the level
at which homeowners should take steps to make their houses more
resistant to radon seepage from the ground.
   House sponsors of the bill say it is uncertain whether this
level is fully protective of human health during long-term exposure
to indoor radon. They said this is why they want to set a national
goal of minimizing exposure to radon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
