<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Europe-AcidRain     10-06 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Europe-Acid Rain,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Research Reveals Widespread Pollution in European Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acid rain has polluted more than half
of Europe's lakes and rivers, and the contamination has spread much
farther than earlier believed, an international report said.
   The report, which was released Wednesday, said nearly all small
bodies of water in central Europe are so badly contaminated that
they can no longer be used for drinking water. It also said the
actual damage could be much worse because the research was based
mainly on information provided by the countries involved.
   ``In some cases, it is too late to do anything,'' said Kaarle
Kenttamies, head of the Finnish Environment Ministry team which
conducted the survey for the U.N.-sponsored Convention on
Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
   ``In other countries, particularly the peripheral regions such
as Scandinavia and southernmost Europe, there is still hope,'' he
told The Associated Press.
   ``But many small lakes and rivers, especially in central Europe,
are dead, and only a 100 percent drop in sulfur emissions can save
them,'' he said. He also said dumping heavy doses of lime could
also help reduce acidity.
   The year-long research project showed nearly all smaller bodies
of water in central Europe can no longer be used as sources of
drinking water, Kenttamies said.
   Acid rain carries a high concentration of acids produced by
sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxide and other chemicals emitted during
the burning of fossil fuels. The U.N.-sponsored conference, which
drew participants from the United States, the Soviet Union and nine
west European nations, urged the Economic Commission for Europe to
adopt stricter measures to fight pollution caused by nitrogen and
sulfur emissions.
   The commission's member countries have decided to start a joint
international pollution monitoring project in 1989 to study
environmental changes caused by acid rain.
   ``Despite certain opposition to such research, particularly in
the United States and Great Britain, we can can safely say that
acidification is one of the worst pollution problems of the
1980s,'' Kenttamies said.
   President Reagan has been criticized by environmentalists for
failing to do more to solve the problem of acid rain during his two
terms in office. In August, however, he gave the go-ahead for
continuing negotiations toward U.S. participation in an
international treaty to freeze emissions of a precursor to acid
rain.
   
   Kenttamies rejected as ``nonsense'' the argument that no
conclusive evidence exists that fossil fuel-fired power stations
contribute heavily to acid rain.
   ``Whatever people say, I've seen enough reports and been to
enough conventions like the one here today to know that we have
such conclusive evidence,'' he said.
   The high cost of fighting acid rain is a problem for countries
which rely heavily on fossil fuels. Britain and Poland, both heavy
coal users, are the only European nations which refused to join in
a project to reduce sulfur emissions by 30 percent of 1980 levels
by 1993.
   Acid rain in Scandinavia, mostly from industrial centers in
eastern and western Europe, also has contaminated lakes and forests.
   Finns were recently shocked to learn of heavy pollution in what
had been considered virgin Lapland in northern Finland caused by
huge Soviet copper and nickel works in the Kola Peninsula.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
