<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Senate-Judges     10-06 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate-Judges,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Advances 11 Court Nominees, Leaves 14 for Later
Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee sent 11 of
President Reagan's court nominees to the full Senate, leaving 14
others with virtually no chance of winning confirmation this year.
   The committee on Wednesday approved two U.S. appellate court
nominees: U.S. District Judge John M. Duhe Jr. of Lafayette, La.,
for the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals; and state common pleas
Judge Richard L. Nygaard of North East, Pa., for the 3rd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   U.S district court nominees approved by the committee were:
Lewis Babcock, Boulder, Colo., for the District of Colorado;
Norwood C. Tilley, Greensboro, N.C., for the Middle District of
North Carolina; Alex R. Munson, Saipan, for the Northern Mariana
Islands; Robert Leon Jordan, Johnson City, Tenn., for the Eastern
District of Tennessee.
   Also, D. Brooks Smith, Altoona, Pa., for the Western District of
Pennsylvania; Charles R. Butler Jr., Mobile, Ala., for the Southern
District of Alabama; Jay C. Waldman, Philadelphia, for the Eastern
District of Pennsylvania; Paul V. Gadola, Grand Blanc, Mich., for
the Eastern District of Michigan and James R. McGregor of
Pittsburgh, for the Western District of Pennsylvania.
   McGregor was approved on the request of Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa. A state judge who has issued controversial rulings, McGregor
could be held up on the Senate floor, according to committee
Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del. Biden said he's not fully
satisfied with McGregor's qualifications but withheld final
judgment.
   Nominations that previously reached the floor: Richard L.
Voorhees, Gastonia, N.C., for U.S. district judge for the Western
District of North Carolina; Susan Liebeler, Falls Church, Va., for
U.S. circuit judge for the Federal Circuit in Washington, D.C.;
Robert P. Patterson Jr., New York City, for U.S. district judge for
the Southern District of New York; Stuart A. Summit, New York City,
for the 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals.
   The following nominations are virtually certain to expire with
congressional adjournment:
   Appellate nominees Judith Richards Hope, Washington, D.C., for
U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia; Pamela Ann Rymer,
Los Angeles, for 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals; Jacques L.
Wiener Jr., Shreveport, La., for the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals; Guy G. Hurlbutt, Boise, Idaho, for the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals; Ferdinand F. Fernandez, Upland, Calif., for the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   District court nominees Vaughn R. Walker, San Francisco, for the
Northern District of California; Howard E. Levitt, Malverne, N.Y.,
for the Eastern District of New York; Donald E. Abram, Greenwood
Village, Colo., for the District of Colorado; Shannon T. Mason Jr.,
Newport News, Va., for the Eastern District of Virginia.
   Also, William H. Erickson, Englewood, Colo., District of
Colorado; Robert C. Bonner, Pasadena, Calif., for the Central
District of California; Adriane J. Dudley St. Thomas, V.I., for the
District Court of the Virgin Islands; Melinda Harmon, Houston, for
the Southern District of Texas and Marvin J. Garbis, Baltimore, for
the District of Maryland.
