<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SocialSecurityCOLAs     10-06 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Social Security COLAs,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House: No `Elderly' Index Needed To Figure Social Security
COLAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration sees no need to
change the formula for calculating cost-of-living increases for
Social Security and other entitlements despite claims that millions
of beneficiaries are being shortchanged.
   White House Budget Director James C. Miller III on Wednesday
said it ``would make no difference'' in what the government spends
on those increases if one Labor Department consumer price index
were subsituted for another in figuring the increases.
   But in a written statement to the Senate Special Committee on
Aging, Miller said, ``I do not believe any changes are needed at
the present time.''
   The panel's chairman, Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont., has introduced
two bills that would immediately substitute one inflation survey
for the other in calculating benefit increases and spend $1.5
million to develop a new survey devoted only to price changes
experienced by the elderly.
   With figures due out in two weeks on how big an increase 38
million Social Security recipients can expect in their checks next
year, the committee held hearings on Melcher's proposals Wednesday.
   Miller cited a Congressional Budget Office study showing that
families headed by people 65 or over have experienced ``the largest
real income gains of any age group between 1970 and 1986.''
   ``Social Security beneficiaries have in fact been well protected
from inflation over the last decade and a half under the exisiting
cost-of-living provisions,'' he said. ``Poverty rates among the
elderly have been cut in half over this period.''
   Since 1978, the government has used annualized third-quarter
changes in the Labor Department's consumer price index for urban
wage earners and clerical workers (CPI-W) to calculate the annual
benefit increases.
   Last year, for example, annualized inflation as measured by that
index for that quarter was 4.2 percent, yielding Social Security
recipients an average $21 a month increase in their benefit checks.
   Melcher and advocacy groups for the elderly want the government
to switch to a more widely used price index for urban households
(CPI-U) immediately, while developing an entirely new CPI-E for the
elderly for eventual use in calculating the benefit changes.
   At Wednesday's hearing, Melcher said the CPI-W understates the
increases that the elderly actually are experiencing because it
does not take into account the higher percentages of their income
spent on medical care and housing.
   Annual differences in the CPI-U and CPI-W indexes have ranged
from 0.1 percent to 0.5 percent over the past five years. But
cumulated inflation as measured by the wage earners survey totaled
16.5 percent over the five years compared with 18.2 percent as
measured by the more widely accepted urban household survey.
   ``This means that millions of retirees who depend on benefits or
pensions from these programs may not be getting a square deal,''
Melcher said. ``If all the costs of the elderly were figured in,
(annual) COLAs would be higher as much as $5 a month. For some
people $5 isn't very much money, but for many elderly $5 is a lot
of money.''
   At Melcher's instigation, the Labor Department earlier this year
constructed an experimental index measuring only the inflation
experienced by consumers age 62 and over.
   Reflecting that the elderly spend nearly 9 percent of their
income on medical costs compared with roughly 5 percent spent by
urban households in general, it showed inflation over the past five
years totaling 19.5 percent for those 62 and over.
   Had the experimental index been in use, the average Social
Security retiree would have received a total of $528 in additional
benefits over the past five years, said Mary Jane Yarrington, a
policy analyst for an advocacy group, the National Committee to
Preserve Social Security and Medicare.
   However, Labor Statistics Commissioner Janet L. Norwood said the
experimental survey had larger sampling errors than the official
measures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
