<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MoneyLaundering     10-06 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Laundering,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerry, McConnell Vow To Add Money Laundering Provision To Drug
Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a Senate narcotics panel says
foreign banks must be forced to keep records of large cash
transactions to help block laundering of U.S. drug profits.
   ``Cash, U.S. dollars, are the stock and trade of narcotics
traffickers and currently there is a gigantic loophole,'' Sen. John
F. Kerry, D-Mass., said Wednesday.
   Kerry, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
narcotics and terrorism, said an estimated $30 billion to $100
billion in drug-tied U.S. cash is laundered each year.
   He and Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the panel's ranking Republican,
said that when the Senate begins debate on sweeping drug
legislation they would push an amendment designed to create a paper
trail for prosecutors. Debate on the drug legislation is expected
to start before the end of next week, when Congress adjourns for
campaigning.
   Major drug traffickers now take U.S. drug profits by plane or
boat to nations in the Caribbean or Central America and deposit
huge chunks of cash in banks there, often under phony corporation
names, Kerry said. The dealers then have the banks wire the money
to the institutions' U.S. branches.
   In that way, drug traffickers can launder their illegal profits
and avoid federal regulations that require banks in the United
States to maintain strict records of cash transactions of $10,000
or more.
   The Kerry-McConnell proposal would extend that requirement to
foreign banks with U.S. branches as well as to American banks with
overseas offices.
   Kerry said he expected strong opposition from large banks.
   ``This bill will destabilize drug dealers' criminal networks by
denying them free access to the American banking system,''
McConnell said. ``It will give law enforcement officials the tools
necessary to trace and seize drug assets and prosecute those
criminals right out of business.''
   The Kerry-McConnell amendment would require the Treasury
Department to negotiate within two years agreements with nations
that have been identified as key money-laundering centers.
   Under the legislation, all offshore banks with U.S. ties would
be required to maintain records of cash transactions of $10,000 or
more, obtain from those depositors a waiver of privacy rights if
the records are needed in a drug-related investigation, and obtain
from depositors personal identification and documents stating the
source of the money.
   ``With enactment of this amendment, international drug dealers
will have to find a black market dry cleaner for their U.S. dollars
because all the legitimate laundromats will be closed to them,''
Kerry told a news conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Greenhouse-Congress     10-06 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greenhouse-Congress,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal To Combat `Greenhouse Effect' Focuses On Energy
Efficiency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new House bill designed to combat the
``greenhouse effect,'' or global warming trend, would require a
wide range of energy-saving measures, including a higher ``gas
guzzler'' tax and rebates for buyers of fuel-efficient autos.
   Republican and Democratic lawmakers said Wednesday in
introducing the legislation that they did not expect action on the
bill before Congress adjourns next week.
   The Reagan administration has said more study is needed before
taking action to curb the greenhouse effect.
   Rep. Claudine Schneider, R-R.I., chief architect of the new
proposal, said available options for reducing greenhouse gases such
as carbon dioxide can vary in cost by ten-fold or more.
   ``This makes it imperative that the strategy the federal
government undertakes in formulating global warming prevention
policies avoids imposing needless and wasteful expenditures ...,''
she said.
   The global warming trend, which some scientists say already has
begun, could raise the average temperature of the earth by 3
degrees to 8 degrees in the middle of the next century.
   The warming comes about because gases arising from human
activity build up in the atmosphere, trapping radiant heat that
normally would escape to space. The most important gas, carbon
dioxide, comes from the burning of fossil fuels such as oil and
coal.
   Also on Wednesday, a report from the Environmental and Energy
Study Institute, a companion organization to the congressional
Environmental and Energy Study Conference, called for a `first
priority'' on energy efficiency by the next administration.
   The report said political leaders must be willing to raise the
consumer cost of using fuels that produce carbon dioxide. A
prominent example would be gasoline.
   Ms. Schneider's measure calls for substantial increases in funds
for research and development, modification of federal buildings to
create 40 percent energy savings by the end of the century, tough
efficiency standards for electric lights and major increases in
auto fuel efficiency along with a higher ``gas-guzzler'' tax and
rebates for buyers of efficient models.
</TEXT>
