<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-CentralAmerica     10-06 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Central America,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Shrugs Off His Support For Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen shrugged off his differences
with Michael Dukakis over supporting Nicaragua's Contra rebels and
said the important point was they both support efforts to bring
peace to Central America while the Reagan administration offers
only a military answer.
   Republican Dan Quayle, meeting Democrat Bentsen in a debate in
Omaha, Neb., between the two vice presidential candidates, said
Dukakis' policy toward Central America was out of step with
mainstream United States voters.
   Asked about his long-term support for the Nicaraguan Contras
despite Dukakis' opposition to the aid, Bentsen said, ``Governor
Dukakis and I have disagreed on the Contra program _ no question
about that.''
   But, he said, he opposed the Reagan administration's Central
American policy because ``they look at the Contra aid program as
the only way to resolve that problem.''
   ``I really think we have to give peace a chance,'' Bentsen said,
``and that's why I have been a strong supporter of the Arias plan,
a plan that won the Nobel prize for President (Oscar) Arias, the
President of Costa Rica.''
   He said the United States had to work with leaders of Central
American countries to ``try to bring about the democratization of
Nicaragua by negotiation, by pressure, by counseling, by diplomatic
pressure _ that we ought to be trying that first.''
   The Reagan administration has paid too little attention to the
rest of Central America, Bentsen said.
   Said Quayle: ``There's no doubt, in a Dukakis administration
that the aid would be cut off to the democratic resistance in
Nicaragua and that is unfortunate.''
   He said Dukakis seemed to think it was all right for the Soviet
Union ``to put in billions of dollars to prop up the communist
Sandinistas, but somehow it's wrong for the United States to give a
few dollars to the democratic resistance.''
   Quayle said he still supported the Monroe Doctrine, set forth in
1823 by President James Monroe, that the United States would oppose
any attempt by European powers to interfere in the Western
Hemisphere.
   And he said 85 percent Americans supported the 1983 U.S.
invasion of Grenada, but that Dukakis had criticized it.
   ``We turned a communist country into a non-communist country,''
Quayle said. ``The governor of Massachusetts is simply out of step
with mainstream America.''
   Bentsen noted that both he and Dukakis speak Spanish and said
they wanted to launch a new alliance for progress for Central
America and Mexico, ``a country with 85 million people sharing a
2,000-mile border with us, with half of those people under the age
of 15, a country that has had its standard of living cut 50 percent
in the last six years.''
   ``We ought to be concerned about that and we ought to be
involved,'' he said. ``Bring in the Europeans _ the Spanish, who
have a real affinity for that area. Bring in the Japanese, who have
a great capital surplus now and looking for places to invest it.''
   Such investment could foster peace, raise the standard of living
and provide the stability needed for democracy to prosper, Bentsen
said.
</TEXT>
