<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Military     10-06 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Military,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 2,200 Soldiers Commit Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly said today that
2,670 soldiers committed suicide, were beaten to death or died from
other unnatural causes since 1980.
   The figures were provided to the assembly in a Defense Ministry
report on deaths in the 650,000 member armed forces.
   The report said 2,254 soldiers committed suicide with the
remaining 416 killed in assaults by their superiors or fellow
soldiers or other unspecified causes. The deaths were in all
branches of the armed forces, and included officers and enlisted
personnel.
   Discipline is notoriously harsh within the South Korean armed
forces. Younger soldiers can be subjected to beatings and other
punishments by older personnel despite an official ban on physical
abuse.
   The report also listed 3,723 other soldiers and officers killed
in accidents since 1980, such as explosions, mishandling of arms,
and motor vehicle and miltitry aircraft accidents.
   Korean males are subject to about two years of military
conscription.
   Dissidents have claimed some opposition supporters serving in
the military killed themselves because they could not stand
surveillance or discriminatory treatment in barracks.
   Some dissident leaders said they would form a special group to
investigate the deaths to determine if there had been any improper
conduct, according to Seoul newspaper reports.
   The Defense Ministry had to submit the report to the National
Assembly as part of legislative scrutiny on conditions within the
military.
   Under the new democratic constitution adopted last year, the
legislature is empowered for the first time in 16 years to inspect
the military and other branches of government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
