<1ST_LINE>u p BC-DebateExcerpts 1stAdd   10-06 1249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Debate Excerpts, 1st Add,1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OMAHA, Neb.: Corn Flakes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Question: Let us assume ... the president is incapacitated ...
and you have to take the reins of power. ... What would be the
first steps that you'd take and why?
   Quayle: First I'd say a prayer for myself and for the country
that I'm about to lead. And then I would assemble his people and
talk. ... And I think this question keeps going back to
qualifications ... You've got to look at experience, and you've got
to look at accomplishments. ...
   Question: Would you acknowledge to the hundreds of injured and
maimed people ... deregulation may have gone too far and the
government should reassert itself in protecting workers' rights?
   Quayle: There is a commitment, and there will always be a
commitment, to the safety of our working men and women. ... In my
judgement, deregulation has worked. We have a deregulated economy
and we have produced through low taxes, not high taxes, through
deregulation, the spirit of entrepreneurship ...
   Bentsen: This administration came in and put in a James Watt and
Anne Gorsuch. Now that's the Bonnie and Clyde, really, of
environmental protection. And that's why it's important that you
have people that truly believe, and trying to represent the working
men and women of America.
   Question: Do you believe it's time to ... target federal money
to the small- and medium-size farmer?
   Bentsen: I feel very strongly that we ought to be doing more for
the American farmer. ... We've seen an administration that has lost
much of our market abroad because they have not had a trade policy.
... We would be pushing very hard to open up those markets, and
stand up for the American farmer.
   Quayle: The governor of Massachusetts ... went to the farmers in
the Midwest, and told them ... to grow Belgium endive. That's what
he and his Harvard buddies think of the American farmer.
   Question: Two guys come through your door ... and say, ``We'd
like you to change,'' without offering a lot of specifics.'' Why
would you accept their deal?
   Bentsen: ... If you let me write $200 billion worth of hot
checks every year, I could give you an illusion of prosperity, too.
... We need an administration that will turn this trade policy
around and open up those markets, stand tough with our trading
partners to help keep the jobs at home and send the products abroad.
   Quayle: ... We are proud of the record of accomplishment and the
opportunities and the hope for millions of Americans ... because of
the policies that we have had for the last eight years and we want
to build on that and change it for even the better.
   Q: Why not use the military to go after the South American drug
cartels and after General Noriega?
   Quayle: We are using our military assets in a prudent way to
deal with interdiction. ... But we've got to get on the demand side
of the ledger. We've got to get to education. ... We need to focus
on ... law enforcement. And here's where we have a major
disagreement with the governor of Massachusetts. ... You cannot be
tough on drugs and weak on crime.
   Bentsen: We'd put one person in charge in the war against drugs,
and we'd commit the resources to get that job done.
   Question: You said you'd say a prayer (if you took over in an
emergency) and you said something about a meeting. What would you
do next?
   Quayle: ... I know what it takes to lead this country forward.
And if that situation arises, yes, I will be prepared, and I'll be
prepared to lead this country if that happens.
   Bentsen: ... You have to look at maturity of judgment, and you
have to look at breadth of experience. You have to see what kind of
leadership roles that person has played in his life before that
crisis struck him. ...
   Question: Surely you must have some plan in mind about what you
would do if it fell to you to become president? ...
   Quayle: I will be prepared to carry out the responsibilities of
the presidency of the United States of America. ... I have far more
experience than many others that sought the office of vice
president of this country. I have as much experience in the
Congress as Jack Kennedy did when he sought the presidency. ...
   Bentsen: Senator, I served with Jack Kennedy. I knew Jack
Kennedy. Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine. Senator, you're no Jack
Kennedy. ... And frankly, I think you're so far apart in the
objectives you choose for your country that I did not think the
comparison was well taken.
   Q: Does the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket have any realistic plan for
getting the American hostages being held in the Middle East
released in any due time?
   Bentsen: ... The one thing we ought to have, know by now is that
you can't go out and make secret deals with the Ayatollah. You
can't trade arms for hostages. ...
   Quayle: There's no doubt about it that arms for hostages is
wrong, and it will never be repeated. We learn by our mistakes. But
there have been a number of successes in foreign policy in this
administration. ...
   Question: How do you explain ... how you can be a social
conservative ... and still run with Michael Dukakis on the national
ticket?
   Bentsen: Michael Dukakis wasn't looking for clone. I think it's
part of the strength and the character of this man that he reaches
out and that he wants someone that will speak up, and that I'll do.
   Question: Could you describe ... what experience you may have
had and how it shaped your political philosophy?
   Quayle: ... It's the advice that my maternal grandmother Martha
Pulliam, who's 97 years old ... she says ``You can do anything you
want to if you just set your mind to it an go to work.'' Now the
Dukakis supporters sneer at that, because it's common sense. ...
   Bentsen: ... To have spent part of my life seeing some of the
struggles that have taken place in one of the lowest per capita
incomes in the United States, and that's one of the reasons I've
worked so hard to try to assist on education. ...
   Closing Remarks:
   Quayle: ... The road of George Bush is the road to the future
and it comes down to this: an America second to none, with visions
of greatness, economic expansion, tough laws, tough judges, strong
values, respect for the flag and our institutions. George Bush will
lead us to the 21st century, a century that will be of hope and
peace. Ronald Reagan and George Bush saved America from decline. We
changed America. ... George Bush has the experience, and with me,
the future -- a future committed to our family, a future committed
to the freedom.
   Bentsen: ... Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen offer you
experienced, tempered, capable leadership to meet those challenges
of the future. ... America can't just coast into the future,
clinging to the past. This race is too close. The competition is
too tough. And the stakes are too high. ... Mike Dukakis says the
best of America is yet to come. ... It's going to take leadership
and it's going to take courage, and the commitment and a
contribution by all of us to do that.
</TEXT>
