<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpeedBumps     10-06 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speed Bumps,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Fed Up With Speeders Arrested for Building Speed Bumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he was fed up with cars
speeding out of a high-school parking lot has been arrested for
building two speed bumps at an entrance.
   ``It was the most unique response I've seen to a problem,''
Fairfax County police Lt. Justin B. Murphy said Wednesday.
``However, it's illegal.''
   Tom Alsop, 34, was arrested Tuesday night and charged with
destruction of public property. He is to appear in court Oct. 28,
and faces 12 months in jail and a $1,000 fine if convicted.
   ``I didn't pursue the right channels. I was basically spinning
my wheels,'' Alsop said. ``In hindsight, maybe it was a stupid
thing to do. We don't want anything big, we just want a little
help.''
   Alsop, who runs a carpet cleaning business near W.T. Woodson
High School, said he sees students speed out of the lot every day.
   They also perform ``burnouts'' by pouring oil on the road and
spinning their tires until smoke is generated, he said.
   ``At 2 o'clock every day, you get a burnout session,'' he said.
   Alsop installed a chain-link fence on his property last year
after a station wagon landed wheels-up in his yard.
   Alsop said he has complained about the students' driving to
school officials four times during the last three years to no
avail. So he decided to take action himself.
   The 5-foot-long-by-2-inch-high bumps were easy to build, Alsop
said.
   ``Take hot asphalt, pour it on the ground and whack it with a
shovel,'' he said.
   Alsop removed the bumps after the police arrived.
   ``These were just little bumps,'' Alsop said. ``I didn't think I
was doing any harm.''
   Woodson Principal Charles E. Billak said a staff member has been
assigned to monitor the problem. Three or four students lost their
privilege of driving to school last year after being caught doing
burnouts, Billak said.
   ``Automobiles are a problem,'' he said. ``We could do without
them.''
</TEXT>
