<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VeepDebate-Color     10-06 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veep Debate-Color,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rowdy Crowd, Testy Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crowd was rowdy. Throughout the vice
presidential debate, the candidates were greeted with derisive
laughter and raucous cheers from alternating sides of an auditorium
calculatedly divided evenly between Republicans and Democrats, down
to the very last partisan.
   Throughout it all Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle doggedly stuck to
their podiums, exchanging occasional glares.
   ``It sure wasn't hermetically sealed,'' laughed Ed Touhy, who
produced the debate program for a bipartisan commission. ``For a
while, I was afraid they were going to rush the stage.''
   Both candidates and workers had spent the week in intense
preparation over the smallest details, and the training was
apparent from the time the two candidates strode purposefully on
stage in matching dark suits and similar striped ties.
   Quayle's sole concession to informality was a foot propped
casually on his podium, while Bentsen stubbornly gripped a pen in
his right hand, occasionally stabbing the air to underscore a point.
   The debate started slowly, but tension between the candidates
grew, capped when Bentsen glared at Quayle and said: ``Senator, you
are no Jack Kennedy.''
   The two candidates shook hands at the beginning and end, but
there was little warmth in between, and the crowd paid scant
attention to repeated pleas from moderator Judy Woodruff, of the
``MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' television program, to react less
noisily.
   The candidates generally stared stonily into space during the
demonstrations, picking up where they left off after it subsided.
   ``I'm wondering if the rowdiness of the crowd doesn't dictate
that future debates will be held in television studios rather than
a public auditorium,'' Fouhy said later. ``It was a pretty rowdy
crowd.''
   The candidates occasionally had some tensions with their
questioners also.
   Pressed repeatedly to give his qualifications for president,
Quayle at one point snapped ``I think this is the fourth time I've
had this question.''
   No, he was told, just the third.
   Bentsen, pressed to explain a fund-raising tactic, stiffened a
bit before saying ``I don't find it embarrassing at all.''
   Organizers made no apologies for the stiffness of the
arrangements, telling reporters it was their job to produce good
television. And that's precisely what came out _ a television
program staged as artfully as a sitcom.
   ``This is a television program, and we've got some of the best
production people in the world doing it,'' Fouhy said. ``You direct
a television program so people watching at home have a good idea
what's happening.''
   The League of Women Voters originally was to sponsor the second
presidential debate, next week in Los Angeles, but pulled out
charging the candidates exercised too much control over the format
and turned the event into a ``charade.''
   That sort of criticism, insisted Fouhy, was ``a lot of
nonsense.''
   ``I'm delighted that it went well,'' Fouhy said. ``There was
real substance. This was not a battle of the network sound bites.''
   The show will go on. Saws and hammers came out within minutes of
the debate's close, dismantling a stage that had been shipped to
Omaha from Winston-Salem, N.C., and the first debate between
Michael Dukakis and George Bush.
   Next stop is Los Angeles and the final presidential debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
