<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Medflies 1stLd-Writethru a0727 10-06 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medflies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Weather Postpones Medfly Spraying After Beverly Hills Takes Cover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with spraying postponed;
picks up 4th graf, `The target ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beverly Hills residents threw tarpaulins over
their Porsches and Ferraris and others stayed indoors Wednesday as
the state prepared a sticky aerial bombardment of Mediterranean
fruit fly pesticide.
   But low clouds late Wednesday grounded three helicopters that
were set to spray Malathion over a 35-square-mile swath of homes
and businesses west of downtown, including sections of Beverly
Hills, to stop a burgeoning infestation of the crop-destroying pest.
   The spraying was rescheduled for Thursday night, said William
Edwards, chief deputy to Los Angeles County's agricultural
commissioner.
   The target area is densely packed with homes and businesses.
Forty Medflies have been found in yards since Sept. 26, indicating
a serious infestation that, if allowed to spread, could threaten
crops worth $8 billion a year statewide, authorities said.
   While the most exclusive residential sections of Beverly Hills,
including shaded streets dotted with movie stars' mansions, were
not included in the spraying area, many of the community's
expensive shops and opulent apartment buildings fell into the
target zone, along with other sections of Los Angeles and other
municipalities with homes ranging from modest bungalows to estates.
   The nearest commercial crops are dozens of miles away from the
spray area, but the pest can spread rapidly. Medflies lay their
eggs under the skin of a wide variety of fruits and vegetables,
hatching maggots that destroy the crop.
   The last serious infestation, in 1980 and 1981, cost California
farmers an estimated $100 million. ``We need to get this done as
quickly as possible,'' Edwards said of the spraying.
   State experts say the spraying could cause inconvenience, but no
health hazard, as the Malathion in the small concentrations used is
harmless to warm-blooded animals.
   However, the pesticide is mixed with a sweet, sticky corn syrup
bait that can damage car paint.
   Ron Ferraro, who runs Scandinavian Auto Body, scrambled to find
tarpaulins or garage space for a fleet of Alpha Romeos in Beverly
Hills. ``You're looking at about $7,500 in refinishing that would
have to be done,'' Ferraro said.
   Agricultural Commissioner Leon Spaugy said the fight to save the
state's farm industry knows no economic boundaries. ``We're
encouraging people to cover up their Rolls Royces just like they
would cover up their Pintos,'' he said.
   Among the cities and the sections of Los Angeles in the area are
Culver City, Palms, Baldwin Hills and West Hollywood.
   Members of the California Conservation Corps started passing out
flyers notifying residents of the spraying Monday, and there have
been news reports all week, but some objected they hadn't been
warned in time.
   West Hollywood Mayor Helen Albert, in a letter to state
agriculture officials, complained the city hadn't been given enough
time to warn its residents or assess possible health hazards.
   Responded Edwards: ``They should be mad at the people who caused
this (infestation), and that's the people who brought the
(contaminated) fruit in. We're trying to protect the state's
biggest industry, and that's agriculture. If we don't do this,
farmers are going to have to use a lot more pesticide and fruit is
going to cost more.''
   The Medfly is native to Central America, Hawaii and other
tropical areas. Most California infestations are believed to start
with flies unwittingly brought home by tourists in illegally
transported fruit, or in fruit mailed from Hawaii.
   The anti-Medfly strategy is two-fold. First, the population is
knocked down with the Malathion bait, which remains active about a
week. Then, millions of specially bred sterile flies are released
so the surviving wild flies mate harmlessly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
