<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-06 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RHINELANDER, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rhinelander residents apparently are a
little nuts about acorns.
   When state forestry officials put out a call for acorns, little
did they know it would bring an avalanche of nuts brought in by
children, families and retired folks.
   The state Department of Natural Resources quit buying the red
oak acorns at $20 bushel after people brought to the Rhinelander
ranger station more than twice as many as originally needed for the
state's three nurseries.
   ``I was shocked. I don't think anybody in their wildest dreams
expected this,'' Timothy Mulhern, a forester in Rhinelander who set
up the acorn collection station, said Wednesday.
   He said the collection drive began last month, and people
brought 1,182 bushels of acorns to the station in just three days.
   As the acorns began to roll in, officials decided to increase
the number of acorns they would plant to 700 bushels, but people
from as far away as Michigan continued to haul their acorns to
Rhinelander, in north-central Wisconsin.
   Eventually, the acorns filled four garage stalls waist-high,
Mulhern said. Some people brought their children to see the nuts,
he said.
   ``It's like a giant squirrel stored all the acorns in the world
right here for winter,'' one DNR official said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who has
spoken strongly against high-fat, high cholesterol diets of
Americans, didn't bat an eye as he gobbled down a breakfast of
scrambled eggs, sausage and coffee.
   Koop smiled and laughed good-naturedly as his fellow diners _
most of whom were doctors or health officials _ teased him about
the All-American meal.
   But when a reporter later asked about the breakfast, Koop's
familiar stern demeanor reappeared.
   ``When you're my age and in my situation _ your blood
cholesterol and triglyceride levels are normal _ you can indulge
now and then,'' Koop said following the breakfast in his honor at
the University of Minnesota-Duluth.
   People with hyperlipemia _ too much fat in the blood _ have
certain restrictions on their diet, he said.
   ``Don't make the mistake of thinking that what's good for a
person with hyperlipemia is good for the nation,'' Koop said.
</TEXT>
