<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Emperor     10-06 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emperor,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Hirohito Discharges More Blood, Fever Remains High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors expressed fears that transfusions may be
causing emperor Hirohito's fever and pulse rate to rise, but gave
him more blood this morning as his internal bleeding continued.
   Emperor Hirohito received 0.4 pints of blood in a transfusion
this morning after discharging a small amount of blood, according
to palace officials.
   It was the 14th-straight day transfusions have been given to the
87-year-old emperor, who has been bedridden since internal
hemorrhaging caused him to vomit blood on Sept. 19.
   Kenji Maeda, head of the general affairs department of the
Imperial Household Agency, told reporters the emperor's temperature
was 100.58 degrees as of 9:00 a.m. Wednesday morning his fever was
98.96 degrees.
   ``We cannot rule out the possibility that the emperor's fever
was caused by internal inflammation in the upper digestive tract,
or by (the series of) blood transfusions, or both'' Maeda quoted
Akira Takagi, the emperor's chief physician, as saying.
   Hirohito has so far received a total of 11.98 pints in
transfusions, well above the normal amount of blood circulating in
his body, according to news reports.
   Doctors halted a blood transfusion being given to the emperor
Wednesday afternoon before it was complete because of concern over
his high temperature and rising pulse rate.
   Hirohito's temperature and pulse rate rose sharply Wednesday as
doctors administered the transfusion in an attempt to ``help
overcome anemia and improve his overall physical condition,'' Maeda
said.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch has continued to discharge
small amounts of blood intermittently since the onset of the crisis.
   He has been unable to take solid food except for two small
fragments of ice and a few spoonfuls of porridge since falling
sick. He is being fed intravenously.
   News reports have said Hirohito has cancer, but palace officials
have refused to confirm or deny them and have urged the media to
refrain from making such speculation.
</TEXT>
