<HEAD>Newspaper VP, General Manager Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Rothenburg resigned as vice president and
general manager of The Washington Times, the newspaper reported in
today's editions.
   Rothenburg, 46, whose title will be retired, directed the
newspaper's advertising sales and circulation programs for more
than five years.
   The report said he resigned to explore other opportunities that
he did not disclose.
   H. William Paul Jr., general manager of Insight magazine, will
become general manager of The Washington Times Corp., which
publishes both the newspaper and the magazine.
   Ronald S. Godwin, senior vice president of The Washington Times
Corp., praised Rothenburg's contribution during his five years as
head of the paper's business affairs.
   ``Paul provided a strong leadership on which the corporation
will be able to build in the future,'' he said.
   Rothenburg was president of his own management consultant firm
before joining the newspaper. Before that he was an executive with
the Detroit News.
   Paul joined the newspaper in 1985 after serving as vice
president of Liberty University.
</TEXT>
