<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Paves Way for Approval of International Copyright Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 89-0 approval of legislation
paving the way for the United States to join 76 nations in an
agreement that grants global copyrights to literary and artistic
works.
   The bill would change U.S. copyright law, sets up Senate consent
to ratification of the treaty, signed in Berne, Switzerland, on
Sept. 9, 1886. Ratification will come on a separate vote.
   ``Adherence to the convention will greatly benefit the United
States,'' Sen. Pat Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee's subcommittee on patents, copyrights and trademarks,
said after Wednesday's vote. ``It will provide the guidelines which
govern the copyright regulations between nations.''
   The Berne Convention prohibits member nations from
discriminating against copyrighted works of other member nations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Environment Group Sues Government to Halt CFC Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group says it is suing the
Environmental Protection Agency to force the government to order a
complete end to the use of chemicals that destroy the earth's
protective ozone layer.
   The suit by the Natural Resources Defense Council challenges the
adequacy of the partial cutbacks that EPA ordered for five major
chlorofluorocarbon compounds, or CFC's, on Aug. 1.
   Those regulations paralleled provisions of the 1987 treaty by
major producing nations pledging themselves to a 50 percent
reduction in CFC output by 1998.
   ``The United States is the single largest contributor to
world-wide emissions of ozone-depleting chemicals,'' responsible
for about 30 percent of global use, David Doniger, an attorney for
the council, said Wednesday. ``We have a responsibility to clean up
our own house.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Germ Mail Ban Draws Opposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is facing strong
opposition to a proposal to ban the mailing of germs and dangerous
toxins.
   Assistant Postmaster General Frank R. Heselton said Wednesday
that final action on the ban has been postponed until the issue can
be more fully studied.
   Heselton told a House Post Office and Civil Service subcommittee
the Postal Service has contacted the federal Centers for Disease
Control and the Department of Transportation for assistance in
developing safety standards for hazardous mail.
   Heselton said opposition has come from doctors, laboratories,
colleges and universities, medical centers, pathologists and
biologists and state and federal health groups, among others.
