<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 11thLd-Writethru   10-06 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 11th Ld - Writethru,a0493,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pinochet Loses Referendum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with government conceding,
CORRECTS ministry percentage total for yes votes to 44.3, sted 48.3
percent; picks up 7th graf pvs: There were...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SCL2,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet lost
a referendum that would have allowed him to stay in power until
1997, government and opposition returns showed Thursday.
   The defeat sets the stage for open elections next year.
   In a speech broadcast nationwide on television and radio,
Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez, formally conceded Pinochet's
defeat at 2:40 a.m. (1:40 a.m. EDT).
   ``We abide by the results, which the country already knows,''
Fernandez said.
   Earlier, Air Force Commander General Fernando Matthei, a member
of the law-making military junta, said: ``It seem to me that the
`no' (vote) has won.''
   ``We are calm. We are going to analyze the situation,'' Matthei
added as he entered the downtown government palace at 1 a.m. for an
emergency meeting with Pinochet, the four-man junta and the
15-member Cabinet.
   Shortly after Matthei's statement, the Interior Ministry at 2:10
a.m. announced for the first time substantial voting returns that
showed the vote against Pinochet's continued rule prevailing. It
earlier had said Pinochet was winning.
   With 15,969 of the country's 22,248 voting tables reporting, the
ministry counted 2,754,805 votes, or 53.3 percent, against
Pinochet, and 2,290,972 votes, or 44.3 percent, supporting the
president.
   There were also 53,292 blank votes and 68,108 votes voided for
being wrongly marked.
   An earlier opposition tally gave the ``no'' vote an even wider
margin with Pinochet losing, 57.8 percent to 39.9 percent.
   Patricio Aylwin, president of the Christian Democratic Party and
spokesman for the coalition, declared, ``It's clear that the
majority of Chileans have voted no.''
   On Wednesday in balloting that was peaceful and heavily
attended, Chileans voted on a proposal by Pinochet and other
military commanders that he remain president until 1997. The
right-wing, 72-year-old army chief seized power in a bloody coup in
1973 that ousted the 3-year-old elected government of President
Salvador Allende, a Marxist who died during the takeover.
   If he had won, Pinochet would have assumed a new 8-year term in
March. By losing, an open presidential election is to be held late
next year and the winner would assume power in March 1990, with
Pinochet remaining in power until then.
   Earlier, military patrols in armored personnel carriers and
trucks with mounted machine guns were seen circulating in
working-class neighborhoods and slums _ where anti-Pinochet
sentiment traditionally runs high _ that ring the capital. A few
hundred people danced in the streets of La Victoria slum in
southern Santiago, waving banners and celebrating an anticipated
``no'' victory.
   ``We all voted no, because we are repressed,'' said one
participant, 50-year-old construction worker Jose Garrido.
   Jorge Zincke, military commander for the Santiago area, reported
scattered incidents after the voting, which he said were being
controlled by police. He said anti-government demonstrators erected
barricades in the streets of San Bernardo, south of the capital,
and Puente Alto, to the southeast.
   He said six people were arrested for carrying arms and a public
bus was burned and its driver beaten.
   Santiago's streets were mainly empty as most Chileans heeded
opposition calls to stay at home.
   Pinochet said earlier in an interview broadcast by Radio
Cooperativa of Santiago, ``So far everything is calm, but I've got
some information that leaves me thinking. There are some people who
have seen individuals wearing ski-masks.'' He gave no details.
   Leftist urban guerrillas commonly employ ski masks, but both of
Chile's guerrilla groups have publicly announced a truce until
after the voting day.
   A huge turnout among the 7.4 million registered voters slowed
balloting at many polling places and could delay definitive
tallies, authorities said. Voting tables started closing at 5 p.m.
and the counting began.
   Foreign observers said the plebiscite appeared to be open and
honestly conducted.
   Former President Oswaldo Hurtado of Ecuador, an observer, said:
``What I have seen is Chileans being able to cast their votes
freely and in private.''
   Official returns from the National Election Service are not
expected until Friday.
   Voting is mandatory and those who don't vote can be fined up to
22,000 pesos, or about $80.
   In Santiago, the capital city where more than one-third of the
nation's 12 million people live, some voters showed up an hour
before polls began opening at 8 a.m. Lines more than a mile long
had formed by midmorning, under bright sunlight in the Southern
Hemisphere spring.
   Pinochet, smiling and wearing a beige civilian suit, voted at a
downtown Santiago station.
</TEXT>
