<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Narcopriest     10-06 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Narcopriest,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Facing 20 Years For Drug Trafficking Protests Innocence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who was caught
with 46 pounds of cocaine says he is innocent of drug trafficking
and insists he will remain a priest for the rest of his life.
   Father Jose Luis Gil Fernandez, who turned 58 on Wednesday, said
he felt ``tranquil'' after a Venezuelan public prosecutor requested
a 20 year sentence this week for Gil for trafficking in drugs.
   The prosecutor, Pablo Gonzalez, also asked for 15 years in jail
for Juan Rojano Martinez, a former priest whom Gil implicated as
the man who forced him to deal in drugs.
   Gonzalez requested a stiffer sentence for Gil because he
allegedly used his status as a minister of God to facilitate the
drug dealing.
   ``I am totally innocent. I am going to wait all this out and I
will continue being a priest for the rest of my life,'' Gil said
prior to his second hearing before Judge Aura Chaparro of the 40th
First Circuit Penal Tribunal in Caracas.
   The silver-haired priest clutched a red-bound Bible in his hand
and had a small silver cross pinned to his navy blue knit vest.
   Gil was arrested last April by Venezuelan intelligence police in
Simon Bolivar International Airport outside Caracas as he tried to
smuggle the cocaine onto a plane bound for Madrid.
   Rojano, who left the priesthood 27 years ago, and his wife
Graciela were arrested in their Caracas residence hours after Gil.
   Police found 180 grams of cocaine and cash in the house,
Rojano's lawyer, Hugo Albarran, said prior to the hearing.
   Gil is Spanish-born but was the parish priest of San Mateo, 36
miles west of Caracas, for 30 years. According to Gil's lawyer,
Edoardo Petricone Chiarilli, he has given up the parish post since
his arrest.
   Gil is apparently the first priest ever to be tried for drug
trafficking.
   Petricone said Gil is pleading innocent because he was coerced
into carrying drugs by Rojano. Albarran said Rojano is pleading
innocent because he was falsely accused by Gil.
   According to Petricone, Gil inadvertently got involved in
trafficking in 1984 when he carried a package of unknown content to
Spain as a favor to Rojano.
   Rojano and Gil have known each other for 20 years, according to
Rojano's lawyer Hugo Albarran.
   Upon Gil's return, Rojano notified him the package contained
cocaine and threatened to ``expose (Gil) to public shame'' if he
refused to carry more drugs, Petricone said.
   He said the only other times the priest carried cocaine to Spain
were in January 1988 and again last April, when he was arrested.
   Judge Chaparro, who is stepping in for vacationing Judge
Francisco Caracciolo Lamus, indicated that a decision on Gil and
Rojano will not be made until November at the earliest.
   Drug trafficking carries a sentence of up to 30 years in
Venezuela.
</TEXT>
