<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile-Voters 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Voters, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0441,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Voted Early To Avoid Long Lines And Possible Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs and edits to reflect referendum result;
picks up 9th graf, `About 7.4 ...'
^With PM-Chile, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chileans grew frustrated with long lines
that snaked outside polling stations, but many believed the
national referendum on whether Gen. Augusto Pinochet should
continue as president would be fair and accurate.
   The Interior Ministry conceded early today that Pinochet had
lost the referendum. Voters had been asked to decide whether
Pinochet, who seized power in a 1973 military coup, should continue
to rule this South American nation until 1997.
   Open elections for a new president are to be held next year.
   During Wednesday's balloting, many Chileans seemed confident
that their vote would count.
   ``I'll respect the results even if Pinochet wins,'' said Jose
Casanova, a 63-year-old retired farmer, standing outside a polling
station in a working-class northern suburb. ``I think Pinochet will
respect the results even if he loses.''
   ``Anyone who wants to can vote `no.' That doesn't happen in Cuba
and a lot of other countries,'' said Geronima Lopez Rodrigo, 54,
who was waiting her turn in the affluent Providencia neighborhood
of Santiago. ``We have a beautiful democracy, with order and
discipline.''
   About 7.4 million people were registered to vote. Voting is
mandatory, and turnout was heavy across this narrow country wedged
between the snow-capped Andes mountains and the Pacific.
   Anyone who did not vote soon after polls opened at 8 a.m. risked
a long wait under a glaring spring sun.
   Men removed their sport coats and sweaters, and women, standing
in separate lines, fanned themselves or held kerchiefs over their
heads. Government television said two elderly voters, in the cities
of La Serena and Coyhaique, suffered heart attacks and died just
before or after voting.
   But few people grumbled, and even fewer went home without voting.
   ``I took three buses to get here,'' said Carmen Reyes, at a
southern Santiago polling place.
   Housewife Sonia Azoca in the northern neighborhood of Conchali
said: ``I've been here half an hour. I'll probably be here an hour
more. However long it takes, I'll be here.''
   National police in white suspenders, holsters and carrying
batons were posted at each of the 1,000 polling stations
nationwide. Otherwise, the military was barely visible in the
capital's streets, sidewalks and parks, which were practically
deserted.
   After voting, most people took the advice of the government, the
opposition and the Roman Catholic Church. They went home.
   Not one of more than a dozen voters interviewed doubted the vote
count would be fast and accurate.
   ``Fraud is impossible,'' said Fabiola Escuer, 24. ``Both sides
are counting the vote and there are observers from many countries.''
   Election laws provide for pollwatchers from both pro-government
and opposition parties. An estimated 500 foreign observers were on
hand in the capital and provincial cities.
</TEXT>
