<2ND_LINE>PM-People-James Brown,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Tests Show Brown Had PCP In Blood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests indicate that soul singer James Brown
had the hallucinogenic drug PCP in his system when he was arrested
following a two-state car chase, a prosecutor said.
   Brown, 55, was charged with driving under the influence Sept. 24
after the singer led police on a chase that started and ended in
Augusta, Ga.
   Brown also was charged in South Carolina with two assault counts
and failing to stop for police.
   A chemical analysis of Brown's blood revealed the presence of
PCP, Circuit Solicitor Robert J. Harte said Wednesday.
   Brown in the past has maintained he has never used the drug, but
his attorney said the entertainer began treatment in Athens, Ga.,
this week for ``substance abuse.''
   Brown's attorney Albert `Buddy'' Dallas refused to identify the
drug, and referred to Brown's problem as related to
``stress-control.''
   Brown was placed on probation this summer after pleading no
contest to a PCP possession charge and pleading guilty to resisting
arrest and carrying a pistol.
   But Brown said he has never used the hallucinogenic drug and
said the PCP was planted on him.
</TEXT>
