<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-USGirl     10-06 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-US Girl,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Girl Gets Official Welcome in Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old girl from Michigan
arrived in this nation to an official government welcome as guest
of military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, her pen pal in recent
months.
   Sarah York and her mother, Pauline, of Negaunee, Mich., arrived
at Torrijos International Airport near Panama City late Wednesday
on a commercial flight from Miami.
   They will stay until Tuesday, visiting an agricultural fair and
meeting Noriega and other Panamanian officials. The meeting with
Noriega is set for Thursday.
   Noriega, Panama's de facto ruler, has been indicted in the
United States on drug trafficking charges. He has withstood U.S.
economic sanctions against Panama aimed at forcing him to resign.
   ``The girl has risen above the behavior of the adults that
actually direct U.S. politics,'' said Defense Forces spokesman Maj.
Edgardo Lopez Grimaldo.
   Lopez Grimaldo said the girl first wrote Noriega on March 3
after she saw him interviewed on television. She asked him to
recommend books on Central American politics and history.
   In other letters, Sarah told the general she received good
grades in school and liked to read and play piano.
</TEXT>
