<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Suriname     10-06 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suriname,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suriname Asks Dutch and French Help To End Destablization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suriname's new president has asked France
and the Netherlands to help his nation halt recruitment of
mercenaries and arms shipments that he says are fortifying
anti-government rebels.
   President Ramsewak Shankar, whose January inauguration ended
seven years of military rule, told the 43rd U.N. General Assembly
in New York on Wednesday that Suriname ``has inherited serious
social and economic problems that could become a threat to our
national unity and political stability if not urgently addressed.''
   He said one problem involves about 10,000 refugees in eastern
Suriname who fled a guerrilla war by troops loyal to former private
Ronnie Brunswijk. He is a former bodyguard to Desi Bouterse, who
Shankar replaced in January after seven years of leftist military
rule.
   ``My government is making every effort to have dialogue to end
the insurgency, which has often resulted in violent acts off
terrorism,'' Shankar said Wednesday.
   Suriname, a small nation of 370,000 people north of Brazil, has
never directly accused the Netherlands or France of aiding the
insurrection.
   But Shankar said Wednesday that Suriname ``is faced with the
problem that the insurgents are aided and abetted by external
forces, whose chief aim is the continuation of violence through the
provision of arms and the recruitment and financing of
mercenaries.''
   He said his government is seeking help from France and the
Netherlands in stopping arms deliveries and recruitment of foreign
mercenaries.
   Brunswijk's forces have wide support among the 350,000-member
Surinamese expatriot community in the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
