<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TheIfQuestion     10-06 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-The If Question,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen, Quayle Both Say They'd Gather Advisers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle says he could take over as president if a tragedy made that
necessary, telling a debate audience the first thing he would do if
that happened is pray for himself and the country.
   The question dogged the 41-year-old senator from Indiana
throughout his debate Wednesday night with Democratic vice
presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen, who from the beginning
maintained the key issue was who was best qualified to be president
_ not No. 2.
   Reporters putting the questions to the two candidates appeared
to agree, returning to it three times after moderator Judy Woodruff
opened the debate with a comment that, based on the experiences
since World War II, there is a 50-50 chance that Quayle or Bentsen
could be thrust into the Oval Office on a moment's notice.
   ``First, I'd say a prayer for myself and for the country that
I'm about to lead,'' Quayle said. ``And then I would assemble his
people and talk.''
   Bentsen, a 67-year-old senator from Texas, answered in more
general terms, saying the central issue was ``maturity of
judgment'' and ``breadth of experience.''
   He started to get specific at one point, saying, ``What has to
be done in a situation like that is to call in the joint ...'' but
was interrupted by audience reaction and never finished. The
reference may have been to the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   The audience reaction was in response to Bentsen's statement to
Quayle: ``Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.'' Quayle had said he has
as much experience in Congress as Kennedy did when he sought and
won the presidency in 1960.
   Quayle said he is prepared to carry out the duties of the
presidency ``not only because of my service in the Congress but
because of my ability to communicate and to lead.''
   ``It's not just age, it's accomplishments, it's experience,'' he
said, citing his authorship with Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
of the Job Training Partnership Act for training unskilled and
workers and retraining displaced ones. ``I have far more experience
than many others that sought the office of vice president.''
   Expanding on what his first actions would be in reaction to the
fourth occasion in the debate when the question was posed, Quayle
said he would call in members of the Cabinet and the president's
White House advisers and ``talk to them and work with them.''
   ``I'll know them on a first-hand basis because I'm going to be
coordinating the drug effort, because as vice president, I'll sit
in on the National Security Council, because Vice President George
Bush is going to recreate the Space Council and I'll be in charge
of that,'' he said. ``I will have day-to-day activities with all
the people in government.''
   Bentsen didn't escape unscathed on the same issue.
   He was queried about the fairness of his and Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis' repeated campaign remarks
questioning Quayle's qualifications when Bentsen had unsuccessfully
sought the presidency in 1976 with less experience than Quayle has
now.
   ``I must say I didn't do a very good job of running for the
presidency,'' Bentsen said. ``But what we're looking at today is
trying to judge, once again, the breadth of experience and maturity
of someone taking on this kind of task.''
</TEXT>
