<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-06 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices fell sharply on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 133.30 yen, down 0.18 yen from Wednesday's
close of 133.48 yen. Opening at 133.37 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 133.30-133.53 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 95.53-point
loser the previous day, lost another 233.15 points, or 0.85
percent, to close at 27,172.34 points.
   ``Share prices fell mainly because the market will have a
three-day holiday this weekend, in addition to investors'
cautiousness before the release of the U.S. unemployment figures,''
said Manji Ueda with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   The U.S. monthly unemployment rate for September is due to be
released Friday in Washington.
   The market's fall in recent sessions has been contradicting
almost ideal economic factors surrounding the Tokyo market, Ueda
said, suggesting that the condition of Japan's ailing emperor has
been a market-affecting factor.
   In foreign exchange, trading was quiet before the U.S.
unemployment report, said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa with the Daiwa Bank.
   ``The dollar-yen rate was moving very little as investors traded
the currencies only for speculative reasons and position
adjustment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
