<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Medflies Bjt   10-06 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medflies, Bjt,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fog Grounds Medfly Spraying In Swank Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beverly Hills took cover, but fog grounded
the state's aerial insecticide attack on the Mediterranean fruit
fly in the ritzy neighborhood and other areas where the
crop-destroying pest has invaded.
   The postponement gave about 100,000 residents another day to
protect their Porsches, Rolls Royces and expensive outdoor statuary
against thousands of gallons of sticky mixture containing Malathion.
   The mission was rescheduled for 7 tonight.
   Some residents still doubted whether there has been sufficient
notice, but one Mercedes Benz dealer evacuated his high-priced
rolling stock into an underground parking garage and other car
dealers looked for tarps.
   ``I'm surprised with the way they notified us,'' said resident
Kevin Riley. ``The way they notified us has been so low-key that I
question whether there has been adequate notification.''
   Three helicopters scheduled to spray over a 35-square-mile area
of homes and businesses west of downtown late Wednesday stayed at
Santa Monica Airport after the fog rolled in from the ocean,
officials said.
   ``It was just too dangerous to try it,'' said Robert Donley at
the state's Medfly Hotline. ``They want to try it earlier. The
earlier they spray the better the chances they avoid the fog.''
   The spraying was ordered because 40 Medflies were found in yards
since Sept. 26, signaling a serious infestation that, if allowed to
spread, could threaten California's $8 billion in crops.
   The Medfly, a native to Central America, Hawaii and other
tropical areas, is believed to be brought to California unwittingly
by tourists or on illegally transported fruit mailed from Hawaii.
   If the all-night, eight-hour spraying assault wipes out enough
Medflies, officials will release sterile flies to breed with the
surviving insects to render them sterile, Donley said.
   Most of the exclusive residential sections of Beverly Hills,
including the mansions of Hollywood's rich and famous, are spared
of the spraying, but posh Rodeo Drive shops and many car
dealerships are in the target area.
   The pesticide poses no health risks, officials say, but the
sticky corn syrup bait mixed with the Malathion could mess up a
car's paint job. Museums in the area covered their outdoor statues.
   Ron Ferraro, who runs Scandinavian Auto Body in Beverly Hills,
scrambled to find tarpaulins or garage space Wednesday for a fleet
of Alfa Romeos.
   ``You're looking at about $7,500 in refinishing that would have
to be done,'' Ferraro said.
   But Agricultural Commissioner Leon Spaugy said the fight to save
the state's farm industry knows no economic boundaries.
   ``We're encouraging people to cover up their Rolls Royces just
like they would cover up their Pintos,'' he said.
   Along with parts of Beverly Hills, officials are spraying the
Los Angeles sections of Culver City, Palms, Baldwin Hills and West
Hollywood.
   These communities all are dozens of miles from the nearest
commercial crops, but the pest can spread rapidly. It lays its eggs
under the skin of a wide variety of fruits and vegetables, hatching
maggots that destroy the crop.
   The last serious infestation, in 1980 and 1981, cost California
farmers an estimated $100 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
