<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DebateSpin 1stLd-Writethru a0514 10-06 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate Spin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0527; fixes byline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Protocol Takes a Powder as Senators Beat Up on Colleagues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 14th graf, bgng: ``That is xxx to CORRECT Simpson's
party affiliation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is in Washington, but a big chunk of
the Senate assembled in Omaha as Dan Quayle and Lloyd Bentsen's
colleagues came to give reporters instant analyses of their vice
presidential debate. They said of the rivals things a senator
normally never says about a senator.
   Things like: ``cheap shot,'' ``knockout blow,'' ``vicious'' and
``unbecoming.'' One senator said he was ``embarrassed'' for another.
   Protocol took a powder. It's not the way they talk back in the
Capitol.
   More than two dozen lawmakers from both parties were flown in
for the showdown on ``Spin Alley,'' the area of the press hall
where campaign officials circulated to share with reporters their
views of the debates in hopes of influencing what got said on the
air or put in print.
   Each team had rented a charter to jet their players from
Washington into Omaha for the night and they sent in so many that
the spinners nearly crushed the press trying to write down their
reactions.
   Most of them flowed in two streams, one from each party, that
quickly filled the hall minutes after the contest ended. Bush's
campaign chairman, James A. Baker III, rated a briefing all his own
outside the debate hall.
   Before the debate, the two campaigns briefed the surrogates.
Afterward, verdicts in hand, the responses were predictable, and
they didn't always fit the decorum they practice in the Capitol.
   For the Democrats, the big topic was Bentsen's assertion to
Quayle that he was ``no Jack Kennedy.''
   ``I thought that was the knockout blow of the evening,'' said
Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
   ``I think he (Quayle) invited it, and it was a devastating
reply. When someone seeks to compare himself with someone, I think
it is very appropriate to say it like it is,'' said Sen. Bennett
Johnston, D-La.
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., who had sought the presidency and was
a top choice for the vice presidency slot, said he was
``embarrassed'' for Quayle.
   ``I thought that he would do well. I thought this was the chance
to rehabilitate himself. All he had to do was to come in and look
halfway decent and avoid serious mistakes,'' he said.
   The Republicans called the Kennedy exchange a ``cheap shot'' and
insisted their Senate colleague put to rest any doubts that he was
qualified to be president.
   ``That is going to get sorted out in this whole game as a
vicious little spot,'' Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo. ``I think it was a
cheap shot. That was very unbecoming of Lloyd Bentsen.''
   ``The expectation that Dan Quayle was going to come across this
evening as vastly inferior to Lloyd Bentsen was totally a myth,''
said Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M. ``He came out quite to the
contrary a very competent person, given the most difficult
questions that anyone has ever been given.''
   Bentsen's Kennedy comment was ``vicious'' and Quayle's fault was
not being vicious enough in response, he said. Quayle should have
said in the rebuttal, ``Neither is Michael Dukakis,'' Domenici said.
   In what could be seen as perhaps the ultimate counter-spin to
the testy atmosphere, Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., and Rep. Dennis
Eckart, D-Ohio _ Quayle's Bentsen and Bentsen's Quayle in
mock-debate preparations _ stood and posed for pictures in the
press hall as the crowd finally started to thin out near midnight.
   In addition to the officials' ``spinning,'' each campaign
released a list of what were claimed to be distortions and
mis-statements by the opposition. The Republicans won that battle _
their list was out a good hour before the Democrats responded.
   Some of the spinners didn't wait until after the debate to offer
their views, a practice one wag called ``forespin.'' And the
reaction was always in line with the party line.
   ``I think Dan Quayle is more of an issue now than he was 90
minutes ago,'' said Susan Estrich, campaign manager for the Dukakis
campaign. That was about an hour before the debate even started,
but she said it again after the debate too.
</TEXT>
