<DOCNO> AP881006-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearSafety 1stLd-Writethru a0488 10-06 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Safety, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Says New Safety Guidelines For Reactor Got Lost In Paperwork</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 12th graf pvs, `A technical..., with
DOE report in The State newspaper; picks up 13th graf pvs, `As
part...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says new safety guidelines for
the Savannah River Plant that makes radioactive material for
nuclear arms were lost in ``paper work'' for a month last summer.
   During the delay, the plant operator waited 40 hours before
notifying the Department of Energy of a small power surge that
caused the shutdown of one of three atomic reactors at the plant,
Becky Craft, a department spokeswoman, said Wednesday.
   The delay violated both the new and the previous guidelines, she
said, and efforts have been made to improve procedures.
   Savannah River is the only U.S. facility which produces
weapons-grade plutonium and tritium.
   DOE and the E.I. du Pont Nemours & Co., which operates the plant
under contract, have come under fire in recent days because of
disclosures that during a 28-year period, up to 30 significant
reactor mishaps there were not reported to the public and in some
cases to Washington.
   The power surge in August triggered a review by an internal
Energy Department team which found the P reactor involved suffers
from ``numerous and longstanding'' problems with its control rods _
which act as accelerators and brakes on a reactor's rate of fission
_ that may prevent operators from recognizing potentially dangerous
conditions in its core, The Washington Post reported today.
   ``Technical support personnel stated they routinely calculate
core reactivity assuming seven rods are not in their programmed
positions,'' the team's report said, according to The Post. The
newspaper said it obtained a copy of the study, which has not been
released publicly.
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that a study by
a consulting firm of the plant's operations from 1971-1987 shows
that chronic equipment failure and poor operating procedures caused
nuclear reactors there to shut down unexpectedly nine to 12 times a
year for nearly two decades.
   That rate is twice that of the civilian nuclear power industry,
and Richard W. Starostecki, DOE's chief safety operator, told the
newspaper that civilian reactors with the same number of forced
shutdowns would have had their operating licenses revoked.
   Meanwhile, an internal memorandum about a May 10, 1965 accident
at the Savannah River plant said a supervisor had to stop a foreman
from taking action that could have turned a leak of cooling water
into a catastrophic accident, The Times reported from Aiken, S.C.,
near where the plant is located.
   ``One trained man stood between us and disaster,'' said the memo
written by a Du Pont engineer, Frederick B. Christensen, in 1981
when he took early retirement. Christensen had been in the reactor
control room when the incident occurred.
   A technical supervisor at the plant, Gerald F. Merz, told The
Times in an interview Wednesday that this was ``a premature
conclusion.''
   The Department of Energy, in an internal report obtained by the
The State of Columbia, S.C., criticized Savannah River's management
as isolated and said the plant is operated counter to ``practices
common to well-run nuclear plants.''
   The 50-page draft memorandum criticized ``less than precise and
out-of-date operating practices'' throughout the plant's management
and reactor staff, the newspaper reported today.
   Written by a panel of DOE officials and represenatives from
companies working at the plant, the report criticized Du Pont and
DOE for allowing reactor operators to grow complacent. It called
for streamlined communications and better training to handle
emergencies.
   As part of an effort to improve safety and reporting procedures
at Savannah River, Energy Undersecretary Joseph Salgado issued a
new order on June 21 requiring the contractor and the regional
Energy Department office, in Aiken to notify the Washington
headquarters immediately in the event of a safety problem.
   The notice did not reach the mailroom of the regional office
until July 7, nearly three weeks after it was issued. And it took
another month to reach the appropriate office in Aiken, said Ms.
Craft. The regional department office asked for clarification from
Washington and did not send the new guidance to Du Pont until Aug.
23, she said.
   In the meantime there was another mishap, a small power pulse on
Aug. 7 which caused the reactor to be shut down on Aug. 9.
   Since the incident in August, said Ms. Craft, ``we have worked
with du Pont to correct any deficiencies that we had. There are
several programs that du Pont has put in place to prevent this from
occurring in the future,'' she said.
   Du Pont spokesmen did not immediately return telephone calls to
their offices in Aiken.
</TEXT>
