<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-06 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Shares Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dipped slightly against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices fell sharply on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 95.53 points
Wednesday, lost another 233.15 points, or 0.85 percent, to finish
trading at 27,172.34. The index fell for the fifth straight day for
the first time this year.
   An analyst at Nomura Securities said the market's poor
performance stemmed from uncertainty before the release of U.S.
unemployment figures for September, scheduled for Friday.
   ``And of course, another major reason is the condition of the
emperor, although very few people mention it directly,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Emperor Hirohito, 87, has been in serious condition since he
vomited blood Sept. 19.
   Trading was light, with volume on the first section estimated at
600 million shares, and only a few issues such as paper and pulp
attracted attention.
   Meanwhile, the dollar closed at 133.30 yen, down 0.18 yen from
Wednesday's close of 133.48 yen. Opening slightly higher at 133.37
yen, the currency ranged between 133.30 and 133.53 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate was moving very little as investors traded
the currencies only for their speculative reasons and position
adjustment,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of the Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   Other dealers said the market lacked incentives and dealers were
cautious while awaiting the U.S. unemployment report.
</TEXT>
