<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KlanTrial     10-06 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klan Trial,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Seals Klan Verdict After Plaintiff Seeks to Drop Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has sealed a jury's verdict in a
$1.5 million damage suit against the Ku Klux Klan while he
considers a city council member's decision to withdraw as the chief
plaintiff.
   In a rambling explanation to U.S. District Judge Charles A. Moye
Jr., longtime civil rights activist and City Councilman Hosea L.
Williams said Wednesday he had lost sleep worrying about the
blue-collar defendants ``who have nothing but their homes, their
cars and their paychecks. ... I could not disrupt their families.''
   The suit seeks $1 million in punitive damages against two KKK
groups as corporations. Alabama lawyer Morris Dees also asked the
jury to return heavy individual damages: $200,000 against David
Holland, grand dragon of the Southern White Knights; and $100,000
each against Daniel Carver, Georgia grand dragon of the Invisible
Empire; the group's former grand dragon, Edward Stephens; and
Marion Franklin Shirley, a veteran of several white supremacist
groups and an associate of Holland's.
   But state Rep. Billy McKinney, D-Atlanta, who joined the lawsuit
in July, objected to Williams' attempt to halt the trial, resulting
in a hectic day of legal maneuvering while jurors were deliberating
a verdict.
   The suit charged that leaders of the Klan groups conspired to
disrupt a Jan. 17, 1987, ``brotherhood march'' by civil rights
activists in Forsyth County and violate the marchers' civil rights.
   Participants in the march were pelted with rocks, bottles and
other debris thrown from people who were among a large group of
counterdemonstrators who gathered in the virtually all-white county
north of Atlanta.
   A week later, more than 20,000 people descended upon Forsyth
County in a huge civil rights march that drew national attention.
   Moye ordered that the verdict, delivered to the courtroom
shortly before 5 p.m., be sealed in an envelope. He dismissed the
six jurors with orders that they not discuss their verdict with
anyone. He did not tell them why their verdict was sealed.
   Moye ordered a hearing today with Dees, who brought the lawsuit
on behalf of Williams, McKinney and 55 other marchers pelted with
rocks and bottles; and attorneys for the two KKK organizations,
their leaders and other defendants.
   Moye did not discuss the subject of the hearing, but defense
attorneys told the court they will file motions to reopen the trial
in order to question Williams and McKinney.
   The jury, which included one black member, began its
deliberations at Wednesday morning.
   Williams said he was torn by conscience as a believer in
``redemption'' and ``forgiving your enemies,'' saying Jesus Christ
and the late Martin Luther King Jr. would approve.
   Defense attorney Sam Dickson said it was a ``noble, chivalrous
and Christian gesture.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
