<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     10-06 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Says PTL Sale Not A Sure Bet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker says he's digging
in for a long battle to reclaim the television ministry and that
he's not deterred by a Canadian businessman who has signed a
contract to buy PTL's assets.
   Bakker, whose own proposal to buy back the television ministry
fell through, said many obstacles remain for Stephen Mernick of
Toronto, who wants to purchase the ministry's assets for $115
million.
   ``I look towards the long haul, I'm not in this for a short
term. Maybe it'll be another year before we restore (PTL), maybe it
will be two years,'' said Bakker, who left in March 1987 amid a
sex-and-money scandal.
   PTL's court-appointed trustee, M.C. ``Red'' Benton, announced
Tuesday he had signed a contract with Mernick. Benton had
identified other potential buyers but had not previously gone to
the contract stage.
   PTL has been in bankruptcy reorganization since June 1987 and
must sell its assets to pay creditors as soon as possible under an
order from U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds. Reynolds must
approve any sale, and is expected to hold a hearing in about a
month on Mernick's bid.
   ``There are so many obstacles that no way could I even think
about all of the ramifications of all this until I hear the final
gavel of the judge,'' Bakker said Wednesday.
   ``It's not over till it's over, as I've been saying,'' he said
in front of the new Jim and Tammy Information Office about two
miles south of the Christian theme park, Heritage USA. ``It seems
every few weeks we go through it's been sold again, and sold
again,'' he said, referring to other deals that collapsed.
   Attorney Joseph Kluttz, representing Mernick, said Mernick will
pay $50 million at closing for the deal and pay the $65 million
balance over five years.
   Mernick, an Orthodox Jew, has not said what he plans to do with
PTL or Heritage USA but that he would consider retaining its
Christian theme.
   Benton has said other bidders may still present offers directly
to the bankruptcy court, but he said his recommendation gives
Mernick's offer a strong upper hand.
   Bakker had proposed a $172 million plan to buy the ministry's
assets, but his bid lost credibility last month when he could not
come up with a $3 million downpayment.
   Bakker said he was skeptical about Mernick's chances of making
PTL profitable again.
   ``There's a thousand-room hotel there; I don't know how they're
going to fill it, I don't know how anyone without national
telelvison experience could fill it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WildHorses     10-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wild Horses,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wild Horses Released On Sanctuary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 mustangs have found a new home
at a 4,300-acre wild horse sanctuary on the rugged South Dakota
range.
   ``We're going to do our best to make this a success for years to
come,'' said Bob Burford, director of the U.S. Bureau of Land
Management, which sponsored the sanctuary and its dedication
Wednesday.
   The horses joined about 150 others already running free on the
sanctuary in an isolated southern Black Hills canyon.
   The mustangs were rounded up by the federal government from
public lands across the southwestern United States. The wild horses
in some areas were in danger of starving to death because natural
food sources no longer existed.
   The horses also were a nuisance to private landowners. Some have
been found slaughtered in Nevada.
   Nevada Gov. Dick Bryan earlier this week pledged full state
support to help federal officials in their investigation of the
rifle killings of nearly 300 wild horses.
   All the shootings occurred in remote central Nevada within a
40-mile stretch north of Austin, an isolated Nevada town on U.S.
50. Federal investigators said the horses died over a six-month
period.
   But at the sanctuary in South Dakota, state officials said they
think the wild horses will be a popular tourist attraction,
particularly during the state's centennial next year when attention
is focused on South Dakota's frontier and western heritage.
   The driving force behind the sanctuary was Dayton Hyde, a
lifelong rancher and the founder of the Institute of Range and the
American Mustang.
   ``They're having fun,'' Hyde said. ``They spend a lot of their
time just running. They take off like school children.''
   Hyde said he hopes to develop a wild horse museum at the
sanctuary, featuring films about horses and a history of the horse
in the West's development.
   ``I want a front porch from which you can see the horse herd
along the Cheyenne River,'' he said. ``This is some of the most
beautiful country in the West. Not enough people get to see it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     10-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Insurgents Claim Control Of Third Provincial Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels said today they
captured a third provincial capital and seized a city along the
strategic Kabul-Jalalabad highway that includes a major
hydroelectric plant.
   Spokesmen from Afghan resistance parties headquartered in
Pakistan said guerrillas made significant gains against the Marxist
government this week, particularly in eastern Afghanistan.
   A Western diplomat confirmed the fall of Sharan, capital of
Paktika province in eastern Afghanistan. Three of the 29 provincial
capitals now are reportedly under guerrilla control.
   ``Its only significance is that it's a provincial capital,
nothing else,'' said Azim Nasir-Zia of the National Islamic Front
of Afghanistan resistance organization.
   The guerrilla-controlled Afghan News Agency said government
troops at Sharan were captured, but it gave no figures. Guerrillas
claim to control Toloqan, the northeastern provincial capital of
Takhar, and the central Bamyan provincial capital.
   Naser-Zia said Afghan guerrillas also took control of Sarobi, 36
miles east of the Afghan capital on the strategic Kabul-Jalalabad
highway. The city has a hydroelectric plant that feeds power to the
capital, Kabul, he said.
   In other fighting, Afghan rebels said the heavily fortified
military town of Urgun in Paktika province was captured.
   Jan Mohammed of the Hezb-e-Islami group's Khalis faction said
the garrison town was overrun during a joint operation Wednesday
involving guerrillas from the seven resistance parties,
headquartered in Peshawar.
   A field commander with the Itihad-e-Islami resistance group said
the fall of Urgun gives the guerrillas full control of Pakitika
province.
   ``Urgun is considered the most strategic district in Paktika,''
said a guerrilla spokesman. ``It is very important, as control of
Urgun allows control of the most strategic roads to north and
central Afghanistan.''
   The U.S.-supported Afghan guerrillas have been fighting the
Soviet-backed Kabul government for the past 10 years. Soviet
soldiers, who entered Afghanistan to prop up the embattled
Communist government in December 1979, began leaving in May.
   A United Nations agreement signed in Geneva provides for the
complete withdrawal of about 100,000 Red Army troops by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
