<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Two Arabs Accused of Collaborating With Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with Moslem fundamentalist group ending
split with PLO-led groups; PICKS up 2nd graf pvs, `Two sons ...'
SUBS 2 grafs for 13th pvs, `The clashes ...' to CORRECT strike
called in memory of shooting victims sted accident victims; PICKS
up 14th pvs, `On Wednesday ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab gunmen today fatally shot two West Bank
Palestinians accused of collaborating with Israel, including a
village elder gunned down while driving with his children, radio
reports and Arab witnesses said.
   Also today, the Moslem fundamentalist group Hamas called for an
end to Palestinian infighting, indicating that it has healed its
rift with the PLO-backed Unified National Leadership of the
Uprising.
   ``We must be united despite the differences in our beliefs,''
Hamas said in an underground leaflet distributed in the occupied
lands. ``We are ... against any kind of split.''
   The rapprochement came after several meetings between the two
groups in the past two weeks, Arab sources said.
   Hamas repeatedly has challenged the leadership of pro-PLO groups
in orchestrating the uprising. Last month, Hamas staged a
successful general strike in defiance of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Two sons of the slain village leader, an 8-year-old and a
14-year-old, were wounded in the attack in Biddya in the occupied
West Bank, military sources and Israel radio said.
   The dead mukhtar, or traditional village leader, was ambushed by
gunmen while driving his car. He was identified as 46-year-old
Mustafa Salim Abu Bakr.
   Witnesses said the elder's body was set on fire with his car
after the attack.
   The army confirmed the death and clamped a curfew on Biddya, 45
miles north of Jerusalem. The radio said troops arrested several
Palestinian suspects.
   Military sources said there had been past attempts on Abu Bakr's
life, including a gun attack in August.
   The second Palestinian, 25-year-old Ahmed Sahour, was sprayed
with gunfire in a cafe in the Israeli Arab village of Umm El Fahm,
where he had been in hiding since being chased out of the nearby
West Bank village of Amin, the radio and Arab witnesses said.
   The radio said Sahour was struck by six pistol shots.
   The deaths raised to nine the number of suspected collaborators
killed since the Arab uprising began nearly 10 months ago.
Underground leaders have ordered Palestinians to attack all Arabs
cooperating with Israel.
   In all, 283 Palestinians have been killed since Dec. 8, the
beginning of the rebellion against Israel's 21-year occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Six Israelis have also been killed.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, troops shot and wounded two
Palestinians during clashes in the Jebaliya refugee camp and Gaza
City, officials at the city's Ahli Arab Hospital said.
   The army clamped curfews on Jebaliya as well as the Gaza refugee
camps of Shati and Bureij.
   The clashes came during a general strike observed throughout the
coastal Gaza Strip in memory of four Palestinian guerrillas killed
a year ago in a shootout with Israeli soldiers.
   The four, members of the Moslem fundamentalist group Islamic
Jihad, were shot to death Oct. 6, 1987 when they refused to stop at
an army roadblock in Gaza City.
   On Wednesday, two Israel troops were injured when a firebomb
smashed into their jeep in the West Bank town of Tulkarem. One
soldier suffered moderate to serious burns and the other was
slightly injured.
   Troops shot and wounded 14 Palestinians in clashes Wednesday and
a 23-year-old Palestinian from the Balata refugee camp died of
wounds he suffered a week earlier.
</TEXT>
