<2ND_LINE>PM-Phone Murder,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Hears Boyfriend's Murder Over Phone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who listened on the telephone as her
boyfriend was shot to death provided authorities with the name of a
suspect who was charged in the shooting, police said.
   Harold Tinch, 30, a security guard, was shot in the neck,
abdomen and right hand while talking on the telephone Tuesday night
with his girlfriend, Sarah Gordon, 25, of Detroit.
   Alarmed after hearing three shots and then silence on the
Chicago end of the line, Ms. Gordon hung up and dialed the Chicago
Police Department to report what she heard.
   Ms. Gordon's information led to the arrest Wednesday of Ricardo
Manuel, 29, who was charged with first degree murder.
   While Tinch and Ms. Gordon were talking, Ms. Gordon heard a man
enter Tinch's home. She asked who it was, and Tinch responded
``Rick,'' Ms. Gordon told police.
   As the couple continued to talk, Ms. Gordon heard Tinch tell
Rick to ``put the gun down and stop playing with it.'' Tinch owned
a .38-caliber revolver.
   Shortly thereafter, Ms. Gordon said she heard Tinch again ask
Rick to ``put it down. Don't point it at me.''
   She then heard a shot and heard Tinch say, ``Don't shoot me
again.'' Ms. Gordon heard two more shots, then silence.
   Police found Tinch dead in an upstairs bedroom. Police said they
found the revolver, with three expended cartridges, in the room.
   Neighbors directed police to Manuel, who lived a block away.
   Manuel admitted that he shot Tinch, saying it was accidental,
police said.
</TEXT>
