<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0497 10-06 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Exchange Over John F. Kennedy Draws Strong Reaction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Cuomo, Sununu, Ferraro comments, inserting new
grafs 4-5, inserting 2 grafs after 17th graf pvs, ``Bentsen came,
and deleting last 5 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The heated vice presidential debate exchange over Dan Quayle's
invocation of John F. Kennedy is drawing strong partisan reaction,
with Democrats denouncing the ``audacity'' of the Indiana senator
and backers of the Republican ticket accusing Lloyd Bentsen of ``a
cheap shot.''
   Politicians followed party lines in their reaction to Wednesday
night's confrontation between the hand-picked candidates for vice
president.
   Backers of Democrat Michael Dukakis declared Bentsen a landslide
winner, while supporters of Republican George Bush were equally
effusive about Quayle's performance.
   Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York said today that Quayle
``looked like Johnny Carson playing Karnac; he started with the
answers and looked for the questions. So when you judge the top of
the ticket, judge them by the people they select.''
   On the other side, Republican Gov. John Sununu of New Hampshire
said that both Quayle and Bentsen showed ``they can serve as
president if necessary'' but that the focus would now return to
Dukakis and Bush. ``As much as the Democrats are trying to suggest
that Michael Dukakis is not going to serve if elected, he is,''
Sununu said.
   Both commented on NBC's ``Today.''
   Debate coaches gave the edge to Bentsen, with one calling the
Kennedy exchange the point that turned the clash in the Texan's
favor.
   Melissa Maxcy Wade, the director of forensics at Emory
University and a member of a panel of experts who judged the debate
for The Associated Press, said ``I thought Quayle really held his
own until we got to the John Kennedy question. It was like a father
putting down a child. I thought the momentum turned then.''
   The dramatic highlight of the 90-minute debate occurred at the
midpoint when Quayle said his qualifications for high office were
equal to those of Kennedy when he was elected president in 1960.
Like Kennedy, Quayle has served eight years in the Senate.
   ``Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy,'' Bentsen snapped.
   ``That was really uncalled for,'' Quayle retorted.
   Replied Bentsen: ``You're the one that was making the
comparison, senator ... and I did not think the comparison was well
taken.''
   ``Dan Quayle has the audacity to compare himself to John
Kennedy,'' said Buie Seawell, chairman of the Colorado Democratic
Party. ``You saw Lloyd Bentsen throw a right cross that dropped him
to the canvas.''
   ``I think it was a cheap shot,'' Republican Sen. Alan Simpson of
Wyoming said of the Bentsen jibe. ``That was very unbecoming of
Lloyd Bentsen.''
   Arne Carlson, Minnesota state auditor and the state's highest
ranking GOP official, praised both debaters.
   ``Bentsen is obviously mature, well informed,'' he said.
``Quayle came across as quite bright, alert. I think he did an
excellent job of dispelling concern people had over his candidacy.''
   Carlson said Bentsen ``made a terrible mistake with the jab on
John Kennedy. I think most people thought that was unnecessary and
quite rude.''
   ``It threw a chill over the whole debate, a sour note,'' said
Atlanta-based pollster Claibourne Darden. ``It changed from then
on, the way you looked at Lloyd Bentsen.''
   California pollster Mervyn Field also used the man-boy analogy,
to describe the Kennedy exchange.
   ``Bentsen came through as the man and Quayle came through as the
boy,'' he said.
   Geraldine Ferraro, whose family was subjected to intense
investigation after her Democratic vice presidential nomination
four years ago, laughingly disagreed with Quayle's contention that
he was the most-investigated candidate in history.
   ``He's young, but he's not that young; he's got to remember
1984,'' she said today on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   Field said he thought Bentsen did so well people might wish he
were at the top of the Democratic ticket rather than Dukakis.
   ``It may be a mixed blessing to the Democratic ticket,'' he said.
   Darden took a similar view, saying, ``Bentsen makes Michael
Dukakis look weak.''
   Merle Black, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina, said ``I think Bentsen did a better job. I think the
Dukakis ticket ought to be helped by his performance.''
   But he also praised Quayle who, he said, ``performed well enough
that the Bush campaign will not have to engage in extensive damage
control after tonight. But I think he was out-debated by Bentsen.''
   Nancy Neuman, president of the League of Women Voters, called
the debate a draw.
   ``I don't see that one outshone the other particularly,'' she
said. ``I think they came off pretty well as they intended. Whether
the voters won, I'm still trying to figure out.''
</TEXT>
