<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SubwayAds 1stLd-Writethru a0507 10-06 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Subway Ads, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ads Opposing Aid To Salvador Go Up In Subways Despite Initial
Rejection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf, `The ad ...' to UPDATE with
cost of ads in New York City; Pickup 6th graf, `The coalition...'
SUBS 10th graf, `But they...' to delete now-redundant first
reference to D'Elia.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Yorkers already accustomed to subway ads for
hemorrhoid ointments, roach killers and AIDS prevention will see a
graphic ad opposing aid to El Salvador that had been rejected here
and elsewhere as inflammatory.
   The advertisement shows a photograph of a dead man lying in a
pool of blood on a Salvadoran street. ``What are your tax dollars
buying in El Salvador?'' it asks.
   The company that controls subway ad contracts for the city had
rejected it last spring on the grounds that it was ``inflammatory''
and ``offensive.''
   The ad finally went up in every fourth subway car this week
after the organization behind it threatened legal action and the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority decided the ad did not
violate its standards of good taste.
   The ad is sponsored by Winning Democracy in El Salvador, a
Washington, D.C.-based coalition of organizations that opposes U.S.
aid to El Salvador.
   All told, producing and renting the space for the New York ad is
costing Winning Democracy about $20,000, said Mike D'Elia, a New
York spokesman for the group.
   The coalition is placing similar ads in buses and subways
throughout the country. In San Francisco, the ads are due in a
month or two. In Washington, they will be going up this week. They
are up already in Boston.
   The company that arranges ad contracts for Los Angeles' buses
has so far refused to accept the ads, said Carol Waymire, who
represents the Winning Democracy in El Salvador campaign in Los
Angeles.
   In New York, an April rejection letter from the private firm
that handles subway ad contracts for the MTA stated that the ad was
``inflammatory'' and could ``encourage vandalism'' by riders who
might be tempted to tear it down.
   In another letter, the New York Subways Advertising Firm cited a
provision in its contract with the city under which ads may be
rejected if they are ``deemed offensive to good taste.''
   ``But they have all sorts of offensive things advertised in the
subway _cockroach ads, ads about AIDS, about abortion, about
incest,'' D'Elia said.
   ``We think that's great that they put these other signs up. But
we were totally befuddled that we couldn't put our signs up.''
   At no cost to Winning Democracy, Edward Copeland, a lawyer who
specializes in civil liberties, agreed to challenge the rejection
of the ad as a violation of the constitutional right to freedom of
expression.
   ``The First Amendment applies to public forums, and the subways
in New York are public forums,'' he said. ``The Winning Democracy
people have a right to express their viewpoints and to reach out to
their fellow citizens.''
   The conflict was resolved without a lawsuit after Copeland
contacted the MTA.
   ``When we reviewed it, we didn't find it to be objectionable,''
said MTA spokesman Tito Davila. ``We have the final say on these
things.''
   Davila said the subway ad firm is supposed to submit any
rejected advertisement to the MTA for final review, but failed to
do so in this case.
   Bill Apfelbaum, president of the firm, did not return phone
calls by The Associated Press seeking comment.
   As compensation for the delay in accepting the ad, it will run
for two months for the price of one, Copeland said.
   ``We're hoping the ad will get the public debating again about
what's happening in El Salvador,'' said D'Elia. ``We're trying to
expose the policy of U.S. government support for what we consider a
brutal military dictatorship.''
   The United States has sent nearly $3 billion in military and
economic aid to El Salvador during the last eight years, according
to the State Department. The Reagan administration says the aid has
resulted in democratic and economic reforms.
   But opponents say the aid has bolstered military control of the
country and that human-rights abuses and killings by death squads
are rampant.
   The ads, designed by internationally renowned artist John
Baldessari, supply a phone number that readers can call for more
information.
   The ads, in English and Spanish, will reach an estimated 4.5
million New Yorkers, said D'Elia.
</TEXT>
