<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     10-06 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Near On U.S. Bases, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine and U.S. officials said
today they have narrowed differences over U.S. military bases here
and are nearing agreement on their status through 1991.
   President Corazon Aquino and U.S. Undersecretary of State
Michael Armacost gave the assessment after a 45-minute meeting,
which the U.S. official described as a ``very good talk.''
   Filipino and American panels began talks last April on the
status of Clark Air Base, the Subic Bay naval base and four smaller
installations. But the talks have stalled over compensation and
other issues.
   Armacost told reporters after the meeting that Foreign Secretary
Raul Manglapus and Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur met
Wednesday in New York on the bases talks.
   ``Progress is being made and the hope was there for an early
agreement,'' he said.
   In a statement to Filipino reporters later, Mrs. Aquino said she
received a call from Manglapus today and that ``he sounded very
optimistic and confident.''
   The United States maintains the bases under a 1947 agreement
that expires in 1991. The current talks are to determine
compensation and other issues through the final two years of the
agreement.
   After that, any extension must be approved by two-thirds of the
23-member Senate, where opposition to the bases is strong. Mrs.
Aquino refuses to say whether she will support an extension.
   Also today, leaders of a new party backing Aquino pushed through
a plan to reorganize the House of Representatives but agreed to
maintain an alliance with other coalition members.
   The move would give the party, the Struggle of the Democratic
Filipino, clear control of the House as the majority party and
force other rival but non-opposition parties to accept their
minority status, politicians said.
   After a closed-door meeting of pro-Aquino legislators, House
speaker Ramon Mitra announced that a majority voted to reorganize
House committees and that at least five chairmen had tendered
``courtesy resignations.''
   He said party leaders would continue meeting to decide on a
system of apportioning chairmanships of the House's 43 committees.
The reorganization was expected to be completed next week, he said.
   Creation of the party triggered so much realignment within the
coalition that the new group wound up the biggest
pro-administration party with 158 of the 203 seats in the House. It
has seven seats in the 23-member Senate.
</TEXT>
