<DOCNO> AP881006-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-KillingFields     10-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Killing Fields,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Killing Fields' Survivor Assails U.N. For Seating Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographer Dith Pran, who barely escaped
Cambodia's killing fields, denounced the United Nations for
allowing the Khmer Rouge to be seated as part of the Cambodian
delegation.
   ``I am still shocked when I see the Khmer Rouge flag on U.N.
territory. How would you feel if you were Jewish and you saw
Hitler's flag flying at the U.N.?'' Dith said Wednesday to a crowd
of about 250 demonstrators.
   In 1975, when the Khmer Rouge toppled Cambodia's government,
Dith was trapped in the country. Like most of the population, he
endured famine and forced labor on a collective farm, but managed
to escape to Thailand in 1979.
   Dith is now a photographer for The New York Times. His ordeal,
and that of his people, received worldwide attention in the movie
``The Killing Fields.''
   About 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people died under the
Khmer Rouge's attempt to impose agrarian communism from 1975 to
1979. Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and ousted Pol Pot's
Khmer Rouge regime.
   Wednesday's protest coincided with Cambodia's speech to the 43rd
General Assembly, with the Khmer Rouge sharing a seat in the
delegation. The vigil was organized by the Oxfam America relief
agency.
   Oxfam's executive director John Hammock and several of its
officers began a three-day fast Wednesday to protest the Khmer
Rouge membership in the United Nations.
   ``There is no justice yet,'' said Dith, his voice strained with
anger. ``Justice and peace haven't come to my country. ... I want
to see the Cambodians happy. I want to see Cambodians smiling
again.''
   In an effort to root all Western influence out of Cambodia, the
Khmer Rouge renamed 1975 ``Year Zero,'' and sent city-dwellers to
work on collective farms.
   Dith was among the forced laborers until he escaped across the
Thai border to a refugee camp.
   Oxfam, Dith, and many Cambodians fear that the Khmer Rouge, the
best armed of the three groups fighting the Phnom Penh government,
will seize power. The Khmer Rouge are backed by China.
   Hanoi has said it will withdraw 50,000 of its 120,000 occupation
troops from Cambodia this year and that all are to be out by late
1989 or early 1990.
   Many people fear the Khmer Rouge will fill the military and
political void left by the retreating Vietnamese.
   The resistance coalition also includes the non-communist Khmer
People's National Liberation Front of Son Samm and forces loyal to
former Cambodian head of state Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Under the U.N. Charter and international law, the United Nations
says it cannot recognize a government imposed on a country by
outside force, such as the current Cambodian government installed
by Hanoi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
