<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Reform     10-06 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Reform,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medvedev Endorses Importing of Economic Ideas from West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's new ideology chief said
socialism must learn from the West and try the kind of bold
economic experiments President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has proposed.
   In his first major speech since being catapulted onto the ruling
Politburo, Vadim Medvedev said some of Gorbachev's reforms have
fostered abuses, but in general he showed himself a closer ally of
the Soviet leader than his predecessor as ideology chief, Yegor K.
Ligachev.
   Some Western diplomatic analysists had predicted Medvedev, seen
as a reform economist, would be charged with redefining socialism
to incorporate Gorbachev's pragmatic approach to rebuilding the
Soviet economy.
   His remarks, published Wednesday in the newspapers Pravda and
Izvestia, appeared to begin that process. But he took a cautious
first step.
   ``Unfortunately, there have been some irresponsible attempts to
cast a shadow over Lenin's inheritance, over the basic values of
socialism,'' Medvedev said.
   ``And how else can those statements appearing in the press be
interpreted that claim that the command-administrative system
resulted from Lenin, those attempts to deny the socialist nature of
our system, that even doubt the rightness of our choice for
socialism?''
   Medvedev, 59, a political economist by training, was named to
the Communist Party Politburo on Friday by the party's
policy-making Central Committee and was named to head a newly
created commission on ideology.
   He spoke Tuesday to an international conference in Moscow on the
problems of contemporary socialism.
   In his reported remarks, Medvedev showed himself more open to
following the Western example to help solve Soviet problems than
was Ligachev, the Politburo member reputed to be a conservative
opponent of Gorbachev.
   But some Soviets who read Medvedev's speech in the national
press said it was impossible to conclude that the newest Politburo
member had completely embraced Gorbachev's reform agenda.
   The party's new ideology chief spoke of the need for ``deep
qualitative rejuvenation'' in socialism, and said the solution to
some Soviet problems could come from other socialist countries, and
even from the West.
   ``While the socialist perspective is being worked out, the
experience of humanity as a whole cannot be ignored, including the
non-socialist part of the world,'' Medvedev said.
   ``I'm referring not only to the scientific and technical
achievements of the system that is opposed to us, but to many forms
of organization of public life, of the economic process.''
   Medvedev also urged a rethinking of the role of central planning
and the market, and voiced support for two pillars of Gorbachev's
program for ``perestroika,'' or nationwide restructuring: leasing
farmland to individual farmers and spreading economic cooperatives
to provide consumer goods that are lacking in the state sector.
   Ligachev, in an Aug. 5 speech, said the class struggle
determines international relations. But Medvedev hewed more closely
to Gorbachev's line, which maintains that in the nuclear age, East
and West must cooperate to solve common problems.
   ``The conception is outdated that socialism and capitalism can
develop in a parallel way,'' Medvedev said. ``On the contrary,
their ways will inevitably intersect, both systems will inevitably
interact within the framework of the same human civilization.''
</TEXT>
