<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Student'sSuit     10-06 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student's Suit,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Files Lawsuit Seeking MBA or Money Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student who failed an economics test
twice has filed a lawsuit seeking to force the University of
Central Florida to award her a master's degree in business
administration or refund her $5,000 tuition.
   Nora Roth, 48, claims she earned her master's degree with good
grades in her classwork, although she couldn't pass a final test.
   ``After paying all my dues and having a good (grade point)
average I just feel abused,'' Mrs. Roth said. ``I really don't want
their money. I just want what I earned, which is a master's
degree.''
   The economics test is a required review of all four elements of
the material: finance, management, marketing and economics.
   Mrs. Roth passed the three other parts of the test but failed
the economics section. She hired a tutor, crammed for another
semester and took the test again. She failed again.
   She filed the lawsuit last week with the help of her husband
Kenneth, who is a lawyer.
   She claims the test is unfair because the school's economics
professors hold different economic theories and place emphasis on
different areas of the subject. Her test was prepared by a
professor she did not study under and included material she had
never studied, Mrs. Roth contends.
   Dean Clifford Eubanks of the university's College of Business
defended the test, which he said is common at colleges across the
country. Eubanks said Tuesday it was not uncommon for students to
fail the test several times and added that Mrs. Roth can take it
again.
</TEXT>
