<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySwap     10-06 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer To Fight Genetic Test Of Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer says he will try to prevent a
genetic test that could determine whether his client's 9-year-old
daughter was switched at birth and is actually the child of a
Pennsylvania couple.
   A hearing is scheduled for Friday at which the couple, Ernest
and Regina Twigg of Langhorne, Pa., plan to ask a judge to order
that the Sarasota girl produce a blood sample.
   ``You can't just allow people to come in with suspicions and
demand blood tests,'' Arthur Ginsburg, a lawyer for the father,
said Wednesday.
   The Twiggs contend their healthy newborn daughter was swapped
nearly 10 years ago for a sickly one at Hardee Memorial Hospital in
Wauchula.
   The child they raised, Arlena, died of heart problems Aug. 23,
shortly after a genetic test determined she was not biologically
related to the couple, the Twiggs said.
   The Twiggs filed a $100 million lawsuit against Hardee Memorial,
three doctors and a nurse, alleging fraud and negligence. They also
have said they want to find and regain custody of their biological
daughter.
   That search has focused on another blue-eyed blonde who,
according to state records, was born at Hardee three days before
Mrs. Twigg gave birth. The couple believe their real daughter now
lives in Sarasota.
   Ginbsurg said his client is certain he is the biological father
and intends to keep the girl he has raised and loved for 10 years
regardless of what a test would show.
   A genetic test ``can't make him feel any more the father,''
Ginsburg said, ``and I can't see how it will do us any good.''
   Ginsburg said the couple has not presented convincing evidence
that the Twiggs are the true parents and deserve a blood test.
   Marvin Ellin, an attorney for the couple, said no firm evidence
is required to bring a court action to determine paternity.
</TEXT>
