<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Election 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KIRYAT SHARETT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Occupied Lands Move To Center Stage In Election Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with today's campaigning, edits to
trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres forced his
way through a hostile crowd today during a campaign tour of an open
air market where youths taunted the Labor Party candidate with
shouts of ``Peres go home.''
   Aides to Peres described the confrontation in this town, a
traditional stronghold of the rival right-wing Likud bloc, as the
worst of the campaign for the Nov. 1 parliamentary elections.
   Security guards subdued one man who tried to throw a tomato at
Peres, while scores of youths in blue and white Likud shirts shoved
their way toward Peres.
   The protesters also shouted ``Begin, Begin,'' the name of the
former Likud prime minister, Menachem Begin, and mocked Peres'
moderate policies toward Arabs with cries of ``Arafat, PLO.''
   In a speech later to a more sympathetic audience of elderly
people in a shopping plaza, Peres stressed that Labor's peace
strategy was aimed at avoiding a demographic problem with Arabs.
   ``We are 3.5 million Jews in Israel and there are 2.4 million
Arabs'' in territory controlled by Israel, Peres said. ``If Likud
succeeds and annexes the territories, we are going to have an Arab
majority. It is the Likud then that will make a Palestinian state.''
   On Wednesday, the Likud leader, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
vowed that if he is re-elected, Israel will not withdraw from the
occupied territories or allow an independent Palestinian state.
   Shamir spoke in a working class suburb of Tel Aviv and accused
Labor of pursuing a dangerous policy ``leading to pressure on us to
abandon every achievement the Israeli nation made in the Six Day
War, including united Jerusalem.''
   It was in that war in June 1967 that Israel sized the West Bank
and Gaza Strip and annexed Arab east Jerusalem.
   Aides said Peres was upset by the pushing and shoving today in
the Ramle market, although he showed no signs of it as he walked
stony-faced in shirt sleeves through the town of 46,000, several
miles from Tel Aviv.
   ``It demonstrates a certain style that a better part of the
Israeli people do not like to see,'' Peres told The Associated
Press.
   In Jerusalem, meanwhile, the 40-member Central Elections
Committee rejected a bid by right-wing parties to disqualify a
leftist Jewish-Arab party, claiming its support for dialogue with
the PLO would undermine the Jewish state.
   On Wednesday, the board disqualified U.S.-born right-wing
extremist Meir Kahane from running in the elections, saying his
calls to expel Arabs were racist and illegal. Kahane is appealing
the decision to the Supreme Court.
   Peres' colleague, Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev, proposed
Wednesday that Israel remove troops from certain Arab towns to cool
tensions until a land-for-peace compromise could be worked out with
the Palestinians.
   The Likud bloc opposes yielding any of the Arab lands Israel
captured in 1967 on the grounds that territorial concessions would
endanger security.
   The Likud also rejects a Labor-backed proposal to convene an
international peace conference including the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council, Israel, Jordan, a Palestinian
delegation and Egypt.
   Shamir has said Israel would be isolated in a hostile forum and
forced to give up the occupied territories.
   Since the Arab uprising began Dec. 8, more than 280 Palestinians
have been killed in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Six Israelis also
have died.
</TEXT>
