<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Debate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>League Demands $90,000 To Turn Over Debate Hall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 8th graf bgng, Efforts to, with 4 new grafs on
league response bgng, In Washington.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the commission now sponsoring
the second presidential debate says it is seeking a new location
because the League of Women Voters held the original debate site in
Los Angeles ``hostage.''
   Bob Neuman, director of media arrangements for the Commission on
Presidential Debates, said Wednesday the League of Women Voters was
demanding $90,000 in payments before releasing the Shrine
Auditorium in Los Angeles.
   Neuman said the commission still wants the second and final
debate between George Bush and Michael Dukakis to be held in Los
Angeles.
   But the League on Wednesday moved to secure the hall by placing
a $40,000 deposit on it _ two days after the group announced it was
backing out as sponsor of the debate in a dispute over control of
format and staging details, he said.
   Neuman said the League was demanding repayment of the deposit
plus $50,000 reimbursement for expenses before releasing the hall
to the bipartisan commission for the debate, to be held Oct. 13 or
Oct. 14, depending on the length of the Major League Baseball
playoffs.
   ``What they're telling us is they're willing to spend $40,000 to
keep the hall empty,'' Neuman, in Omaha for the vice presidential
debate, said.
   ``We consider that holding the hall hostage,'' he said. ``We're
not going to deal with them.''
   In Washington, League spokeswoman Stephanie Drea said Neuman's
allegations were ``absurd'' and ``an unfortunate ploy to try to
embarrass the League.''
   She said the non-profit League was not holding the Shrine
Auditorium hostage but was merely seeking reimbursement for the
$40,000 deposit and costs of preparing the hall for the debate,
including broadcast equipment and fire safety precautions.
   She said the commitment for the deposit was made long before the
League decided to withdraw its sponsorship of the event.
   ``We got the ball rolling,'' she said. ``Now they can pick it up
and run with it. We should be reimbursed for our very real costs
that have gone into planning for that debate, and no more.''
   The nationally broadcast debate was to have been sponsored by
the League of Women Voters on Thursday or Friday of next week.
   However, league officials, angered by refusal of the two
presidential campaigns to give up control of the format and staging
details, withdrew.
   Commission Executive Director Janet Brown, in Omaha to direct
commission handling of the vice presidential debate, said the
commission was looking for local donors to pay for putting on the
second presidential debate. She said the first debate in
Winston-Salem, N.C., cost $500,000 to stage, and the Los Angeles
one would cost at least that much.
   Neuman said he remained optimistic the debate would be held,
despite the dispute over the hall.
</TEXT>
