<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0510 10-06 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Claims Debate Victory Despite Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Quayle comments; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Leaving the; rally scheduled for 12:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle said today he was not worried about a poll showing that many
television viewers thought he had lost Wednesday night's debate
with Democrat Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``George Bush is going to win the election. He's still way ahead
in the polls,'' Quayle said as he left a morning rally at his hotel.
   An ABC poll indicated that many TV viewers believed Bentsen had
trounced the Indiana senator. But Quayle, asked if he was concerned
about the poll, said, ``Not at all. We're still ahead.''
   Quayle told supporters at the rally that ``we now have a little
more than four weeks left in this campaign.''
   ``This election is going to be decided by the American people
and it's going to be decided on the issues,'' Quayle said.
   He headed for rallies in Missouri and Florida and a lunch with
former President Ford.
   After the debate, Quayle said the Texas senator had ``absolutely
no response to the fact that Michael Dukakis is simply out of step
with mainstream America.''
   Leaving the debate Wednesday night, the Indiana senator beamed
at reporters and pronounced his own performance ``great.''
   He insisted that he was pleased at having been grilled
repeatedly by the panelists about his qualifications for national
office.
   ``We were delighted that they brought it up three different
times because it gave us three different times to talk to the
American people about what I'll do for the country,'' Quayle said.
   The Republican vice presidential nominee received congratulatory
calls after the debate from Vice President George Bush, President
Reagan and Senate Republican leader Bob Dole.
   Bush told his running mate, ``You did great,'' said Quayle
spokesman David Prosperi.
   At a post-debate outdoor rally Wednesday night, Quayle told
2,000 flag-waving supporters that Bentsen ``had a difficult time
defending the liberal governor from Massachusetts.''
   ``There was absolutely no response to the fact that Michael
Dukakis is simply out of step with mainstream America,'' Quayle
said.
   Referring to Wednesday's American League playoff game in which
the Oakland Athletics beat the Boston Red Sox 2-1, Quayle said,
``This afternoon, the team from Massachusetts lost, and tonight,
the man from Massachusetts lost.''
   ``I feel great,'' Quayle said.
   But despite strong statements of victory by Quayle and his
advisers, early indications were that many people had doubts his
performance. An ABC poll of 637 viewers gave the round to Bentsen
by 51 percent to 27 percent, with a 4.5 percent margin of error.
   In particular, Quayle seemed to suffer during an exchange with
Bentsen on Quayle's oft-stated defense of his youth and
qualifications. Quayle, 41, said he had just as much experience in
Congress as John F. Kennedy did when, at 43, he ran for president.
   ``Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy,'' Bentsen said.
   Quayle told reporters outside the rally Wednesday night that
Bentsen's comments were ``uncalled for,'' a charge he had made
during the debate. Aides went further, calling it a ``cheap shot.''
   Late Wednesday, the campaign released a statement of ``Bentsen
distortions and errors.'' On the Kennedy question, the statement
said Quayle ``never said he was JFK; he simply compared his age and
level of experience in response to a question.''
   Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman, said the senator would be able to
put the Kennedy question and those about his qualifications
``behind him.''
   ``We'll focus the attention on Dukakis and on the fact that
Lloyd Bentsen couldn't defend his running mate,'' Prosperi said.
   Despite the heated exchange between the two nominees, Prosperi
noted that it had been Quayle who went over to Bentsen and
initiated the closing handshake ``before Bentsen even left the
podium.''
   ``It just shows he's a bigger man than Bentsen,'' Prosperi said.
</TEXT>
