<HEAD>As Many As 50 Million Watched Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 50 million viewers tuned into the
vice presidential debate Wednesday night, according to preliminary
figures from the 16 largest television markets measured by the A.C.
Nielsen Co.
   U.S. Sens. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and Dan Quayle, R-Ind., faced
off in the 90-minute debate, carried by all three networks and CNN
live from Omaha, Neb., at 8:30 p.m. EDT.
   According to Nielsen, ABC had a rating of 14.1 and a 22 share.
NBC had a 12.1 and 18. CBS had 8.8 and 13. Each rating point equals
904,000 households with televisions. The share is a percentage of
sets in use. That means 53 percent of the televisions that were on
during that time period were tuned to the debate.
   A National League playoff game in Los Angeles between the New
York Mets and the L.A. Dodgers had been rescheduled to follow the
debate. The game was carried by ABC.
   Ratings weren't available immediately for CNN.
</TEXT>
