<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 10-06 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hails Bentsen Debate Performance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Dukakis comments; pick up 3rd graf pvs
bgng ``Before he left...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said today his running mate's
debate performance was ``a real plus for us'' and he laid claim to
momentum in the final weeks of the presidential race.
   The Democratic nominee said Lloyd Bentsen was ``knowledgeable
and relaxed'' during the Wednesday night encounter while Republican
Dan Quayle was ``programmed beyond belief.'' Dukakis characterized
Quayle as ``extremely insecure'' and lacking in ``strength,
confidence or anything.''
   ``This will be a real plus for us,'' Dukakis told reporters as
he flew to Texas to join Bentsen at a rally.
   Before he left Boston, Dukakis' campaign distributed a
blistering analysis of Quayle's performance, saying, ``Whenever
Senator Quayle deviated from his well-memorized script, his answers
were shallow, revealing his lack of substantive knowledge. He
appeared uninformed and a stranger to basic facts on almost every
issue.''
   The statement noted that Quayle was asked several times what he
would do if suddenly thrust into the presidency, and it said that
in every response, ``he failed.''
   Dukakis took time after the Wednesday night debate between
Bentsen and Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle to join supporters and deliver
his assessment of the vice presidential showdown, which he watched
at home.
   ``The most important qualification for a vice president is that
he's ready at a moment's notice to assume the presidency of the
United States,'' Dukakis told supporters waving American and Texas
flags. ``Tonight, Lloyd Bentsen demonstrated that he was the only
one on that stage who's ready.''
   Dukakis said he spoke to the Texas senator after the debate.
   ``I couldn't be prouder of him as my running mate,'' the
Massachusetts governor said. ``He's going to be a great vice
president.''
   Dukakis joined aides in claiming their man trounced Quayle,
particularly in demonstrating a grasp of the issues and showing
presidential confidence and leadership.
   ``What you saw was his strength, his maturity, his vision, his
toughness, his leadership _ all of the qualities that are so
important in a vice president and so important in a president, so
important to someone who is a heartbeat away from the presidency,''
Dukakis said. ``He's a great asset to our ticket.''
   The Democratic nominee also said the debate offered the voters a
chance to learn ``about how I make presidential decisions and the
way George Bush makes presidential decisions. My friends, tonight
that was no contest.''
   Dukakis said the Bentsen-Quayle debate, and his recent debate
with Bush, had helped focus the campaign on the ``real concerns of
mainstream Americans.'' That boded well for Democrats, he said.
   ``What is now beginning to happen is that with the American
people focused in on these two tickets, and on their concerns about
the future, they understand that this is a nation that is never
satisfied with the status quo and never will be. The reason we are
the greatest nation in the world is that we are always moving
forward, always trying to do better, always trying to build a
better future.''
   Dukakis then prompted a thunderous ovation by declaring: ``And
that's why we're going to win.''
   Later, he got the flags waving again by saying, ``On the 20th of
January 1989, the new era of greatness arrives.''
   Dukakis was back on the stump today after spending most of
Wednesday catching up on gubernatorial business.
   He took a break in the early afternoon to meet with reporters,
denouncing Bush's criticism of a Massachusetts furlough program
while dodging a question likely to come up during a Friday visit to
North Carolina _ whether he would have, like President Reagan,
vetoed legislation to protect the U.S. textile industry from
foreign competition.
   Bush has made his criticism of a Massachusetts furlough program
a staple of his campaign and has a new television ad accusing
Dukakis of running a ``revolving door'' prison system. At the
center of Bush's attacks is a case in which an inmate on furlough
raped a Maryland woman and assaulted her fiance.
   ``The vice president's record on crime and the fight against
drugs is pathetic,'' Dukakis said. ``It's been a failure and in my
judgment this is an effort to use the one case with a tragic
occurrence for political reasons. The vice president knows that the
federal government has a very extensive furlough program, knows
that Governor Reagan in California in the '70s had a very extensive
furlough program and tragedies as a result of that.''
   As for the textile bill, which would have placed strict new
limits on imports of textiles, apparel and shoes, Dukakis said he
favored legislation giving five years' protection to the industry
provided it agreed to modernize. There was no such provision in the
bill vetoed by Reagan but Dukakis said there would have been if he
was president.
   Dukakis refused to answer directly when asked whether he would
have signed the legislation as it was presented to Reagan.
   Dukakis also took to the airwaves with another round of ads,
four 30-second spots attacking Bush and his record on drug
enforcement, education, the environment and Social Security.
</TEXT>
