<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0486 10-06 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen's Verdict: `I Had Fun'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 10 grafs new with Bentsen comments en route to Texas;
picks up 4th graf, `Senator, you.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, heading to Texas for
a reunion with Michael Dukakis, pointed cheerfully today to polls
showing he won the debate with Republican Dan Quayle and said,
``Gee, those polls were great, weren't they?''
   Bentsen, stopping to speak with reporters as he left his hotel
this morning, also said he had been angered by Quayle's reference
to John F. Kennedy, which triggered the sharpest exchange of their
debate.
   The Texas senator and Democratic vice presidential nominee
disputed any suggestion that he had appeared nasty in his response
to Quayle over the Kennedy remark.
   ``What happened there was Quayle kept comparing himself to
Kennedy, and he overreached himself and I got fed up with it,''
Bentsen said.
   He pointed out that Kennedy was ``a war hero'' and had run a
nationwide campaign before being nominated president. Asked if he
was angered, he said, ``Sure, as a friend of Jack Kennedy, I deeply
resented his trying to put Kennedy's mantle over himself when he
didn't have a record that compared with Kennedy.''
   An Associated Press panel of veteran debate judges called
Bentsen the winner by a wide margin, and an instant ABC News poll
also gave the victory to the Democratic nominee.
   ``Gee, those polls were great weren't they... I was just
delighted,'' Bentsen said.
   ``I knew I was scoring points and I thought I was winning, but
it's difficult to be objective about yourself.''
   ``I had fun,'' the nominee said after his 90-minute televised
encounter with his Republican rival. ``I think we made our points.''
   Bentsen's principle point of the evening was his stinging retort
to Quayle's assertion that he has as much experience in Congress as
Kennedy had when he sought the presidency.
   ``Senator, you are no Jack Kennedy,'' Bentsen shot back at the
41-year-old junior senator from Indiana whose credentials have been
challenged since Bush selected him for the ticket.
   ``That was really uncalled for, senator,'' responded Quayle.
   Bentsen took a congratulatory phone call from Dukakis before
leaving Omaha Civic Auditorium after the debate, then spoke to 700
cheering supporters in a crowded hotel ballroom just down the
street.
   He made no mention of his remark on Kennedy, which was the
rhetorical and emotional high point of the contest. But he derided
Quayle for his handling of the repeated questioning he took on his
qualifications and what he would do if the presidency was thrust
upon him _ and he depicted Quayle as sticking close to his
advisers' coaching.
   ``You know, I stood up there for 90 minutes listening to Senator
Quayle say what he was going to do if he was president of the
United States and I still didn't know,'' Bentsen said.
   ``Finally I realized that all he was going to do was go back to
that script again.''
   Bentsen was making his first stop today at the Lone Star Steel
Co. near Longview in East Texas. Dukakis, who watched the debate
back home in Boston, was flying down to join him for the one
appearance. They were going their separate ways from there.
   Bentsen, added to the Democratic ticket amid hopes of carrying
giant Texas, was campaigning later in Dallas, and planned to stump
the state again Friday and Saturday as polls showed the Democratic
ticket trailing the Republicans in Texas by as many as 10
percentage points.
   As he left the debate site, Bentsen declined reporters' shouted
invitations to declare himself the winner. ``I think I did fine,
and I enjoyed it,'' he said.
   At the rally he stood before a banner that read ``and the winner
is Bentsen.'' He appealed to Democrats in the farm states of
Nebraska and, just across the Missouri River, Iowa, saying that
Quayle ``doesn't even know what they're talking about'' when farm
target prices are discussed.
   After days of intensive debate preparation, Bentsen tried to
relax Wednesday afternoon before the debate. The 67-year-old
senator displayed exhuberance in a pre-debate check of the
auditorium stage, lifting his wife, B.A., and carrying her off the
stage.
   Bentsen's debate jab at Quayle over his Kennedy comparison was
the object of much of the post-debate analysis or ``spinning,'' as
the partisan commentaries from both parties are called.
   His Democratic Senate colleagues chortled over the tense
exchange.
   ``I thought that was the knockout blow of the evening,'' said
California Sen. Alan Cranson.
   ``It was a devastating reply,'' said Louisiana Sen. Bennett
Johnston.
   But Republcan Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming sounded wounded,
saying: ``I think it was a cheap shot ... That was not the Lloyd
Bentsen I know.''
</TEXT>
