<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 3rdLd-Writethru a0597 10-06 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0597,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Belgrade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Provincial Communist Leaders Resign After Mass Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with AP estimate of crowd,
background on significance of move; PICKS up 5th graf pvs, `The
protesters ...' Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist leadership of the
northern province of Vojvodina said today it will resign. The
announcement came after 50,000 people rallied to demand the ouster
of the politicians in a deepening economic crisis.
   Milovan Sogorov, president of the Communist Party Central
Committee of Vojvodina, made the announcement in Belgrade at an
emergency session of the Communist Party of Serbia, which controls
the autonomous northern province, the official Tanjug news agency
reported.
   The Central Committee was to implement the resignations at an
emergency meeting this evening in this provincial capital, about 40
miles north of Belgrade, state television reported.
   The resignation could pave the way for wholesale changes in the
national Communist Party leadership and in the parties of
Yugoslavia's six constituent republics.
   Angry crowds in Novi Sad chanted ``We want resignations!'' as
they gathered in front of the Communist Party Central Committee
headquarters.
   The state news agency Tanjug estimated the crowds at 100,000,
but an Associated Press reporter at the scene estimated about
50,000 people were on the streets at midafternoon.
   The protesters tried to force their way into the party
headquarters, but cordons of police, including a riot unit, blocked
their way.
   The crowds then moved to a larger square. Loudspeakers broadcast
shouted slogans about Yugoslavia's growing problems, which includes
217 percent inflation, a 15 percent unemployment rate and a $21
billion foreign debt.
   The flag-waving demonstrators chanted ``Police go away!'' ``We
are going to smash windows!'' and ``We want freedom!'' and demanded
the immediate resignation of the provincial Communist leadership,
according to the witnesses.
   Communist officials who spoke were booed and jeered by the
crowd, and television showed one hit with a bottle.
   Most factories and businesses in the city remained closed.
   The Serbian Communist Party issued a statement after its
emergency meeting saying the political situation in Vojvodina was
deteriorating rapidly, according to Tanjug.
   ``The Vojvodina leadership has been deaf to the demands of the
working class and other citizens,'' the statement said, adding, ``a
serious split has occurred between the Vojvodina leadership and the
people.''
   The demonstrations in Novi Sad began about noon Wednesday and
continued into the night.
   Protesters also chanted in favor of Serbian Communist Party
leader Slobodan Milosevic, who is demanding that the republic of
Serbia be given stronger central authority over Vojvodina and
Kosovo, a second autonomous region under Serbia. Serbs claim ethnic
Albanians, who form a majority of the population of Kosovo, are
forcing them out of the southern province.
   The protests in Vojvodina began just after about 5,000 workers
marched on the federal Parliament in Belgrade on Wednesday to voice
their anger over the economic situation.
   In central Serbia, about 140,000 Serbs participated in two other
rallies Wednesday to press demands for greater Serbian control over
Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   The Novi Sad protesters, who support Milosevic's position, were
spurred by a decision taken by the Central Committe of Vojvodina to
reprimand two members who supported his views at an earlier rally,
Tanjug said. The head of Yugoslavia's Communist Party, Stipe Suvar,
said Tuesday that the party's 162-member Central Committee probably
will vote Oct. 17 for a shake-up in the leadership of the ruling
Politburo.
   Yugoslavia is facing its worst economic and political crisis
since World War II, and criticism of the communist leaders is
mounting for their failures to resolve the economic problems and to
defuse tension between the Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</TEXT>
