<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Quayle     10-06 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Quayle,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Accuses Bentsen of `Cheap Shot'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today accused Democrat LLoyd
Bentsen of ``a cheap shot ... unbecoming a senator of the United
States'' for criticizing Republican Dan Quayle for comparing
himself with John F. Kennedy.
   Reagan, posing for pictures with President Moussa Traore of
Mali, was asked by a reporter whether Quayle would be damaged by
being compared with the late president.
   ``No, I think that remark was a cheap shot and unbecoming a
senator of the United States,'' the president said.
   Another reporter asked if Quayle hadn't ``led with his chin'' in
comparing himself with Kennedy during his vice presidential debate
with Bentsen in Omaha, Neb., on Wednesday.
   ``No, the only comparison he was making was that he is being
attacked, I think unfairly, on the basis of his age and his
experience in government, and he was pointing out that John
Kennedy, who sought the highest office and won it, had actually
less experience in government than he has, and they were the same
age,'' Reagan replied.
   As White House aides ushered reporters out of the Oval Office,
Reagan called them back and said he did not believe that Quayle was
``trying in any way to downgrade Sen. Kennedy.''
   Quayle, 41, sparked one of the sharpest exchanges of the debate
when he said he had as much government experience as Kennedy, then
a senator from Massachusetts, when Kennedy ran for president in
1960.
   Bentsen, 67, replied, ``I served with Jack Kennedy. I knew Jack
Kennedy. Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine. Senator, you're no Jack
Kennedy.''
   Quayle shot back, ``That was really uncalled for, senator.''
Bentsen replied that it was Quayle who had made the comparison in
the first place.
</TEXT>
