<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarveyTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0588 10-06 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvey Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0588,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Took Over School Says He Had Right To Bear Arms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony; Picks up
3rd graf, ``I didn't ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tuscaloosa police officer testified
today that a man accused of taking 110 people hostage at a private
school was armed with a rifle every time he saw him through the
front door of the building.
   James L. Harvey, the defendant who is representing himself at
his trial on kidnapping charges, asked Capt. Shirley Fields whether
he saw Harvey ever point the weapon at children inside West End
Christian School at Tuscaloosa.
   ``Not directly at them, but you had it ready,'' Fields said.
   The defendant then asked him whether he thought Harvey's life
might have been in danger and whether that could have been the
reason he had the weapon. Fields said that could have been the case.
   In his opening statement to the jury Wednesday, Harvey, 43,
defended his takeover of the school on Feb. 2 by saying the U.S.
Constitution gives him the right to bear arms.
   ``I didn't kidnap anybody,'' the unemployed Tuscaloosa resident
told jurors. ``I went there to exercise my constitutional rights.
The government is doing things to destroy the future of our
country.''
   Harvey has said he took over the school to call attention to the
homeless and hungry in America. His trial was moved to Huntsville
because of publicity in Tuscaloosa.
   He began his defense after District Attorney Charles Freeman
told the jury that ``children and teachers were in stark, cold
terror for endless hours'' during the incident.
   The 110 counts involve 104 students, five teachers and John
Rhodes Jr., a man Harvey is accused of duping into helping seize
the school. Rhodes was initially charged in the takeover, but
authorities later said he was an unwilling participant.
   All the students, teachers and Rhodes, plus officers and the
school's headmaster, Dan Carden, are among the 137 people
subpoenaed to testify at the trial, which Circuit Judge John M.
Karrh said probably will last from five to seven days.
   Also summoned was Gov. Guy Hunt, who is to testify Friday about
a bogus pardon he videotaped that led Harvey to surrender 12 hours
after he entered the elementary school, armed with a high-caliber
rifle, two loaded automatic pistols and 2,000 rounds of ammunition,
plus two unloaded guns he handed to Rhodes as they entered the
school.
   ``I have a constitutional right to bear arms,'' Harvey said. ``I
went there to prove my right to bear arms. ... I didn't mean to
hurt anyone.''
   In a rambling discourse, he told the jury that politicians don't
tell the truth, that people are poisoning water and air, that
``we're selling our children's futures'' with the national debt.
   During the siege, he said, he told officers who tried to
dissuade him that ``this is not a criminal act. It is a political
act.''
   In fact, Harvey said, because the school was surrounded by
officers, ``I felt like a hostage. It could have ended in five
hours. They put me through psychological warfare.''
   Assistant prosecutor Thomas Smith told jurors that a first-grade
class went from 8:30 a.m., when Harvey entered the school, until
1:46 p.m. ``with no food, no restroom, no water, no nothing.''
   During the siege, Smith said, Harvey ``always had children
around him so he wouldn't get shot. He was using them as shields as
well as hostages. ... He is certainly guilty of all counts of
kidnapping.''
   If convicted on all counts, Harvey could be sentenced to more
than 10,000 years in prison.
</TEXT>
