<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-China     10-06 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-China,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese-Soviet Summit Planned Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will hold a summit
with Chinese leaders early next year, a Kremlin diplomat said today.
   Igor A. Rogachev, a deputy foreign minister who is the Soviets'
point man in contacts with the Chinese, was asked at a news
conference whether a Soviet-Chinese summit will follow a meeting
this year between the two countries' foreign ministers.
   He also was asked whether the summit would occur in the first
half of next year, as news reports from Shanghai have indicated.
   ``My sense is that one might be in a position to suggest that
both would be the case,'' Rogachev replied.
   Relations have been strained between the two communist giants
since the 1960s, and the last Chinese summit was held in 1959
between Nikita S. Khrushchev and Mao Tse-tung.
   Gorbachev, who is also the Soviet Communist Party chief, has
made several overtures to China to remove obstacles to improving
relations. He has ordered a pullout of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan, reduced Soviet troops on the border with China, and
agreed in August to the first direct talks with the Chinese about
the Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia.
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Quichen met with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze in New York last month, and Quian
is to travel to Moscow later this year. No date has been set.
   Rogachev said the Cambodia conflict, in which the Soviet Union
supports Vietnam's occupation, will be high on the agenda for the
Moscow talks.
   Rogachev, who represented the Kremlin in the talks with the
Chinese on Cambodia, did not say whether Gorbachev would travel to
Beijing or whether Chinese leaders would come to Moscow.
   Gorbachev renewed the idea of a summit with China in a speech in
the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk Sept. 16.
</TEXT>
