<HEAD>Three Rescue Boats Capsized: 19 Feared Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 people were reported
killed Thursday in flooding that has ravaged thousands of Pakistani
villages, and another 59 people were feared drowned after four
rescue boats sank.
   Police said 19 people were believed killed Wednesday when three
army boats shuttling people from their flooded homes sank. On
Tuesday, another rescue boat sank and 40 people were believed to
have drowned, officials said.
   In addition, another 104 people are known to have drowned in the
flooding, which began two weeks ago. Police said more than 100
people are missing.
   According to government figures, the flooding has affected more
than 3 million people and 4,000 villages, mainly in the eastern
province of Punjab.
   The flooding began after heavy rains sent the Sutlej, Ravi and
Chenab rivers over their banks.
   Medical officials near the ancient Punjab capital of Lahore have
warned of an epidemic of skin diseases in the affected areas
because of the lack of sanitation.
   Relief centers have sprung up throughout the province providing
food and clean drinking water. Officials said thousands have been
vaccinated against typhoid and cholera.
