<2ND_LINE>AM-Siamese Twins,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7-Year-Old Siamese Twins Doing Well After Separation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese Siamese twins were reported doing well
Thursday after being separated in a 14-hour operation.
   A 72-member medical team operated on the 7-year-old twins, Viet
and Duc, at Tu Du Hospital in Ho Chi Minh City on Tuesday.
   Viet and Duc were ``in very good condition,'' said Yoshiaki
Nemoto, spokesman for the Japanese Red Cross, which provided most
of the medical equipment for the operation. The twins' vital
readings were stable, Nemoto said.
   Kyodo News Service quoted a Vietnamese doctor in Ho Chi Minh
City as saying that the twins were given tranquilizers and pain
killers and were asleep most of time. But he said it would take
about a week to judge the success of the operation, Kyodo said.
   The twins were joined at the pelvis and shared genitals and a
single pair of legs, one bowel, an anus, a bladder, and a pair of
kidneys.
   Each twin received one leg, while the organs went to Duc, the
more healthy of the two, Japanese news media reported. Viet has
been comatose since May 1986.
   Vietnamese officials have said the number of Siamese twins in
their country rose after American use of defoliants known to
produce birth defects during the Vietnam War, including in the
central highlands where Viet and Duc were born in February 1981.
</TEXT>
