<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Stage Violent Protest In Government Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police arrested a group of
radical students who stormed a government office with iron pipes
and firebombs and shouted anti-American and anti-government slogans.
   At least two students were reported seriously injured when
police broke into the office to stop the two-hour protest.
   Police said 23 students from eight universities in Seoul
overpowered security guards and charged into Parliamentary Hall, a
legislative office building near the National Assembly building.
All were arrested.
   The students demanded immediate punishment of former President
Chun Doo-hwan, who has been under investigation for alleged
corruption and brutality.
   The students broke windows and unfolded a giant placard that
read ``Drive out Yankees'' and ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan and his
wife.''
   The radicals locked themselves inside the fourth-floor office of
Chung Ho-yong, a senior member of the governing Democratic Justice
Party, and tossed out papers, chairs and a portrait of President
Roh Tae-woo. Chung was not in the office.
   Dissidents charge that Chung, a former army general, played a
role in supressing a 1980 uprising in the southern city of Kwangju
in which nearly 200 people were killed.
   Hundreds of riot police backed by firetrucks surrounded the
building and spread mattresses on the ground to prevent suicide
attempts by students who threatened to burn the office or jump from
windows if police intervened.
   One student cut his stomach with a razor when about 100 police
officers broke through the office door to end the seizure,
according to witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Another protester jumped from the window and was taken to the
hospital, where he was reported in stable condition. One of Chung's
aides and several policemen were also hurt, the South Korean news
agency Yonhap said.
   Leaflets scattered by the students criticized the United States,
which the dissidents say supports the division of the Korean
Peninsula. The students are demanding the withdrawal of about
42,000 American troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual
defense pact.
   Also Thursday, about 500 students at Seoul's Dongkuk University
battled riot police with firebombs and rocks after an
anti-government rally.
</TEXT>
