<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthKorea-Olympics     10-06 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Korea-Olympics,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympics Are Over, But North Korea Continues To Blast Games</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Thursday continued its verbal
attacks on the Olympic Games in Seoul, calling them ``dictatorial''
and an excuse for suppression of popular protest.
   The government in Pyongyang also accused the United States of
using the Olympics to keep the Korean Peninsula divided. The Games,
which began Sept. 17, ended Sunday.
   ``Facts vividly show how strongly the divisive Olympics, the
dictatorial Olympics, induced by the U.S. imperialists and their
stooges into Seoul, was rejected by the people,'' the
government-run Korean Central News Agency said.
   The report was monitored in Tokyo.
   North Korea demanded to be a co-host at the Games. The
International Olympic Committee said the Games are given to a
single city and cannot be shared.
   North Korea has been charging for months that South Korea and
the United States were scheming to use the Olympics to permanently
divide the Korean Peninsula, split into capitalist South and
communist North since 1945.
   ``The U.S. imperialists' `two Koreas' plot has become more
pronounced nowadays,'' the Minju Chosun, a state-run newspaper,
said last week.
   ``It is proved by the fact that they ... are employing
despicable means to take this opportunity to create an atmosphere
for creating `two Koreas.' ''
   South Korean officials had said they believed North Korea would
stage terrorist attacks on the South to disrupt the Games and set
up tight security, but no incidents occurred.
   The U.S. Navy conducted exercises near the peninsula to prevent
terrorist attacks.
   The North Korean news agency branded the tight security as
``suppression.''
   ``The fascist clique are intensifying suppression, calling
people's protests against the dictatorial Olympics a `dangerous
act,' '' the agency said. ``Subsequently, Seoul is now in a more
horrible atmosphere.''
   The newspaper Rodong Sinmun, the official organ of the Workers
Party of Korea, said the same day that ``the U.S. imperialists, on
the plea of `Olympic safety,' sent carrier flotillas and many other
aggression forces to and around South Korea to resort to a nuclear
blackmail.''
   Radical students in Seoul, opposed to what they see as U.S.
support for an unpopular government, had threatened to disrupt the
Games' last event, the men's marathon, and there was visible
security in place.
   ``The marathon, which is usually held amid enthusiastic cheers
of crowds, was held in Seoul in a horrifying atmosphere, the police
lining the route instead of cheering crowds,'' the news agency said.
   ``It was not a race but a torturous experience for the
marathoners who had to run through the narrow corridor of police
walls.''
</TEXT>
