<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Killings     10-06 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Killings,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Probe of Alleged Massacre Inconclusive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
said investigations into the alleged slayings of 10 peasants by
soldiers were inconclusive, and he ordered that the matter be
studied further.
   As Duarte spoke with journalists Wednesday, forensic specialists
exhumed the bodies of seven of 10 people killed Sept. 21 in San
Francisco, 30 miles east of San Salvador.
   Forensic physician Roberto Maldonado told reporters after the
first three bodies were pulled from the mass grave that powder
burns indicated they were shot from six inches away.
   The bodies of three other people killed Sept. 21 were buried in
nearby San Sebastian and were to be exhumed later.
   Relatives and neighbors of the seven men and three women slain
said they were killed by soldiers of the Jiboa Battalion after most
of the town's residents were detained on suspicion of collaborating
with leftist guerrillas.
   The army said eight villagers were detained but that they were
killed when guerrillas ambushed the army unit taking them to a base
for interrogation.
   No soldier was killed in the alleged ambush, the army said. It
said two attacking guerrillas were killed.
   Duarte said he had received four reports on the killings _ from
a human rights commission, the attorney general's office, the armed
forces and the office of the Roman Catholic archbishop of San
Salvador.
   ``I am still studying the case, but until now none of the
documents provides sufficient criteria. I have asked the attorney
general's office and the armed forces to deepen their
investigations,'' Duarte said.
   Leftist rebels have fought a 9-year-old civil war against the
U.S.-backed government.
   The army has not been accused of civilian killings on the scale
of the San Francisco killings in four years.
   Also Wednesday, about 300 National University students marched
through downtown San Salvador with a coffin containing the body of
a university security guard slain Monday.
   The state university, in a statement, said guard Raul Santos
Escamilla, 34, was shot by two men in a university cafeteria.
   ``This criminal act is part of the government and military
campaign against the university's just struggles,'' the communique
said.
   The military considers the National University a stronghold of
guerrilla supporters.
   Santos had been detained for three days last year by National
Police on suspicion of guerrilla collaboration. He was released for
lack of evidence.
</TEXT>
