<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Interstate,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montana Completes Its Interstate Highways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana has become the 16th state to
complete its portion of the interstate highway system, bridging a
3{-mile gap that confounded engineers for nearly 20 years,
officials said.
   Construction workers last week completed Interstate 15 south of
Dillon, near the Idaho border. Work on the last gap in Montana's
1,200-mile, 30-year, $1.2 billion program began in the 1960s but
triggered a slow earth slide.
   ``About once a month, we went down, stood on it and looked wise,
and tried to figure out what the hell to do with this mountain,''
said Dave Johnson, state engineering specialty supervisor.
   The problem was solved by boring holes and draining away the
water lubricating the earth slide, and construction resumed in the
early 1980s.
</TEXT>
