<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     10-06 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamas And PLO Call Truce; Two Suspected Collaborators Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem fundamentalists announced a truce
Thursday in their power struggle with pro-PLO leaders. Assailants
killed two Palestinians suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   The truce ended a rift that threatened to undermine the nearly
10-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``We must be united despite the differences in our beliefs,''
the Moslem fundamentalist group Hamas said in leaflets distributed
Thursday. ``We are against any kind of split.''
   A Hamas leader, speaking on condition of anonymity, said his
group and the PLO-backed Unified National Leadership of the
Uprising agreed to coordinate general strikes, stop street fighting
between the two groups and end the ``graffiti war'' of defamatory
slogans aimed at each other.
   ``When we fight each other we are only helping the enemy
(Israel),'' said the bearded 25-year-old Hamas leader in an
interview.
   Hamas advocates destruction of Israel and is politically at odds
with PLO chief Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction, which is considering
recognition of the Jewish state.
   A Palestine Liberation Organization official in Nicosia, Cyprus,
confirmed that meetings with Hamas took place but would not
elaborate. The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Since the start of the uprising, Hamas has repeatedly challenged
the Unified Leadership, which is made up of various PLO factions.
Last month, a successful general strike called by Hamas in defiance
of the PLO sparked fistfights between rival activists.
   Also Thursday, assailants killed Mustafa Salim Abu Bakr, 46, a
mukhtar, or traditional leader, in the West Bank village of Biddya.
They suspected him of selling village land to Israelis.
   Bakr was driving in his car with his two sons, ages 8 and 14,
when assailants in Biddya blocked the road with burning tires,
witnesses said.
   The gunmen opened fire, killing Bakr and wounding his two sons.
The assailants set Bakr's body on fire after the attack, witnesses
said.
   The army confirmed the death and clamped a curfew on Biddya, 45
miles north of Jerusalem. The radio said troops arrested several
Palestinians.
   The second victim, 25-year-old Ahmed Sahour, was sprayed with
gunfire in a cafe in the Israeli Arab village of Umm El Fahm, where
he had been hiding since being chased out of the nearby West Bank
village of Amin, the radio and Arab witnesses said.
   The deaths brought to 283 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8. Of those, nine were suspected
collaborators. Six Israelis have been killed.
   Also Thursday, six Palestinians were wounded in clashes with
troops, five of them in the Gaza Strip and one in the West Bank,
Arab hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed two wounded in the Gaza Strip and said it was
checking the other reports.
</TEXT>
