<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Children     10-06 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Children,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Care for AIDS Children Tops $90,000, Much Unnecessary:
Studies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children infected with the virus that causes AIDS
are running up hospital bills of more than $90,000 each, often
because they simply have nowhere else to go, studies indicate.
   ``Many of these children are in the hospital not because they're
sick with AIDS or with anything else,'' said Dr. Kathi Kemper, who
examined cases of children testing positive for evidence of AIDS
infection at Yale-New Haven Hospital in Connecticut.
   ``But because they test positive, nobody wants to take care of
them at home or in foster care, and so there's no place else for
them to go,'' she said in a telephone interview Thursday.
``Basically, they're in the hospital like a day-care center.''
   Home lives of such babies tend to be chaotic because the mothers
who transmitted the virus to them usually are intravenous drug
abusers, often sick themselves and possibly in jail, researchers
said.
   A significant number of babies who test positive aren't even
infected _ they simply are carrying AIDS antibodies they inherited
from their mothers, said Ms. Kemper, now with Harborview Medical
Center in Seattle, Wash.
   AIDS antibodies _ natural disease-fighting agents produced by a
person's system in the face of AIDS infection _ fade from
uninfected babies' bloodstreams by age 6 months to 15 months, she
said. All AIDS tests in current use detect antibodies to the virus,
rather than the virus itself.
   Even youngsters who really are sick often are put in the
hospital or kept there unnecessarily, Ms. Kemper said. ``Some of
them easily could be getting treatment on an outpatient basis.''
   Yet potential foster families often fear they might catch AIDS _
a remote possibility _ and insurance and Medicaid policies are set
up to reimburse for hospital care more efficiently than for
outpatient or home care, she said.
   By Sept. 26, the federal Centers for Disease Control had
recorded 1,185 cases of AIDS among children under age 13, of whom
672 had died. Medical researchers have estimated that 10,000
children could be infected by 1991.
   The study by Ms. Kemper and colleague Brian Forsyth, published
in Friday's Journal of the American Medical Association, looked at
children who had tested positive for AIDS antibodies at Yale-New
Haven Hospital through Oct. 31, 1987.
   ``Among children eligible for the study, 54 percent of their
hospital days were judged medically unnecessary,'' the study said.
   The most common non-medical reason for hospitalization was lack
of any other place to send the child, it said.
   A related study in Friday's Journal found that hospital stays
for children infected with the AIDS virus ranged from $466 per day
for ``boarder babies'' _ those who simply had nowhere else to go _
to $705 per day for the sickest youngsters.
   That study, led by James D. Hegarty of Harlem Hospital Center in
New York, looked at 37 children diagnosed with AIDS or an
AIDS-related condition in that hospital from 1981 through 1986.
   ``Average lifetime costs were $90,347 per child,'' the study
said. ``One third of the total inpatient days and over 20 percent
of the cost resulted from social rather than medical factors.''
   Ms. Kemper called for better education and better reimbursement
for potential foster parents and modified policies under the
Medicaid program and private insurance plans.
   She noted that Connecticut waged a foster-parent education
campaign and boosted reimbursement to $1,000 a month for foster
families, helping reduce the rate of unnecessary hospital days from
64 percent in 1983 and 1984 to 30 percent in 1987 for the children
studied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
