<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForestDonations     10-06 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Donations,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fund Created to Help Restore Yellowstone Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund has been set to handle donations to
help the Yellowstone National Park area recover from this summer's
devastating fires, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the department's Forest Service,
said the Greater Yellowstone Area Recovery Fund has been
established in response to offers from individuals and groups
wishing to make donations.
   Thirteen major fires burned 1.6 million acres in the greater
Yellowstone area, including 566,508 acres on national forests,
including parts of Wyoming, Idaho and Montana.
   Robertson said the donations will be used for cleanup operations
and to collect local seed, grow seedlings, plant trees, control
erosion and repair damaged facilities.
   ``We also have received many offers of seeds and seedlings,'' he
said. ``Unfortunately, we usually cannot accept these because the
tree species offered is not native to the local area and would not
survive.''
   Donations can be sent to: Forest Service, 11177 West 8th Ave.,
Lakewood, Colo. 80225-0127. Checks should be made out to
``USDA-Forest Service,'' and ``Greater Yellowstone Area Recovery
Fund'' should be specified on the check.
   Those wishing to donate to help fire recovery on national
forests in other areas of the country may do so by contacting the
Forest Service's public affairs office in Washington, D.C., or
individual national forests.
   The public affairs office address is P.O. Box 96090, Washington,
D.C. 20090-6090. The telephone number is 202-447-3760.
</TEXT>
