<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FTC-Political     10-06 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Political,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Political-Letter Battle Flares on Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Trade Commission staffer, in hot
water over some politically oriented letters he sent out, told a
House subcommittee Thursday that he was just doing what he thought
was expected.
   Carter L. Clews, who was fired from the FTC and then reinstated
pending a formal investigation of his activities, admitted sending
letters to the news media critical of statements made by Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis.
   ``I had simply tried to do my job as I understood it,'' Clews
said.
   He told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee that the
letters he sent out had been seen by his superiors at the agency's
press office before they were dispatched.
   Anna H. Davis, director of the FTC Office of Public Affairs,
denied that, saying that the problem was in a postscript Clews
added to one letter without her knowledge, and that other letters
he sent out were not authorized at all.
   The letters were sent to broadcasters and newspapers in an
effort to counter a statement by Dukakis that the FTC's antitrust
efforts had been a joke.
   In the letters, Clews challenged that statement and offered the
services of commission members for interviews to discuss the
agency's activities and Dukakis' remarks. That drew a challenge
from two commissioners, Democrat Andrew Strenio and independent
Mary Azcuenaga, who questioned whether the letters violated the
Hatch Act, which bans political activities by federal workers.
   Clews then left the commission after being given a choice of
resigning or being fired, he testified. But he later complained
that his resignation had come under duress, so he was returned to
the payroll pending an investigation. He is currently on
administrative leave.
   Mrs. Davis testified that one letter, sent to 800 talk show
hosts across the nation, had been approved by agency officials, but
that Clews subsequently added a postscript on his own and got a
commission intern to sign Mrs. Davis' name.
   Clews told the subcommittee on oversignt and investigation that
the intern signed the letter because Mrs. Davis had approved it but
was out of town at the time it had to be printed. As for the
postscript, he said he assumed Mrs. Davis was aware of it because
she was present when the letter was placed in envelopes for mailing.
   A second letter questioning Dukakis' statements was sent to
several columnists, carrying Clews' signature. He contended that
Mrs. Davis had seen that letter in advance, but she denied that and
testified that Clews had sent that out on his own, avoiding normal
clearance procedures.
   A third letter offering to respond to Dukakis was sent to
Washington news bureau chiefs under Mrs. Davis' signature.
   Clews testified that he had written that letter also and sent it
to Mrs. Davis, who he said signed it. In her statement, however,
Mrs. Davis said, ``While the signature is very similar to mine, I
did not sign it, nor do I know who signed it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
