<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--BootleggingSentence     10-06 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bootlegging Sentence,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Sheriff Sentenced to Four Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former sheriff who admitted taking
payoffs to protect bootleggers in his dry county was sentenced
Thursday to a four-year prison term and a $5,000 fine.
   Former Scott County Sheriff Glen Warren, 54, and former Chief
Deputy Will Reed, 43, had pleaded guilty to two counts of extortion
each. They acknowledged taking payoffs from bootleggers in exchange
for protecting them from raids by agents from the Alcoholic
Beverage Control Division of the state Tax Commission.
   Reed, who said he acted at Warren's biding, was sentenced to one
year in jail by U.S. District Judge Henry T. Wingate, who also
fined him $2,500.
   The maximum penalty Warren and Reed could have received was 40
years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
   Five bootleggers pleaded guilty to perjury charges after they
lied to a federal grand jury investigating payoffs.
   Warren, who had been in office for eight years, sought
re-election but lost to retired state Trooper William S. Richardson
last year.
</TEXT>
