<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-06 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   April Fools' Day only comes once a year,
so people with a semiannual urge for silliness should welcome Dick
Dunn's campaign to make Oct. 6 Mad Hatter Day.
   ``Outrageous statements and non sequiturs are the order of the
day,'' Dunn, a computer worker at Interactive Systems, wrote in a
letter to the Boulder Daily Camera newspaper.
   In the tradition of such Boulder events as kinetic sculptures
and harmonic convergences, Mad Hatter Day _ named in honor of the
befuddled fellow in Lewis Carroll's ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland'' _ was born one day in 1986 after Dunn spent hours
hacking away at his keyboard.
   Dunn, 39, said he chose Oct. 6 because Sir John Tenniel's
classic illustrations of Carroll's stories show the Mad Hatter in a
top hat with a slip stuck in the band noting: ``In this style _
10-6.'' The slip actually notes a hat order and price, but Dunn
decided the corresponding calendar date would be appropriate for
his holiday.
   He concedes the word of the holiday has been slow in spreading,
but he has garnered some support from local officials.
   Boulder city spokesman David Grimm said he was game to
contribute some silliness.
   ``I do that every day,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAVAGE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is a student of Savage Elementary a wild
child?
   Parents seeking to a different name for the town's only
elementary school say the current one gives students an
undeservedly raucous reputation. But those behind a ``save Savage''
effort say they seek to preserve the memory of local entrepreneur
M.W. Savage.
   The name is particularly hard on Savage Elementary youngsters
who go on to school elsewhere, said School Board Chairman Larry
Carlberg. ``They're known as the Savage kids,'' he said.
   But a recent bid to change the name has raised the rankles of
old-timers and history buffs in this town of 8,000 people. With the
backing of the City Council, American Legion and Chamber of
Commerce, the ``save Savage'' effort has gathered 731 signatures
opposing the change.
   ``I've gone to school there. We have two sons that also went to
school there,'' said Carol Gutoske, who's lived in Savage for 40
years. ``Nobody I talked to thought it was detrimental.''
   The town's name dates to the early 1900s, when M.W. Savage
gained widespread fame for the success of his harness-racing horse,
Dan Patch. He built a horse training farm, a racetrack and an
electric railway in Savage, gradually reshaping the Minnesota River
town's image.
   The town's name was changed from Hamilton to Savage in his honor.
   Supporters of the name change said they never meant to create
such controversy.
   ``Our purpose is not to divide the community or anything like
that,'' said Mary Eichen, president of the parent-teacher
organization. ``It's just something we thought would be a good
idea.''
   The school board is expected to vote on the matter later this
month.
</TEXT>
