<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gleason-Books     10-06 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gleason-Books,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gleason Book Collection Reveals Taste For Supernatural</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackie Gleason's reading tastes leaned heavily
toward offbeat subjects like UFOs, parapsychology and the occult _
1,700 of 3,700 volumes in the late comedian's collection of books
dealt with those topics.
   The collection has been donated by Gleason's widow, Marilyn, to
the University of Miami library. The actor best known as the
blowhard bus driver Ralph Kramden on television's ``The
Honeymooners'' died last year at age 71.
   ``Some of these books are kind of crackpot. Things like, `I Rode
in a Spaceship,''' UM librarian Jay Kalvan said. ``He went out of
his way to collect books on the occult. He was just personally
interested in any unexplained phenomenon. He didn't just collect
it, he read it.''
   After cataloging, the collection will be available for
inspection by the public by appointment.
   Frank Rodgers, director of UM libraries, said Mrs. Gleason
donated the collection in recognition of his longtime association
with Miami. Gleason did his TV variety show live from Miami Beach
for many years.
   ``She wanted them to stay in this community,'' Rodgers said.
``And we're delighted she came to that decision.''
   Gleason friend Hank Meyer, the publicist who lured Gleason's
show to Miami Beach in the 1950s, said the books reflect a
little-known side of the comic.
   ``That flamboyant image he had, that wasn't Jackie,'' Meyer
said. ``He was really very quiet, serious and introspective.'' The
publicist said Gleason was a ``voracious'' reader who went through
three or four books a week.
   ``He was a very bright person and he had a photographic
memory,'' he said. ``He would recall every passage he read. That's
why he never rehearsed (scenes from his shows). He'd read a script
once and have it memorized.''
</TEXT>
