<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HostageBirthday     10-06 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Birthday,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister Hopes Country Stars Will Sign Card</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of the longest-held Middle
East hostage is asking Hank Williams Jr. and other country music
stars to sign a birthday card to cheer her brother during captivity.
   Peggy Say is asking performers to sign the 1{- by 2-foot card
during rehearsals for Monday's 22nd annual Country Music
Association awards show.
   Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, was abducted March 16, 1985. He will be 41 on
Oct. 27.
   The card will read: ``Happy birthday Terry from Music City, USA.
We love you and are praying for your freedom.''
   ``I've asked particularly to have Hank Williams Jr. sign it
because he is Terry's favorite,'' Mrs. Say said from her home in
Cadiz, Ky.
   She said the card would be displayed at a ceremony on Anderson's
birthday, and details would be released to newspapers in Beirut,
Lebanon, in hopes of reaching her brother.
   ``Hopefully Terry will see it and know that he's truly not
forgotten,'' Mrs. Say said.
   A spokesman for the State Department said the government does
not foresee immediate freedom for other hostages following a
captive's release earlier this week.
   Mithileshwar Singh, a 60-year-old Indian citizen and resident
alien of the United States, was in good spirits following his
release Monday after 20 months of captivity.
   A group calling itself Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of
Palestine claimed responsibility for Singh's kidnapping and said it
freed him as a goodwill gesture.
   His release raised hopes for the freedom of the 16 foreign
hostages still held in Lebanon.
   Mrs. Say said she expected her brother to be released by the end
of the year. She did not indicate, however, that she had any
specific information about an impending release.
   The latest word on Anderson's condition came from Marcel
Fontaine, a French hostage released in May, according to Mrs. Say.
   ``He said that Terry was strong and determined to survive, that
Terry felt it would be the U.S. election before he would get out
and that he was gearing for that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
