<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Reconciliation     10-06 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Reconciliation,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Preaches Reconciliation as Guerrillas Step Up Attacks
on Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-supported government on
Thursday strongly advocated reconciliation with Islamic guerrillas
after a recent escalation of rocket attacks on the capital.
   ``A concerted effort of all mentalities and from all walks of
life is urgently needed,'' Vice President Abdul Rahim Hatif said in
an interview during the two-hour flight from New Delhi to Kabul.
   Government press center staffers said the Central Committee of
the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan would meet Monday to
discuss ``important matters,'' including efforts to bring the
guerrillas into a dialogue with the government.
   Hatif, who said he was not a party member, is one of four vice
presidents named by President Najib four months ago in a show of
broadening the base of his government.
   However, key positions in the government _ including the
presidency _ are held by the party or by politicians closely
associated with it.
   The guerrillas, who call themselves Mujahedeen or Islamic Holy
Warriors, have steadfastly refused to deal with Najib's government.
   Although the Soviet Union has withdrawn about half the 115,000
troops deployed in Afghanistan in the past five months, the Soviet
presence is still heavy in Kabul, the capital.
   But the Soviet armor and aircraft have not deterred rocket
attacks on the city.
   On Wednesday morning, 42 rockets hit Kabul in less than three
hours, killing 13 people and wounding 34, according to Qurban
Shayrzad, the city's deputy police chief
   On Sept. 28, at least 33 people were killed and more than 130
wounded in the worst round of rocket attacks on Kabul in recent
memory. Most of the casualties were caused in a single attack at a
crowded bus stop.
   In an interview with Western reporters, Shayrzad blamed all the
attacks on the guerrillas.
   The opinion in the streets, however, seems less certain.
   Several Kabul civilians, speaking on condition of anonymity,
expressed belief that some of the rockets were fired by Soviet or
Afghan troops who blamed the guerrillas in an effort to alienate
support for them.
   Vice President Hatif said he thought a variety of political
views, including those of the guerrillas, should be represented in
the government. But he said he could not envision an interim
government without the People's Democratic Government Party.
   Diego Cordovez, special U.N. envoy for Afghan affairs, last
month in New York proposed creation of an interim government
composed of impartial Afghans, including those both in the country
and abroad.
   Hatif, a 63-year-old businessman, said any government should
have both public support and the means to defend itself.
   Referring to Cordovez's proposal, he asked: ``How would it be
possible for those people who have no public support to implement
their decisions? How would it be possible (for them) to come
between two warring parties?''
   He called the guerrillas ``irresponsible people with complicated
weapons,'' and he accused Pakistan and the United States of
continuing to arm the guerrillas even though the Soviet withdrawal
was half completed.
   Under terms of an April 14 agreement signed in Geneva,
Afghanistan and Pakistan pledged to stop interfering in each
other's domestic affairs. The United States and the Soviet Union
signed as guarantors of the accord, which calls for all Soviet
troops to leave Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   On Thursday, Kabul police escorted three Western reporters to
homes they said were hit by guerrilla rockets the previous day.
   The first house was occupied by a soldier, Mohammad Shah, who
said four women and one boy in his family were killed when a rocket
hit the wall around their home on the north edge of Kabul.
   At another house in the nearby Wazirabad neighborhood, four
girls between the ages of 2 and 9 were killed by a rocket,
according to their uncle, Mohammad Karim. Karim said he was a
political officer of the Sarandoy, a paramilitary police force.
</TEXT>
