<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherShot     10-06 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Shot,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Shot By Sister In Classroom As Children Watch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parochial school teacher was shot and
seriously wounded Thursday when her sister entered the classroom,
told about 10 children to move back, then opened fire, police and
witnesses said.
   No children in the sixth-grade classroom at Most Pure Heart of
Mary School were hit.
   Police said the wounded teacher, Angela Jean Brown, 35, was hit
at least once in the midsection as several shots were fired from a
pistol. She was taken to Mobile Infirmary, where she was listed in
serious but stable condition.
   Less than an hour after the shooting, the teacher's sister,
Arilyn Jean Lelande, 29, was charged with first-degree assault,
Sgt. Lester Clark said.
   The shooting stemmed from ``an ongoing domestic problem between
the two sisters,'' Clark said. ``It wasn't anything like somebody
walking off the street.''
   The pupils said the woman with the gun told them to ``get back''
before turning to Mrs. Brown, who was seated at her desk. ``I want
my money,'' the children quoted the woman as saying before firing.
   ``I saw the children running and crying,'' said Patsy McDell, a
traffic officer at the school. ``I went to them and they told me
the teacher had been shot.''
   ``I saw the car speed out of the road with a woman driving. She
almost hit two kids,'' Mrs. McDell said.
   Police Sgt. James Mayo spotted Miss Lelande driving a few blocks
away from the school. ``I stopped her,'' he said. ``She got out of
the car, handed me the gun, which was still cocked and loaded, and
said, `Here it is.'''
   ``She asked me not to leave her car in the street, to have it
towed in because people in the neighborhood would tear it up,''
Mayo said.
   The first officer to arrive at the scene of the shooting,
Richard Henebry, said the teacher was conscious and told him, ``My
sister shot me.''
   Officials at the Roman Catholic school, which has an enrollment
of 180 in grades one through eight, said most children were
returned to the school later in the morning, but classes were
called off for some.
   There have been at least four shooting incidents at the nation's
schools in recent months, including three in the last month. Also,
trial began Wednesday in Huntsville for James Harvey, an unemployed
man defending himself on 110 kidnap counts for a 12-hour siege of a
private school in Tuscaloosa last February. Harvey told the jury he
was exercising his right to bear arms.
   On Monday, a gunman shot into an elementary school playground in
Mascotte, Fla., and wounded a third-grade student before
disappearing into the woods.
   On Sept. 26, a gunman at an elementary school in Greenwood,
S.C., wounded nine pupils, two fatally, and two teachers, before
being captured.
   Four days earlier, a man described by friends and relatives as
emotionally disturbed since serving in Vietnam stalked through an
auto parts store and a Chicago school, killing four people and
injuring two before being shot to death.
   On May 20 in the Chicago suburb of Winnetka, Ill., a mentally
disturbed woman, Laurie Dann, shot to death one youngster and
wounded five at an elementary school, then wounded a man at a
nearby house before taking her own life.
</TEXT>
