<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UnderageSailor     10-06 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Underage Sailor,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OK Benefits For Underage War Hero</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calvin Graham said Thursday that a weight was
lifted from his heart when the House voted to give him back pay and
benefits denied by the Navy because he lied about his age and
enlisted during World War II when he was only 12.
   But Graham, who was injured aboard the USS South Dakota during
the battle of Guadalcanal, says he's still crossing his fingers
that the legislation will clear the Senate before it adjourns for
the year _ possibly as soon as next week.
   ``It's not that much money,'' he said from his home in Fort
Worth, Texas. ``It's the pride of the thing to me _ that would be
worth a lot to me.''
   Graham was discharged from the military 45 years ago when he
returned from the Pacific and was thrown into the brig because of
his age.
   Graham was denied his mustering out benefits and was granted
disability status for one tooth, although he claims he lost all of
his teeth after shrapnel ripped through his mouth at Guadalcanal.
   The legislation, approved on a unanimous voice vote Tuesday in
the House, would compensate Graham with $18,000 for his mouth
injury and give him mustering out benefits of $4,917.
   The military in 1980 offered to give Graham back pay and
mustering out benefits of $337 _ what he would have received upon
his discharge in 1943. But Rep. Martin Frost and House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, worked to get Graham compensated in 1988 dollars,
with interest.
   Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, meanwhile, is attempting to get the
Senate to act quickly on Graham's behalf and has asked Sen. Howell
T. Heflin, D-Ala., to help move the bill out of the Senate
Judiciary subcommittee that he chairs.
   The Navy in 1978 granted Graham an honorable discharge, Bentsen
said.
   Graham's story was the subject of a CBS television movie, ``Too
Young the Hero,'' earlier this year, and Frost said he believes the
publicity finally stirred Congress into acting. The bill had been
introduced four or five times previously.
   Graham rejoined the service when he reached the proper age and
served with the Marines during the Korean War. He is now confined
to a wheelchair from injuries suffered during a fall from a pier in
California years ago.
</TEXT>
