<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-China     10-06 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-China,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese-Soviet Likely; Gorbachev To Visit North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will probably meet
with Chinese leaders early next year and also plans to visit North
Korea, the Kremlin said Thursday.
   Igor A. Rogachev, deputy foreign minister in charge of contacts
with China, was asked whether a Soviet-Chinese summit would follow
a meeting this year between the two foreign ministers, and whether
the summit would occur in the first half of 1989 as Chinese reports
have indicated.
   ``My sense is that one might be in a position to suggest that
both would be the case,'' Rogachev replied at a news conference.
   Moscow and Beijing have been at odds since the 1960s. Nikita S.
Khrushchev and Mao Tse-tung held the last summit in 1959.
   Gorbachev has taken several actions that opened the way to
better relations, including withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from
Afghanistan, reducing troop strength on the Chinese border and
agreeing in August to the first direct talks with China about
Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia.
   Foreign Minister Qian Quichen of China met with the Soviet
foreign minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, last month and plans to
visit Moscow later this year, but no date has been set. Rogachev
said Cambodia, where the Soviet Union supports Vietnam's
occupation, will be high on the agenda.
   Rogachev has represented the Kremlin in the talks with China on
Cambodia.
   He did not say whether Gorbachev would travel to Beijing or
Chinese leaders would visit Moscow. Gorbachev broached the idea of
a summit in a speech Sept. 16 in Siberia.
   On Thursday, Rogachev told reporters the Kremlin hopes relations
with China can be based on ``friendship and good-neighborliness.''
   Gorbachev's visit to North Korea will fulfill a commitment made
by Andrei A. Gromyko. Soviet news reports Sept. 26 said Gromyko
would visit North Korea as the Soviet president in the first 10
days of October.
   Gromyko was retired from the presidency and the ruling Communist
Party Politburo last week, however, and Gorbachev was elected
president.
   Rogachev told the news conference Gorbachev has a standing
invitation to visit North Korea and expects to do so but has not
set a date.
</TEXT>
