<HEAD>Widow From Miramar Wins $10 Million Lotto Prize</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT that woman has step children, sted seven
children. Subs 4th graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claimed her $10 million
Florida Lotto jackpot on Thursday said the money will give her a
sense of security but she has no plans to quit her job.
   Elynor Purcell, 67, said she went to work Sunday, the day after
the jackpot drawing, at the turnstiles at the Calder Race Course
clubhouse and waited until Monday to tell her neighbor.
   ``I woke my friend Judy up and told her. I guess it was about 10
after eight so it was a little early for her,'' Mrs. Purcell said
during a news conference. ``She said, `If you came up here at this
hour of the morning there must be something wrong,' and I said
`Yeah, I'm rich.' I think I started to tear up a little bit.''
   Mrs. Purcell, 67, moved to Florida from near Pottsville, Pa., in
1959. She has lived in Miramar for about 12 years. She said she has
stepchildren living in Pennsylvania but didn't say how many or
where they lived.
   When she correctly picked the six winning numbers last week, the
jackpot had been advertised at $9 million, but it was boosted to
$10.04 million by vigorous sales, which means she will collect
$502,000 a year for 20 years.
   She also has won the daily numbers game, called CASH 3, three
times since it started in January, said lottery Secretary Rebecca
Paul.
   Ms. Paul also announced that this week's Lotto jackpot has been
boosted from $8 million to $10 million because sales of the $1
tickets were even with last week's.
   Mrs. Purcell said she didn't have any system for picking her
winning numbers, which were 16, 20, 27, 31, 40 and 41.
   She has no specific plans for spending the money.
   ``It's a little early to decide that now,'' she said. ``It will
probably give me a sense of security since I will be able to
collect this for 20 years.''
</TEXT>
