<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     10-06 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Accepts Victor's Welcome, Takes New Jibes at Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONE STAR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exultant Lloyd Bentsen flew home to
Texas Thursday, taking new jibes at Dan Quayle's need for ``job
training'' while accepting fellow Democrats' accolades for his
performance against Quayle in the vice presidential debate.
   ``Last night, the eyes of Texas and the whole nation were on
you, and they liked what they saw,'' Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis told Bentsen before a cheering crowd in
this rural East Texas community.
   Bentsen and Dukakis, who usually campaign separately, united for
the joint post-debate rally. Bentsen normally introduces Dukakis
when they do appear together, but Bentsen followed Dukakis to the
microphones this time.
   ``After listening to Dan Quayle last night, I can understand why
he kept talking about job training,'' Bentsen said, getting a roar
from the 2,500 people in a lakeside park.
   Across the lake was a steel factory that he said has lost
thousands of jobs to foreign competition. Bentsen said the
Republicans don't want to talk about that.
   ``My friends, if you don't speak of these concerns, you're
endangering America,'' he said.
   The Texas senator appeared elated by poll figures suggesting
most television viewers thought he won the debate.
   ``Gee, those polls were great, weren't they?'' he told reporters
traveling with his campaign. ``Well, I knew I scored some points,
and I thought I was winning, but it's difficult to be objective
about yourself.''
   The Dukakis campaign planned to take advantage of what they felt
was a clear Bentsen debate victory by airing new television spots
questioning Quayle's qualifications for the presidency, said Dayton
Duncan, Dukakis' press secretary.
   The flash point of Wednesday night's debatge came when Bentsen
told Quayle he was ``no Jack Kennedy.'' Bentsen acknowledged that
the topic had been raised during his preparations, but denied his
answer was a ``canned'' response.
   ``What happened there was Quayle kept comparing himself with
Kennedy, just overreaching himself, and I got fed up with it,'' he
said. ``I deeply resented him trying to put Kennedy's mantle over
himself when he didn't have a record that compared with Kennedy.''
   Democratic party chairman Paul Kirk, who traveled to Texas with
Bentsen, said he was surprised Quayle compared himself with
Kennedy, even though the Indiana senator had done so on the
campaign trail before.
   ``It was so transparent I didn't think he had the gall to bring
it up,'' he said. But once that happened, ``he was fair game,''
Kirk said, dismissing Republican complaints that Bentsen was mean.
   Bentsen and Kennedy were elected to Congress together in 1948.
Bentsen served three terms in the House before dropping out of
politics for 16 years to pursue a business career.
   The debate reinforced the doubts many people had about Quayle,
Bentsen contended.
   ``The polls show that those that were concerned about his
qualifications for the presidency had that buttressed by the
debates last night,'' he said.
   He disputed Quayle's contention that the debate showed Bentsen
running away from Dukakis.
   ``No, I came to his defense many, many times. I talked about how
proud I was to be on the ticket with him,'' he said.
   After days of tension, Bentsen was relaxed and chatted with
reporters at length on the campaign jet. Among other things, he
listed what he would do if he suddenly had to take the reins of
power _ including quick action to make sure the Soviets didn't try
to take advantage of a U.S. crisis.
   Quayle has been criticized by Democrats for failing to give a
detailed answer when asked that question several times during the
debate.
   Bentsen said one of the last things he did before heading to the
hall on Wednesday night was to gather his wife and children in his
hotel suite and pray. He wouldn't say what he did afterward to
celebrate, except to say there were ``a lot of hugs.''
   After the Lone Star rally, Bentsen was flying to Dallas, where
he planned private meetings, a fund-raiser, and rest. He then
planned to campaign through Saturday almost entirely in Texas,
where the Democrats still trail despite his presence on the ticket.
</TEXT>
