<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Kennedy-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0693 10-06 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>JFK's Men Agree Quayle ``No Jack Kennedy''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new grafs 11-12 to update with Kennedy Library</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of John F. Kennedy's inner circle
enthusiastically agreed Thursday with Lloyd Bentsen that Dan Quayle
is ``no Jack Kennedy.'' But they gave less support to the Texas
senator's own claim of friendship with the late president.
   Lawrence F. O'Brien, who worked for Kennedy in the 1960
presidential campaign and later in the White House, said he found
Quayle's effort to compare himself to the late president ``both
laughable and pathetic.''
   Quayle can cite age, family wealth, years in Congress, and
political ambition to support his claim that his experience is
similar to Kennedy's when the Massachusetts senator ran for
president 28 years ago.
   But when he drew the comparison during the vice presidential
debate Wednesday night, Bentsen quickly retorted:
   ``I served with Jack Kennedy. I knew Jack Kennedy. Jack Kennedy
was a friend of mine. Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.''
   Republicans, jumping to Quayle's defense, branded Bentsen's
remark ``a cheap shot,'' while Democrats denounced Quayle's
``audacity'' for comparing himself to the late president.
   ``I agree with Bentsen,'' said former Kennedy speechwriter
Richard Goodwin. ``I have a feeling it was a pretty widespread
sentiment.''
   Goodwin said, ``I don't suppose the number of years in Congress
makes an awful lot of difference. It's a question ofwhat you've
done with them and what kind of human being you are. ... Kennedy
happened to be a much more intelligent, better-informed human
being.''
   O'Brien, when asked if he recalled any close relationship
between Kennedy and Bentsen, said the Texan ``was considered by us
a friend.''
   However, Goodwin said, ``I don't recall them being quite that
friendly. ... I'm sure he knew him and they worked together.''
   The research section at the Kennedy Library in Boston said files
of White House correspondence between Kennedy and Bentsen, who was
in private business in Texas while Kennedy was president, turned up
only routine requests for autographed pictures.
   Much of Kennedy's correspondence from the period when he and
Bentsen served together in the House was missing, a researcher said.
   Historian James MacGregor Burns said Kennedy ``has come to be a
kind of landmark president'' still revered by Americans even though
he served less than three years before he was assassinated.
   ``His image was always so sharp and compelling that it lingers
in the national memory,'' he said.
   That may explain why Republicans cite Kennedy about as often as
Democrats do.
   Turning to the Quayle comparison with Kennedy, Burns said,
``Literally, their careers are comparable. But the big difference
was that Jack Kennedy, probably because of his father and good luck
and so on, had been involved in national and international politics
for years.
   ``For example, he had been speaking up against colonialism, much
to the annoyance of the Truman and Eisenhower administrations.''
   Kennedy's father had been U.S. ambassador to Great Britain and
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission under President
Franklin D. Roosevelt.
   Goodwin also cited what he called the ``extraordinary'' way that
Kennedy's memory has been ``resilient and enduring.''
   ``It's partly a mystery, but somehow Kennedy became symbolic of
the American's last idealized picture of America as young,
adventurous, headed towards greatness, great purpose, all the rest
of it,'' he said.
   When he spoke to a sixth grade class recently in Maine, said
Goodwin, ``all they wanted to ask about was Kennedy.''
</TEXT>
