<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Elections     10-06 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Elections,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Faces Hostile Crowds In Search For Undecided Voters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres was
jostled, booed and called a traitor Thursday as he campaigned for
undecided voters in this traditional stronghold of the conservative
Likud Bloc.
   ``Peres go home!'' chanted scores of Likud supporters dressed in
blue-and-white party hats and waving Likud banners at the
65-year-old Peres as he entered an open-air vegetable market.
   They taunted Peres for conciliatory policies toward the Arabs,
especially his proposal to trade parts of the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip for peace.
   The crowd of about 400 surged toward Peres, who was knocked off
balance several times but unharmed. Police linked arms to protect
Peres, and security guards grabbed a man who tried to hurl a tomato.
   The Labor leader told The Associated Press: ``It demonstrates a
certain style that a better part of the Israeli people do not like
to see.''
   The crowd was made up mostly of young Sephardim, or Jews whose
familes immigrated from Middle East countries and who now account
for a slight majority of Israel's 3.4 million Jews. They voted
heavily for Likud in the 1977 elections and ended 29 years of rule
by the Labor Party, which was dominated by Askenazi Jews
originating from Europe.
   In a meeting with party workers, Peres acknowledged that the
working-class town of 37,000 residents, including 5,300 Arabs, had
been a Likud stronghold but said ``we hope to change that.''
   Peres then set out on a 90-minute walk down Herzl Street, the
main commercial throughfare. He sought out voters who said they had
not made up their minds or who had voted for Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's Likud Bloc in the past.
   Independent pollsters estimate the undecided account for more
than 20 percent of the electorate and could determine the outcome
of the Nov. 1 balloting.
   To retirees, housewives, shopowners and the unemployed his
message was the same: keeping the West Bank and Gaza Strip would
mean annexing a large Palestinian balance that would threaten the
Jewish nature of the state.
   ``We mustn't lose the Jewish majority in Israel. If the Likud
wins, there will be an Arab majority. Shamir doesn't want a
Palestinian state, but he will bring one about,'' Peres argued.
   He noted 3.5 million Jews and 2.4 million Arabs already lived in
Israeli-held territory and the populations would be nearly equal
early next century.
   At one point, Peres stopped a housewife in her 20s and persuaded
her to put out a cigarette she was smoking. ``I smoked for 40
years, but I quit and now I feel much better,'' said Peres, a
reformed three-pack-a-day puffer.
   But he had more difficulty in getting her vote. The woman said
she had been forced to leave her home in the Sinai Desert when the
land was returned to Egypt.
   ``Because of the territories, it's difficult for me to vote for
Labor,'' she said.
</TEXT>
