<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NuclearSafety     10-06 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Safety,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Seek Independent Probe of Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senators on Thursday asked an independent
committee to review safety and operations at the Savannah River
Plant, a South Carolina facility that produces nuclear weapons
material.
   The plant, run by E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co. under contract
from the Energy Department, has come under increasing scrutiny
since disclosures last week that as many as 30 major mishaps there
over three decades had not been reported to department headquarters
or disclosed to the public.
   The alleged questionable safety and operating procedures,
detailed in internal documents from Du Pont and the department,
continued until this August, when the latest incident caused
engineers to shut down the P-Reactor at the plant. The facility's
other two reactors also have been shut down.
   ``We are very concerned about both the August 1988 incident at
P-Reactor and earlier incidents discussed in a recently disclosed
1985 Du Pont memorandum,'' said the letter, signed by Sens. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C.; James McClure, R-Idaho; Bennett Johnston, D-La.,
and Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.
   They called for an investigation by the Advisory Committee on
Nuclear Facilities Safety, which is headed John F. Ahearne and was
established by Energy Secretary John Herrington to give independent
assessments of operations at nuclear facilities.
   Ahearne expressed concern over the failure of Du Pont and Energy
Department officials to notify him during the August incident,
according to detailed report on the mishap released Thursday by the
department.
   The report concluded that despite a power pulse, ``there was no
accident, no near-miss, and the reactor was not out of control.''
   ``The decision was made to shut down P-Reactor, a strategic
defense facility, even though no imminent safety hazard was
present,'' said the report, prepared by a committee headed by J.
Phil Hamric, assistant manager for projects at the Energy
Department.
   The report found that engineers starting P-Reactor on Aug. 7
miscalculated the amount of xenon and tritium in the reactor and
used an unorthodox method of adjusting two of the rods used to
control the nuclear reaction. The reactor experienced a small power
pulse, or ``blip,'' the next day.
   The reactor was shut down on Aug. 17 under orders from officials
of the Energy Department and Du Pont at Savannah River.
   A detailed analysis disclosed that ``two full weak control rods
(35A and 53F) were found to be at their full up position when they
should have been fully inserted,'' the Hamric report said. ``No
reason nor accurate time for the occurrence was annotated in the
operating logs.''
   As a fix, operators ``drove rods 35A and 53F back to their
original positions by using ... a device for positioning single
rods by bypassing their normal control signal path,'' the report
said.
   `A concise and clear log entry was not made,'' it said. ``Such
joint movement of control rods had never previously been seen by
this operating shift, but restart continued normally.''
   A spokesman for Du Pont said company officials had not yet seen
the Hamric report but have moved to correct some of the
deficiencies.
   ``Some of these problems have been identified,'' spokesman Clif
Webb said. ``We have been thinking about making these changes for
some time.''
   Ahearne, head of the independent committee, was informed of the
unusual procedures not by Du Pont or Energy Department officials,
but by a newspaper reporter who called him on Aug. 16, the report
said, and he ``was surprised to learn of the situation at Savannah
River.''
   The following morning, Ahearne sent a request by telecopier
asking du Pont and Energy Department officials at Savannah River
for full information, the report said.
   Ahearne was out his office Thursday and did not respond to
inquiries from The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Chile     10-06 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Chile,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls Results in Chile An Important Step Toward Deomcracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration responded quickly
and with jubilation Thursday to the vote in Chile to reject
President Augusto Pinochet's bid to extend his 15-year rule.
   But the head of a private research group said the margin of
victory for the general`s opponents _ 54.7 percent to 43 percent _
was too narrow to finish him off politically.
   ``The old fox is in good shape,'' said Larry Birns, director of
the Council on Hemispheric Affairs. He said the Christian
Democratic and Socialist opposition is divided, and that Pinochet
could run in next year's election and defeat separate candidates.
   ``The opposition did not crush Pinochet,'' Birns said in an
interview.``Those on the extreme left and the extreme right
probably will resume violent activities, which were suspended for
the period of the election. This could produce a situation where
Pinochet can say the chaos I predicted is returning to Chile and
the state of emergency has to be reimposed.''
   The State Department and the White House, however, voiced
pleasure with the way the referendum was conducted and appeared to
bless the results, as well.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the voting was ``an important
step toward democracy.''
   She also praised the Pinochet government for accepting the
results.
   ``We congratulate the people of Chile for having given the world
such an impressive demonstration of the power of the ballot box,''
Mrs. Oakley said. ``They turned out in exceptionally high numbers
and took part in an exemplary voting process which they helped
administer.''
   Her statement also credited the Chilean armed forces with
protecting the polling places and said they had guaranteed order
``in an admirable manner.''
   Mrs. Oakley called on Pinochet's supporters and opponents to
work together to build ``a new national consensus.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration was ``pleased with the process ... of the plebiscite
and we congratulate the Chilean people on carrying this forth.''
   The spokesman refused to comment on the results directly,
saying, ``We won't comment on individual Chileans and who won or
lost _ but we think they are on the right track.''
   ``We welcome the democratic process and we hope that it will be
carried out peacefully and effectively in the next year,'' he added.
   Asked if the administration believed that Pinochet would move
toward democratic elections, the spokesman said of the Chilean
president, ``He's indicated he will accept it and work toward
elections a year from now, and we hope that's the case.''
   The elections would be held in December 1989. Had Pinochet won
the referendum he could have remained in office until 1997.
   Before the balloting, the Reagan administration and Harry G.
Barnes Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Santiago, did not disguise their
distaste for Pinochet.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met last week in New York
with Foreign Minister Ricardo Garcia and underscored that the
United States favored a free and fair election.
   On Monday, the State Department registered concern that the
government would interfere with the balloting. On Tuesday, Mrs.
Oakley said the department had received and welcomed assurances
from Chile that the outcome of the plebiscite would be respected.
   Meanwhile, Barnes, who will end his assignment in November, told
The New York Times in an interview in Santiago on Monday that he
would leave happier if Pinochet were defeated in the plebiscite.
   ``I look forward to coming back in March 1990, when the first
democratically elected president would be inaugurated, if the `No'
wins, rather than having to wait until 1997,'' the 62-year-old
ambassador was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
