<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-German     10-06 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-German,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls Berlin Wall `Horrendous Scar'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan celebrated German-American
Day Thursday with a call for the removal of the Berlin Wall, which
he called ``a horrendous scar,'' dividing East and West Germany.
   Reagan, in remarks to a gathering of U.S. and West German
officials in the Roosevelt Room of the White House, hailed the
``shared principles of democracy and liberty'' that have sustained
the two allies for 40 years.
   ``Unfortunately, for Germans as well as Americans, a horrendous
scar continues to mar the hopes and prospects of a united Germany,
free of totalitarian shackles,'' Reagan said.
   The president called the post-World War II division of Germany,
symbolized by the Berlin Wall, a ``cruel and unnatural division.''
   ``The wall ... stands as a gash dividing those who hope, and
those who despair, and those who are free to do as they may, and
those who do only what the state will allow,'' the president said.
   ``Once again, I implore those in the East to remove this stain
on human decency,'' he said. ``Release those bonds and some day
there will be one united and free Germany. And the United States
will be even further enriched by the great German people.''
</TEXT>
