Heights' annual slave auction, a popular fund-raiser for seniors at
the predominantly white school of 750 students, which is run by the
First Baptist Church of Temple Heights.
   Students were supposed to wear clown costumes and be auctioned
off to the highest bidder. The purchased ``slave'' would spend the
next day doing minor chores for the buyer. The auction, which has
been conducted for 15 years, generally raises $1,000 to $1,500.
   Charrise, one of three blacks in the 45-member senior class,
protested the event, sayiould get better.''
