<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Polio     10-06 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Polio,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Will Vaccinate All Residents Under 40 Against Polio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials will vaccinate every Israeli
up to the age of 40 against polio following an outbreak of the
disease that affected at least nine people, the Health Ministry
announced Thursday.
   About 3.2 million residents will be innoculated, and the program
should be completed in a month, ministry spokesman Shmuel Algrabli
said. It will cost about $3.1 million.
   ``We hope this will help to calm people down,'' Algrabli said.
``We are calling on the public not to panic and not to try to be
innoculated privately. There is enough vaccine in the country for
everyone.''
   The government undertook the campaign after hearing
recommendations from a team of international health experts called
to Israel for consultations after nine patients were diagnosed with
polio, Algrabli said. There are another three unconfirmed cases of
the disease, he said.
   The outbreak of polio, thought to be wiped out in the country,
was a surprise to Israelis, who are innoculated rountinely as
infants. The new vaccination is an additional booster.
   Polio is an infectious disease caused by a virus inflammation of
the gray matter of the spinal cord. It is accompanied by paralysis
of various muscle groups.
   Just weeks before the Israeli polio cases were reported last
month, the European World Health Organization, to which Israel
belongs, was considering declaring the disease eradicated in the
region.
   No cases were reported in Israel last year and only one case was
reported in 1986. The recent cases have been blamed on overflowing
sewage.
   Israel's health officials are now considering changing the
method of routine childhood vaccination from the live-virus Sabin
to a combined innoculation of Sabin and the dead-virus Salk
vaccine. No final decision has been made, Algrabli said.
   Since the polio was first identified last month, about 500,000
Israelis have already received a booster vaccination, Algrabli said
They include residents of affected areas and all soldiers in the
army.
   The next stage of the innoculations will start Friday in the
northern towns of Acre and in the Rehovot area, where the polio
virus was found in sewage.
   A separate series of tests will determine whether the boosters
should be administered in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
Algrabli said. He said tourists planning to visit Israel do not
need to be innoculated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
