<HEAD>ACLU Head Says Bush Could Unleash Attacks On Civil Liberties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the American Civil Liberties Union
said Thursday that George Bush's attacks on the organization and
the issues it supports show the vice president has aligned himself
with the ``darkest forces'' in the nation.
   Bush's criticism of the ACLU demonstrates he is ``willing to
toy'' with Americans' civil liberties that are protected by the
Bill of Rights, said Ira Glasser, executive director of the ACLU's
national chapter.
   While the ACLU is used to criticism, the group ``doesn't expect
that kind of nonsense from a major candidate,'' Glasser said at a
luncheon.
   ``He has aligned himself with the darkest forces,'' Glasser
said, adding that Bush's comments reflect his ignorance of the
ACLU's mission.
   Bush, in trying to paint his Democratic opponent, Michael
Dukakis, as a far-out liberal, has cited Dukakis' long-time
membership in the ACLU. In his first debate with Dukakis last
month, Bush said: ``I don't agree with a lot of, most of the
positions of the ACLU.''
   Though Bush's criticism of the ACLU has prompted an outpouring
of spontaneous support for the group, Glasser said he feared Bush's
expressions could create a climate of fear in which it was
acceptable to attack civil liberties.
   While Dukakis has expressed his support for civil liberties,
Glasser said he was disappointed that the Massachusetts governor
failed to vigorously defend the ACLU in the televised debate
between the two presidential candidates.
   ``Bush attacked Dukakis and Dukakis tried to hide,'' Glasser
said.
   The ACLU, Glasser said, is a non-partisan group with 250,000. It
supports the rights of Americans whose constitutionally guaranteed
freedoms are under attack.
