<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Killed in Rebel Attacks in Afghanistan, Tass Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government guerrillas fired rockets at an
Afghan city, hitting a hospital and killing dozens of people, Tass
reported Thursday.
   The Soviet news agency, quoting its Afghan counterpart Bakhtar,
said three patients and a nurse were killed in the attack Wednesday
and that the hospital in the city of Kandagar was damaged.
   Also Wednesday, a mine planted by terrorists tore apart a bus in
Nangarhar province. Twenty-three passengers were killed and 13
seriously injured, Tass said.
   On Thursday, a rocket attack killed a woman and her four
children in their house in the city of Charinkara in Parvan
province.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev told reporters
at a Moscow news briefing Soviet troops had broken a guerrilla
blockade of the city of Paghman in Kabul province. He said the
siege was ended after several days of fighting.
   On Wednesday, Tass reported that guerrillas fired more than two
dozen rockets into the Afghan capital, Kabul, during rush hour,
killing 13 people and wounding 34.
   The Soviet Union said last week it had halted the withdrawal of
its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan because of alleged
Pakistani and U.S. violations of the Geneva accords. Under the
accord signed April 14, the Kremlin agreed to withdraw its soldiers
in exchange for a pledge by Pakistan and the United States not to
meddle in Afghanistan's affairs. Half of the Soviet forces were
withdrawn between May 15 and Aug. 15, and the rest are to be out by
Feb. 15.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Kabul government fight a nationwide Moslem insurgency.
