<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-CrimeVictim     10-06 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Crime Victim,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Crime Victim To Tape Ad For California GOP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Maryland man attacked by a convicted murderer
on furlough from a Massachusetts prison said Thursday he will
recount his experience in advertisements for a pro-George Bush
group in California.
   Cliff Barnes said he has agreed to tape radio ads this weekend
for the Committee for the Presidency. Barnes said he isn't sure
whether his wife, Angi, who was raped by the attacker, would
accompany him.
   Barnes and his then-fiance, of Oxon Hill, Md., were attacked in
April 1987 by Willie Horton, who had fled Massachusetts while out
of prison under that state's furlough program. Horton broke into
Barnes' house, tied him up and slashed his stomach 22 times, then
beat up his fiance and raped her twice.
   Bush, in his Republican presidential campaign, has repeatedly
cited the incident to underscore his argument that Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, is soft on
crime.
   ``I'm not doing this for Bush,'' Barnes said in a telephone
interview from a Washington auto dealership where he is service
manager. ``I'm going for an independent committee. I volunteered.
This is not a case of someone exploiting victims. I want to get my
piece said.''
   While acknowledging that his agreement to tape the
advertisements was tantamount to a Bush endorsement, Barnes said,
``I'm not telling anyone who I'm voting for.
   ``This is not political. I would have the same problem with this
man (Dukakis) if he was running for plumber of the year,'' Barnes
said. ``It's unconscionable to me that this man (Dukakis) hasn't
even apologized to my wife. That's what's mobilizing me. He didn't
even drop me a line.''
   Barnes emphasized that he is not opposed to prison furlough
programs in general _ only those that release first-degree
murderers sentenced to life without the possibility of parole.
   Barnes said he understood the California group was composed of
conservatives from both major parties.
   However, the committee is an independent Republican campaign
started by Steve Garvey, the former star first baseman for the Los
Angeles Dodgers and San Diego Padres, to help the Bush campaign.
   Barnes said he planned to leave Thursday for the West Coast, a
trip that will be paid for by the Committee for the Presidency. He
said he isn't sure whether his wife will travel with him, adding
that she is still haunted by the attack.
   Committee director Lee Stitzenberger said he expects the radio
ads will be used in the final weeks of the presidential campaign.
   Dukakis, who in March suspended the furlough program for
murderers serving life without parole, has attacked Bush for
politicizing the tragedy.
   ``This is an effort to use the one case with a tragic occurrence
for political reasons,'' Dukakis said in Boston. ``(Bush) knows
that the federal government has a very extensive furlough program,
knows that Governor Reagan in California in the '70s had a very
extensive furlough program and tragedies as a result of that.''
</TEXT>
