<DOCNO> AP881006-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JFK-TestBan     10-06 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-JFK-Test Ban,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secret Tapes Show JFK Was Worried His Military Chiefs Could Harm
Test Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in final graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kennedy worried that leaks from Congress
about his military chiefs' testimony would scuttle the historic
nuclear test ban treaty, according to secret Oval Office tapes
released Thursday.
   The conversations involving Kennedy, his top advisers and Senate
leaders in the summer of 1963 show a president personally engaged
in the strategy, nose-counting and public relations required to
push a major treaty through the U.S. Senate.
   Kennedy's chief worry was that a hostile Senate subcommittee
would get the military brass to testify first in private, then
selectively leak portions of the testimony to suggest that the
military leaders had doubts.
   In the end, however, Kennedy steered the limited nuclear treaty
to an 80-19 vote and signed it in his office on Oct. 7, 1963,
exactly 25 years ago Friday. The anniversary prompted the Kennedy
Library to make public the material on the treaty, which was a
portion of tapes whose existence was disclosed in 1973.
   On Aug. 12, 1963, Kennedy spoke with a Senate ally, Democrat
Mike Mansfield of Montana, and shared his anxiety over the
positions of Sens. Henry ``Scoop'' Jackson of Washington, Barry
Goldwater of Arizona and Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
   ``In my opinion, the chiefs (Joint Chiefs of Staff) are the key,
and what they will say in public would be more pro-treaty than what
they will say under interrogation by Scoop Jackson with leading
questions and Barry Goldwater and Strom,'' Kennedy told Mansfield.
   The president wanted the chiefs to testfy first, in public,
before the Foreign Relations Committee, chaired by the more
sympathetic William Fulbright of Arkansas. Kennedy wanted to head
off closed testimony by the chiefs before the Armed Services
Subcommittee on Preparedness Investigation, chaired by conservative
Democrat John Stennis of Mississippi.
   ``What I am concerned about is that these chiefs will write in
private a record which they will then feel obliged to sustain in
public. Well, if we could get them on public record and publicize
that to the nation, then whatever was leaked out of the committee
would have much less impact.''
   Mansfield remained worried, warning against getting Stennis'
back up.
   ``Yeah, well, this is bigger than, than Stennis,'' Kennedy said.
   The Limited Nuclear Test Ban Treaty was initialed in Moscow on
Aug. 5, 1963, between the Soviet Union, the United States and Great
Britain. The three nations agreed to ban nuclear explosions in the
air, underwater and on land but allowed continued testing
underground.
   Kennedy had proposed a comprehensive ban, but Soviet leader
Nikita S. Khrushchev vetoed the idea, said Sheldon Stern, a
historian at the Kennedy Library. Since 1963, the issue of a total
ban has arisen several times, but the superpowers have never agreed.
   Stern said the Oval Office tapes included no dramatic
revelations but supplied a close-up look at the treaty process.
   ``It's a mixture of so many different levels of concern:
constitutional, diplomatic, political, personal,'' Stern said.
   The tapes reveal that Kennedy was well aware of the sales job he
faced to win a two-thirds ratification vote in the Senate, and he
made sure to enlist former Presidents Truman and Eisenhower.
   In July, Kennedy spoke with Secretary of State Dean Rusk and
proposed giving a presidential speech in favor of the treaty.
   ``We got to hit the country while the country's hot. That's the
only thing that makes any impression to these goddamned senators,''
said Kennedy, who had left the Senate himself just 2{ years earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAds     10-06 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Ads Focus On Quayle; Bush Attacks Furlough Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis' presidential
campaign moved quickly Thursday to exploit the vice presidential
debate, releasing two television advertisements meant to cast doubt
on both George Bush's judgment and Dan Quayle's qualifications.
   The ads, on the heels of Wednesday night's debate, are aimed at
undecided voters concerned about whether the Indiana senator has
the experience and maturity needed in a vice presidential
candidate. The Dukakis campaign hopes to lure them into the
Democratic column by reinforcing those concerns.
   One spot, called ``Oval Office,'' depicts vice presidents
Truman, Johnson and Ford taking the presidential oath of office as
a narrator says one out of five vice presidents has had to rise to
``the most powerful office in the world.''
   ``For this job, after five months of reflection, George Bush
made his personal choice _ J. Danforth Quayle,'' the narrator says.
``Hopefully, we will never know how great a lapse of judgment that
really was.''
   The other anti-Quayle ad is part of a series called ``the
packaging of George Bush,'' which features a group of actors
portraying cynical Bush advisers trying to package their product
for the voters.
   In the latest rendition, called ``Crazy,'' the handlers complain
that despite their best efforts at debate coaching, Quayle blew it
anyway.
   ``We've got a disaster on our hands,'' one of the handlers says.
``Suddenly the words `President Quayle' even make me nervous,''
says another. ``Is it too late to drop him? Bring in Bob Dole?''
asks a third. ``It's too crazy,'' says a fourth. ``It's not that
crazy,'' the first one says.
   The ad ends with the same tagline as the four others in the
``packaging'' series: ``They'd like to sell you a package. Wouldn't
you rather choose a president?''
   Quayle survived the debate with no noteworthy gaffes. But the
consensus was that his vice presidential rival _ Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen _ was the clear victor.
   The two Quayle ads are part of a major Dukakis TV offensive that
includes the ``packaging'' series and four direct hits on Vice
President Bush's records on the environment, drugs, Social Security
and education.
   The Dukakis campaign also plans to introduce an ad called
``Failure,'' based on Dukakis' contention that Bush has failed
every mission given him in the Reagan administration. The
assignments have included leading fights against drugs and
terrorism; reforming federal regulations; and bettering trade
relations.
   Two of Bush's newest ads attack Dukakis, the Massachusetts
governor, for raising taxes and for letting criminals out of prison
on a ``revolving door'' furlough program. Another new spot, called
``His Mistakes,'' features Massachusetts residents complaining
about Dukakis and concludes with a Democratic woman saying she's
going to vote Republican this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
