<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Long-DistanceWitness     10-06 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Long-Distance Witness,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Hears Boyfriend Slain over Phone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who called to chat long-distance with her
boyfriend listened in horror as an intruder entered and shot him to
death, but police say her quick action helped them track down the
suspect.
   During a telephone call from Detroit, Sarah Gordon, 25, heard a
man enter the apartment of her boyfriend, Harold Tinch.
   Ms. Gordon asked who it was and Tinch responded ``Rick,'' and
continued their conversation as if he were not concerned, Ms.
Gordon told police.
   As the couple continued to talk, Ms. Gordon heard Tinch, 30,
tell Rick to ``put the gun down and stop playing with it.'' Tinch,
a security guard, owned a .38-caliber revolver.
   A short time later, Ms. Gordon said she heard Tinch again ask
Rick to ``put it down. Don't point it at me.''
   Suddenly, there was the sound of a gunshot, she told police.
   ``Oh, don't shoot me again,'' Ms. Gordon heard Tinch say. She
then heard two more shots.
   After a long moment of silence on the Chicago end of the line,
Ms. Gordon hung up and dialed the Chicago Police Department to
report what she heard.
   Police say her actions aided them in quickly locating the
assailant.
   When they arrived at Tinch's apartment, they found him dead,
shot in the neck, abdomen and right hand.
   Police said they questioned neighbors about any acquaintances of
Tinch named ``Rick'' and were directed to Ricardo Manuel, who lived
a short distance from Tinch's apartment.
   Manuel, 29, was charged with first-degree murder early
Wednesday, police said.
   Detectives said Manuel told them, ``I shot him, but it was
accidental. I put the gun down on the dresser and it went off.''
   Asked if they knew of any motive Manuel might have had to murder
Tinch, police said Thursday they could not say anything more about
the case.
</TEXT>
