<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-Attack     10-06 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Attack,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Toss Grenades At Town Post, Assembly Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred leftist
guerrillas tossed grenades at a southern civil defense post
Thursday, and a rocket grenade struck this capital's National
Assembly building, damaging a stone wall.
   Also Thursday, a leftist political coalition announced its
presidential and vice presidential candidates for next year's
election.
   One soldier was killed and three were wounded in the pre-dawn
attack on Zaragoza, 10 miles south of San Salvador, said an army
sergeant at the civil defense post.
   A rocket-propelled grenade also struck the wall of a stairway
leading to the main assembly chamber, National Police Cpl. Jose
Rodriguez said. Spectators were going up the stairs to view the
morning session when the projectile struck, but no one was hurt,
Rodriguez said.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attack, which knocked a
couple of stones loose and left a small hole in the wall.
   Up to 400 guerrillas attacked the civil defense post in Zaragoza
at 1:10 a.m., the sergeant said. His face was bandaged and his
clothes still covered with blood from a shrapnel wound.
   ``They hit us hard, but they also have dead,'' the sergeant
said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``They attacked us on all
sides but we managed to fight them off.''
   He said 12 men were on duty at the time of the attack, which
lasted three hours. He did not elaborate on the guerrilla dead and
there were was no guerrilla body at the scene, as there usually is
in such cases.
   Rebels also destroyed the local office of ANTEL, the state-owned
telecommunications enterprise, and blew up two utility poles with
transformers, causing a blackout of the surrounding area, he said.
   The attack was the first on Zaragoza, a town of 6,000, in the
9-year war pitting Marxist-led rebels against forces of the
U.S.-backed government.
   Armed forces officers for two years have contended the
guerrillas had been virtually cleared out of La Libertad province,
where Zaragoza is located.
   ``Until today I had only seen the war on television,'' said
Isabel Burgos, a 40-year-old woman who lives next to the defense
post. She said spent the siege under the bed.
   The Democratic Convergence, a coalition of three small leftist
parties said Guillermo Ungo, a lawyer, would run for president and
Reni Roldan, a physician, would be its vice presidential candidate.
   Ungo is also president of the Democratic Revolutionary Front,
which is allied with the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front,
the umbrella organization of four guerrilla groups.
   The Convergence represents the left's first participation in
elections since 1977.
   The left until now has labeled such elections a farce,
contending the civil war makes free and fair elections impossible.
 
</TEXT>
