<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSSuit     10-06 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Suit,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force AIDS Victim Sues Blood Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHALIMAR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS victim who claims she contracted
the disease from a transfusion at an Air Force hospital has filed
suit against the blood bank used by the hospital.
   The state Circuit Court suit for unspecified damages was filed
late Tuesday by Kandra Crosby Sicuranza, 18, against the Northwest
Florida Blood Center in Pensacola. She also filed an administrative
complaint against the Air Force.
   Ms. Sicuranza's mother, Sheila Davis, said she plans to ask $10
million from the Air Force. ``No amount of money is going to change
the facts,'' Ms. Davis said. ``My daughter is going to die. But
this will do what it can.''
   The suit alleges the blood center negligently allowed blood from
an AIDS carrier be delivered to the hospital at nearby Eglin Air
Force Base, where she gave birth to a son in January 1987. She was
a military dependent at the time.
   After the baby was delivered, Ms. Sicuranza received four units
of whole blood that hospital records indicated had been screened
and declared safe by the blood center, the suit alleges.
   Three months ago, Ms. Sicuranza learned that one of the donors
who gave the blood she received had tested positive for the AIDS
virus when he later tried to give blood. On her 18th birthday, Aug.
12, she was told she, too, had contracted the disease. Her son,
however, is free of the disease.
   Gene Roberts, director of the blood center, declined comment on
the suit, but said the facility does not pay donors and complies
with all local and federal testing standards.
   Ms. Sicuranza's lawyer, George Day, said an administrative
complaint has been filed with the Air Force as a prelude to a suit
against that service.
   ``That's what federal law says you have to do, so that's what we
did,'' Day said. ``They have six months to answer, which they never
do. What it really is, is a six-month delay that gives them time to
sort themselves out.''
</TEXT>
