<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Veeps-Environment     10-06 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veeps-Environment,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Lobby `Scorecard' Flunks Both Vice Presidential
Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite their professed support for
environmental cleanup and conservation, neither vice presidential
candidate fared particularly well on an ``environmental scorecard''
released Thursday by a lobbying group.
   Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., scored 20 percent while Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, rated 40 percent, according to the League of
Conservation Voters.
   James Maddy, executive director of the league, which lobbies on
behalf of a number of environmental organizations, said Quayle's 20
percent score ``means he ges it wrong four times out of five.''
   ``I heard him say last night that he deserved a good grade for
his performance on the environment, but I guess we showed up this
morning with his transcript,'' Maddy said.
   Of Bentsen, Maddy said the Texan had rated higher in the last
Congress, when the league gave him a 50 percent rating.
   ``We'd prefer to see it go up a lot,'' Maddy said of Bentsen's
score.
   During Wednesday's debate, Quayle was asked why he had voted
``two-thirds of the time'' against environmental protection
legislation.
   ``I have a very strong record on the environment in the United
States Senate,'' he said, adding that he had voted for the
Superfund and to override a Reagan veto of the Clean Water Act.
   Bentsen derided Quayle's ``late conversion'' to environmentalism
and charged, ``it was this administration, their administration,
that cut out the money early on to be able to clean up ... Boston
Harbor.'' He said the Democrats were responsible for the Superfund
and the Clean Air and Water acts.
   Quayle, in turn, attacked Dukakis for his supposedly tardy
efforts to clean up the harbor, ``the most polluted waterway in
America,'' and his plans to ship waste outside Massachusetts for
disposal.
   The league graded House and Senate members by tallying their
votes on several issues deemed important by the league's board. The
group also took into account legislators' co-sponsorship of bills,
actions in committees and perception by environmentalists in their
home districts.
   The average score in the Senate was 47 percent, with Republicans
siding with the league 37 percent of the time and Democrats, 56
percent.
   A new Dukakis cites the league by name, noting that it ``gave
George Bush a ``D'' rating and they endorsed Michael Dukakis for
president.
</TEXT>
