   A study sponsored by the American Jewish
Committee finds no evidence of patterns of discrimination against
Jews in the executive suites of American corporations.
   Tracing careers of 444 men and women who got master of business
administration degrees, the study found that five to 10 years after
starting out, 83 percent of Jews held administrative positions, as
did 69 percent of Protestants and 53 percent of Catholics.
   Jews had average annual salaries of $111,000, Protestants
