<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionWars     10-06 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Wars,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven More Arrested As Demonstrations Dwindling From Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 6th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 11 demonstrators Thursday in the
third day of protests aimed at shutting down Atlanta abortion
clinics.
   The demonstration was part of a week of protests dubbed ``The
Siege of Atlanta'' by the New York-based anti-abortion group
Operation Rescue. This week, 368 demonstrators been jailed and
protest leaders have made allegations of police brutality, denied
by officials.
   Thirty arrested demonstrators have been released on bond, police
spokesman Cal Jackson said.
   On Thursday, police dragged or carried some of the people
arrested about 200 feet to a van, while sympathizers in a crowd of
about 100, on the other side of a portable steel barricade erected
by police, prayed or sang hymns.
   Seven were arrested, police said, for obstructing a car on its
way to the clinic. The others were charged with failure to obey an
officer.
   Shortly afterward, volunteers escorted a young woman up the
steps to the door of the Feminist Women's Health Center, while one
demonstrator pleaded with her to reconsider. The woman shouted that
she was going through with it, ``and I'll throw the bloody mess in
your face!''
   While some Operation Rescue members had pleaded with the woman
to reconsider, others claimed she was ``a plant'' brought to the
clinic to give the impression that it was operating normally.
   Clinic directors have said demonstrations have caused some women
to reschedule abortions, but deny that the protests have caused a
reduction in the number of appointments.
   Operation Rescue first appeared in Atlanta during the Democratic
National Convention in July, and stayed in town for much of the
summer. Since the protests began, more than 1,100 anti-abortion
protesters have been jailed, mostly on trespassing charges.
   Police have resorted to rougher, more expedient arrest tactics
this week, which has led to charges of brutality from Operation
Rescue and its leader, Randall Terry.
   Operation Rescue attorney Bob Fierer accused Atlanta police Maj.
Kenneth Burnette of kicking a protester in the face during
Tuesday's demonstration.
   ``There will be serious injuries if police don't act with
restraint,'' he said, and vowed to file a federal civil rights suit
against Burnette.
   A videotape of the incident, distributed to reporters by Fierer,
showed Burnette pushing a man with his foot or lower leg but
indicated the man did not appear to get kicked and did not appear
hurt.
   Burnette on Thursday repeated the police department's resolve
``not to let the protesters close down these legal businesses.'' If
protesters could close the clinics, they could close ``other
businesses in your neighborhood or your church if they happen to
disagree with it,'' he said.
   Terry called the clinics ``illegitimate child-killing centers
that have no right to be here. There is no negotiated settlement.''
</TEXT>
