<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-06 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Damp Chill for the Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cool, damp weather chilled the central Plains on Thursday, and
much of the northeastern quadrant of the country was told to watch
for frost or freezing due to dropping temperatures overnight.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms spread over Kansas, central
Oklahoma and southwest Missouri, and fog and drizzle dampened
western Nebraska and eastern Colorado. The rain kept the air cool,
holding temperatures in the 40s.
   Rainshowers also were widely scattered over the lower Great
Lakes, and there were some thunderstorms over the southern tip of
Florida and the Keys.
   Low clouds socked in coastal areas of the Pacific Northwest,
with the visibility down to one-sixteenth of a mile at Everett,
Wash., due to fog.
   The National Weather Service posted overnight frost advisories
for eastern Kentucky and southern Indiana and freeze advisories for
northern Indiana and all of Michigan. Freeze and frost warnings
were issued for parts of the central and northern Appalachians and
southern New England.
   Temperatures early Thursday afternoon were in the 40s over the
northern and central Appalachians, northern New England and
northern parts of the upper Great Lakes. It was in the 50s and 60s
across much of the rest of the country, but in the 70s and 80s over
Florida, southern Georgia and along the Gulf Coast, as well as in
most of Texas, inland California and Nevada. The desert Southwest
had readings in the low to mid 90s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Loring Air Force Base near Limestone, Maine, to 95
degrees at Phoenix.
   The nation's low early Thursday was 17 degrees at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   The forecast for Friday called for called scattered showers over
Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle, southwest Missouri and northeastern
Arkansas. Showers and a few thunderstorms also will develop over
southern Utah and northern Arizona, and rain is expected in western
New York. Skies will be partly cloudy over the upper Mississippi
Valley and cloudy along the mid-Atlantic coast, but mostly sunny
elsewhere.
   The highs for Friday will range from the 40s over most of Maine,
in the 50s across the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and
the Ohio Valley eastward to the northern Atlantic coast, and from
south-central Kansas to central Oklahoma. Temperatures in the 80s
were predicted for south-central and southeast Texas, Florida,
inland California, Oregon and Idaho and in the 90s in the desert
Southwest and Southern California valleys.
</TEXT>
