<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Future Bjt   10-06 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Future, Bjt,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Facing Daunting Challenge After Pinochet's Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chilean opposition, buoyed by its
ballot-box defeat of military President Augusto Pinochet, now faces
the challenge of maintaining its new-found unity in advance of open
elections.
   In addition, potentially divisive issues such as human rights
trials and the future of the Communist Party could sow dissent as
opposition leaders pursue talks with the armed forces to speed the
transition to full democracy.
   Pinochet lost a plebiscite Wednesday on a proposal for him to
remain in power until 1997. According to the 1980 constitution
pushed through by the 72-year-old army commander's administration,
open presidential elections will be held in December 1989.
   Furher negotiations between the military government and the
opposition hinge on Pinochet's standing with his troops, said Paul
Sigmund, a Princeton University professor and expert on Chile and
Latin American authoritarian governments.
   ``I think it depends on whether the referendum loss officially
discredits him within his own service,'' Sigmund, in Santiago to
observe the voting, said during a telephone interview.
   Sigmund said the navy, air force and national police appear more
willing to negotiate than Pinochet's army, which has been fervently
loyal to its chief.
   ``They are more flexible,'' Sigmund said of the navy, air force
and national police. ``They've been predicting this'' defeat.
   Political maneuvering by top opposition figures for nomination
to the presidency also is expected to influence relations within
the 16 parties that formed a coalition to lead the anti-Pinochet
campaign.
   Sigmund said he expected Patrick Aylwin, president of the
centrist Christian Democratic Party, and Ricardo Lagos, Socialist
leader of the center-left Party for Democracy alliance, to run for
the presidency along with someone who will represent the political
right.
   Aylwin and Lagos helped lead the coalition, created early this
year after years of bitter feuding among the opposition. Pinochet
often played on those divisions to strengthen his rule.
   Aylwin and Lagos insisted after the vote that unity must be
maintained, and even expanded to include groups on the right and
left who had been excluded in the past.
   ``We don't want there to be winner and losers,'' Aylwin said.
``To the contrary, everyone must collaborate in the reconstruction
of the country.''
   ``The armed forces have an important role to play,'' Aylwin
added.
   Lagos' moderate leftist stance offends many conservatives, and
he has hinted at a willingness to put aside presidential ambitions
in the interest of a smooth transition of power.
   Asked if the pro-Moscow Communist Party should be included,
Lagos said all democratic parties to the right and the left should
be embraced. ``There should be no exclusions,'' Lagos said.
   Some leftist groups in the coalition favor including the
Communists.
   However, the armed forces are fiercely anti-communist, and the
1980 constitution outlaws communist groups and the propagation of
Marxist ideas. They are certain to reject the notion of sitting
down at the bargaining table with anyone associated with communists.
   Leftist parties also are calling for justice in human rights
abuse cases. More than 700 people disappeared and thousands have
allegedly been tortured by security forces under Pinochet,
especially in the aftermath of the 1973 coup that brought him to
power, rights groups say.
   Parties of the political right and center, apparently
recognizing the military's fear of rights trials, have approached
the issue with caution. They routinely say only that ``the truth
must be known,'' implying an investigation should be conducted but
not necessarily a trial involving military figures.
   The constitution also calls for a congress to be elected in a
year but its provisions make virtually impossible any amendments.
Observers believe the opposition's priority will be to ease the
procedure for amending the document, leaving other, more specific
changes for later.
   Leftist parties want it amended immediately to allow for quick
elections and Pinochet's rapid exit from the presidency. But Aylwin
indicated his party was in no such hurry. ``The period could be six
months, nine months, or a year,'' Aylwin said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Noblet, based in Santiago, is The
Associated Press bureau chief for Chile.
</TEXT>
