<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AssemblyLine     10-06 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Assembly Line,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Line Marks 75th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assembly line, which propelled Henry
Ford into automaking and industrial history, celebrates its 75th
anniversary this week.
   Ford Motor Co. planned a ceremony for Friday at its Wayne
assembly plant. There, Ford's great-grandson, Edsel B. Ford II,
will ride off the modern-day assembly line in a Model T.
   In remarks prepared for Friday's events, Edsel Ford, general
sales manager of the company's Lincoln-Mercury division, said that
as in his great-grandfather's time, the company still is striving
for quality and efficiency.
   ``Seventy-five years ago, my great-grandfather and his
associates put in place the mechanism to realize his dream of
building an affordable motor car for `the great multitude' using
the best employees and materials,'' Ford said.
   Production of the famous Model T began in mid-1908, and quickly,
Henry Ford was determined to bring down the price of his product.
   Three-quarters of a century ago, and a few miles away from the
sprawling Wayne assembly plant, workers at a Ford plant in Highland
Park were tinkering with an idea that would revolutionize
manufacturing worldwide.
   On April Fools' Day, 1913, an engineer in the plant's
flywheel-magneto assembly area tried out a new assembly technique
that spread quickly to other component operations.
   Then on Oct. 7, 1913, the entire process was transferred to the
final assembly area. The first Model Ts to be built by the process
were dragged by rope through the area as 150 workers stood in
place, attaching components to the frame as it passed.
   Within a few years, the technique was adopted by a wide range of
manufacturers.
   Nowadays, robots have taken the place of some workers and cars
along the assembly line are raised, lowered and tilted to make
access for workers easier. But amid the high technology, the car
moves past the worker much in the same way it did 75 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
