<HEAD>Store's Concrete Awning Collapses, Killing Nine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A store's concrete awning
collapsed Thursday afternoon and crushed nine pedestrians to death
on a busy street, civil defense officials said.
   Three children and their mothers were among the dead and eight
other people were injured in the accident in Porto Alegre, a city
of 1.1 million people 1,030 miles southwest of Rio, civil defense
spokesman Orly Furtado said.
   The six-foot-wide concrete and steel structure crashed down on
shoppers passing a store of the Arapua chain, which sells household
goods.
   Firemen used cranes to lift the broken concrete from the dead
and injured, Furtado said in a telephone interview from Porto
Alegre. He said four of the injured were in serious condition.
   Furtado said the cause of the accident was not known.
   ``The building is neither new nor particularly old,'' he said.
``There are no apparent structural changes.''
</TEXT>
