<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Fever Subsides After Blood Transfusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's fever subsided Thursday after he
received his daily blood transfusion.
   Palace doctors were quoted earlier as expressing fear that
numerous transfusions in the past two weeks, already totaling more
blood than the frail, 87-year-old monarch normally has in his body,
were increasing Hirohito's fever and pulse rate.
   He received 0.4 pints ofblood Thursday morning to compensate for
continued internal bleeding, palace spokesman Kenji Maeda said, and
has received 12 pints in the past 14 days.
   His temperature settled back to 99.3 Thursday evening from 100.9
hours earlier, Maeda said.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch has been bedridden since
internal hemorrhaging caused him to cough up blood Sept. 19. He is
being fed intravenously.
