<DOCNO> AP881006-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TuberculosisArrest     10-06 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tuberculosis Arrest,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested for Tuberculosis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-used law allowed police to arrest a
woman who refused to be treated for tuberculosis and was believed
to have spread the disease to family members, officials said
Thursday.
   Margaret Allen, 29, of Suitland, was arrested Wednesday by the
Prince George's County Sheriff's Department and taken to Montebello
Rehabilitation Hospital, a state institution in Baltimore.
   She was in satisfactory condition Thursday and was expected to
remain there for three to six months, a hospital spokesman said.
   Dr. Elin Gursky, director of epidemiology and disease control
for the Prince George's County health department, said Ms. Allen
was arrested under a little-used provision of state law that allows
public health officials to control the spread of contagious
diseases.
   Tuberculosis, which is marked by coughing, night sweats and
weight loss, can be cured, but can be fatal if left untreated,
Gursky said.
   Health officials cannot force Allen to receive treatment, but
they can incarcerate her to prevent her from spreading it to
others, Gursky said. Allen was described as being in a highly
infectious stage of the disease, and could be jailed if she leaves
the hospital, Gursky said.
   Several members of her family have tested positive for
tuberculosis, and are expected to receive treatment, Gursky said.
   The criminal warrant was issued in July, after health officials
failed to find her to serve a civil injunction issued in Prince
George's Circuit Court, said Harry Matz, an assistant attorney
general with the state Department of Health and Mental Hygeine.
   Matz said repeated telephone calls and visits to Allen's home by
health officials failed to persuade her to get treatment for the
disease she was diagnosed with last winter.
   Stuart Comstock-Gay, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union of Maryland, said the state has the responsibility
to protect the public.
   ``On the other hand, I don't think state can force her to be
treated. But they can keep her out of the public's way if she's
going to be passing the disease frequently and easily,''
Comstock-Gay said. ``If it were the cold or flu, it would be a
different ballgame.''
   Tuberculosis is an airborne bacteria that can be transmitted by
sharing a close space with an infected person, Gursky said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Satellite     10-06 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Satellite,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report More Money Needed for Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel may have to stop construction of a new
satellite unless it can find about $200 million more to finish it,
a newspaper reported Thursday.
   The satellite, designed as a communications vehicle and named
for the biblical prophet Amos, is being built by government-run
Israel Aircraft Industries and is scheduled for launch in 1993, the
newspaper Yediot Ahronot said.
   Three other papers said some army generals opposed the project
because of its high cost. Official declarations have said ``Amos''
would be used primarily for civilian purposes, beaming television,
radio and telephone transmissions to Israel.
   Yediot Ahronot said the Cabinet is expected to decide in a few
weeks whether the job can be finished.
   An Israeli official, speaking privately, confirmed the report
but would not elaborate.
   The English-language Jerusalem Post Maj.-Gen. Ehud Barak, the
deputy chief of staff, called the project as a ``Lavi fantasy.''
The Lavi was a U.S.-financed jet fighter project scrapped last year
because of cost overruns.
   Other officers objected to the new satellite because it will
cost at least $500 million, the Post said. Aircraft Industries
officials were reported to have said it would cost only half that.
   Other reports on the army controversy appeared in the socialist
newspaper Al Hamishmar on Wednesday and Davar on Thursday.
   Davar said Aircraft Industries and Defense Ministry officials
were leading the effort to obtain funds. Military and Aircraft
Industries spokesmen refused comment.
   Prof. Yuval Neeman, who heads Israel's space agency, said in a
telephone interview: ``Defense Ministry officials may have objected
to the expenditure, but it is a commercial, not a military
problem.''
   He added, however: ``Government ministries, including the
Defense Ministry, may have been asked to purchase broadcast
channels on the satellite.''
   News reports said the project was conceived by the private
General Satellite Corp. headed by former army intelligence chief
Meir Amit.
   The debate over ``Amos'' comes two weeks after Israel launched
its first space satellite, ``Horizon-1,'' which is said to carry
surveillance equipment for possible intelligence gathering.
   Neeman said ``Horizon-1'' will stay in orbit through November,
more than a month longer than originally scheduled. He said the
flight would be extended because the craft was orbiting at a
greater distance from Earth than planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
