<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Northrop     10-06 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northrop,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice To Stay Out Of Suit Against Northrop Over MX Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Thursday it will
stay out of a private lawsuit against Northrop Corp. which alleges
the government was defrauded of more than $1 billion in connection
with the manufacture of the MX missile-guidance system.
   The suit brought by eight current and former Northrop employees
accuses the company's electronics division of intentionally
delivering to the Air Force defective inertial measurement units,
which guide the MX Peacekeeper missile.
   The 67-page complaint unsealed Wednesday in U.S. District Court
in Los Angeles, and filed in October 1987, says Northrop failed to
ensure that the guidance components were properly manufactured,
controlled, processed and inspected. It says Northrop wrongfully
received $1 billion from the government and seeks three times that
amount. In addition, four of those filing the suit seek
compensatory damages.
   The complaint was brought under the False Claims Act, which
allows private parties to bring suit on behalf of the government
and gives the government the right to join a case.
   Assistant Attorney General John Bolton said the Justice
Department has decided there is insufficient basis for it to enter
the matter now.
   The government could enter the suit at a later time.
   In a related matter, the Justice Department sued Northrop in
August 1987 for $3 million for failing to properly test a component
of the MX. The Justice Department suit followed a private suit
filed in 1986 by two of the eight Northrop employees involved in
the currently pending complaint.
   Tony Cantafio, Northrop's chief spokesman, said ``the quality
and reliability of the inertial measurement units Northrop builds
has been measured consistently since the MX system became
operational in December 1986, and has consistently met or bettered
Air Force expectations.''
</TEXT>
