<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0712 10-06 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle: ``No Question'' He Would Follow Bush's Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: to mention CBS poll, SUB 18th graf, The Indiana...the debate.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle, refining his
response to what he would do if he became president, said Thursday
there was ``no question'' that he would continue George Bush's
policies.
   Asked by reporters why he had not made that response during
Wednesday night's debate, Quayle said, ``It was a very narrow
hypothetical. ... I hadn't had that question before.''
   At a fund-raiser here and rally in Joplin, Quayle said his
Democratic opponent, Lloyd Bentsen, failed repeatedly to address
``whether he would continue the extreme liberal policies of Gov.
Dukakis if he took over the presidency.''
   ``He didn't answer the question. He waffled, shuffled, ducked
and dived,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle told reporters he was disappointed the debate did not
have more questions about foreign policy, which he said was one of
his strengths.
   But it was the issue of his qualifications and the possibility
of stepping into the Oval Office that obviously concerned the
campaign Thursday, and Quayle took pains to address it in his
speeches.
   ``When I was asked that question, I made a judgment that the
people of America deserved to hear me outline the level of my
qualifications and the depth of my experience to assume the
presidency,'' Quayle said.
   ``I responded to that point and the core of my thinking is this:
there is no question that I would maintain and build on the
excellent policies of a President George Bush.''
   On his campaign plane, Quayle noted that he had answered
Wednesday night that he would first pray and then convene a Cabinet
session upon becoming president.
   ``By convening a Cabinet session, that certainly implies that
you're going to continue the policies of George Bush. I did not say
that, but that's certainly implied,'' Quayle said, adding, ``I
think I did just fine last night.''
   Quayle criticized the ``snickering and laughing'' he said came
from supporters of Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis. Quayle said he heard them when he said during the debate
that America was the ``envy of the world.''
   ``I think that's going to be one of the cutting edges of this
election because they look down on America,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle attacked Bentsen in strong terms, saying that he had been
unable to defend Dukakis' position and ``ran from Michael Dukakis
faster than a deer runs from a forest fire.''
   ``I am proud of the man at the top of my ticket. I am happy to
support his positions, and I won't run away from them like Sen.
Bentsen did last night,'' Quayle said.
   There were signs sprinkled at the Joplin rally at Missouri
Southern State College reading, ``Dan, you're no Jack Kennedy,'' a
reference to Bentsen's derisive comment when Quayle compared his
experience to Kennedy's.
   Quayle told reporters on his plane that Bentsen's comment was
``a cheap shot.''
   But asked whether he was glad the debate was over, Quayle
replied, ``I'd like to have another one.''
   The Indiana senator had a long day of campaigning Thursday, with
stops in Missouri, Florida and Tennessee. He left Omaha in an
upbeat mood, saying he was not worried about an ABC poll indicating
many viewers thought he had lost the debate. A CBS poll released
Thursday produced the same results.
   ``George Bush is going to win the election. He's still way ahead
in the polls,'' Quayle said.
   The Dukakis campaign, meanwhile, released two anti-Quayle
television ads that struck again at his qualifications. One ad
noted that Bush had chosen Quayle to replace him should tragedy
occur and said, ``Hopefully we will never know how great a lapse of
judgment that really was.''
</TEXT>
