<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0698 10-06 0885</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MIDLAND, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Outlines Anti-Crime Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush tried to rally voters
around his embattled running mate Thursday, saying Dan Quayle has
been ``unfairly pounded'' by his opponents but proved himself in
his debate with Democrat Lloyd Bentsen.
   After barely mentioning Quayle during two earlier stops in
Texas, Bush brought up the debate during an evening rally before
several thousand people _ even after his campaign strategists had
spent the day playing down the debate's importance.
   Polls show that Quayle has been a drag on the GOP presidential
ticket, with many voters concerned about his qualifications.
   Democratic rival Michael Dukakis frequently belittles Quayle's
qualifications, and Democratic vice presidential candidate Bentsen
stunned Quayle in Wednesday night's debate by telling the
boyish-looking senator, ``you're no Jack Kennedy'' _ a political
hero with whom the GOP candidate had just compared himself.
   Taking up Quayle's case, Bush said: ``He did an outstanding job
(in the debate) and he has been unfairly pounded by my opponents.
And last night, last night, the country saw what I have seen all
along _ a young knowledgeable experienced American and I am proud
to have put my trust in a whole generation of young people.''
   The crowd roared approval.
   Bush spent most of the day campaigining in Texas, first in Fort
Worth and later in Midland. It was a day when the theme was
supposed to focus on Bush's call for a ``common sense'' attack
against crime with emphasis on busting street gangs.
   Bush spoke before the Fort Worth Crime Commission, an
organization of law enforcement officials and citizens involved in
anti-crime efforts. Afterward, he flew to Midland to make an energy
address in the community where he broke into the oil business in
the 1950s.
   In Midland, Bush made only a brief reference to the debate,
telling an airport rally, ``I think Dan Quayle did an outstanding
job.'' he did not mention Quayle in his speech earlier in Fort
Worth.
   While Bush and his strategists struck an upbeat note about the
debate, polls by ABC and CBS indicated that Bentsen was the clear
winner.
   Arguing that the debate will have very little impact on the
outcome of the presidential race, Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater
said ``an event like that has very little to do with the election.''
   ``This race is going to quickly get back to the two candidates
for president,'' Atwater said.
   Bush, while warming up for a morning jog at Texas Christian
University, brushed aside a question about Bentsen's tart response
when Quayle said he was as experienced as Kennedy when he sought
the presidency.
   ``I'm not going to tell you what I think about that because I'm
out here to have some fun,'' he said.
   But Bush supporters at the Midland rally made the most of the
exchange. Campaign signs distributed to children to hold said:
``Dan's no JFK. Thank God.''
   Bush has recently become more specific on issues, perhaps stung
by Democrats' barbs that he has been running a campaign of slogans
and no substance.
   In Fort Worth, he assailed the prison furlough program in
Massachusetts under Democratic rival Michael Dukakis, saying:
``1,905 times he gave free, unsupervised weekend passes to
first-degree murderers, many sentenced to life without parole.
Fifty-nine criminals convicted of violent crimes never came back
from the governor's generous vacation program.''
   Trying for an evening news sound-bite, Bush tried a twist on
tough-guy actor Clint Eastwood's warning to criminals: ``Go ahead,
make my day.'' Reagan has also made frequent use of that line.
   ``My opponent's answer is slightly different,'' Bush said. ``His
motto is: `Go ahead, have a nice weekend.''
   Bush's ``common sense'' anti crime program contained a variety
of proposals, old and new, including use of the death penalty,
doubling the federal prison budget to build new facilities with an
additional $250 million each year, and converting unneeded military
bases into state and federal prisons.
   Money seized from drug dealers and racketeers should be
earmakred to help pay for more prison space, he said. He proposed
creation of an anti-gang unit within the Justice Department's
criminal division to coordinate resources of federal, state and
local agencies.
   He called for new mandatory sentences for gang activity
involving interstate drug and weapons trafficking and racketeering.
A fact sheet distributed with his speech said Bush would urge
states to permit the prosecution as an adult anyone 15 years old
and up who is charged with murder, rape, armed robbery, armed
burglary, felony assault or drug trafficking.
   As part of the war against gangs, Bush said,``We should make
sure that no one makes bail, is given probation, gets out on parole
or stays out on parole unless they can pass a drug test.''
   In Midland, Bush said Dukakis had experienced ``a battlefield
conversion'' on energy policy in his pursuit of Texas voters. He
said Dukakis had changed his mind after once advocating a windfall
profits tax on oil companies.
   Bush said that Dukakis, in 1976, had said the nation must press
for re-regulation of natural gas. ``These days he talks mushily of
`the question of deregulating natural gas,' of a `delicate
balancing of interests,' of protecting `both consumers and
producers,''' Bush said.
</TEXT>
