<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Algeria 1stLd-Writethru a0703 10-06 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Algeria, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Declared, Curfew Imposed; Protests Continue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with curfew imposed, late night
shooting; two reported dead, details. PICKUP 12th pvs `The
Algiers...'; minor editing thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RACHID KHIARI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algeria proclaimed a state of emergency
and imposed a curfew Thursday to quell rioters devastating the
capital for a third straight day in a revolt against high prices
and unemployment.
   The military command, in a late-night statement, said rioters
damaging public property would be fired on.
   President Chadli Bendjedid, in the first serious crisis of his
10-year rule, put all administrative and security authorities under
military command Thursday morning. It was the first time soldiers
were in charge of public order since French rule ended 26 years ago.
   Submachine gun fire could be heard repeatedly in the center of
Algiers Thursday afternoon and evening.
   The French news agency, Agence France-Presse, reported at least
two people dead.
   The military command issued a midnight-to-6 a.m. curfew Thursday
night for Algiers and its suburbs as sporadic demonstrations and
street fires continued. The command said those ignoring the curfew
risked arrest.
   The command said public property would be protected ``by force,
including the use of arms, after warning shots.''
   Unconfirmed reports said injured people were hospitalized but
hospital personnel would not answer questions. Many arrests were
reported but authorities gave no figures. Damage has been estimated
informally at several hundred million dollars but no official
figures are available.
   Large sections of Algiers were scenes of devastation with
government buildings burned, cars and buses overturned and windows
broken. Smoke from tear gas hung in the air.
   Inflation has totaled more than 20 percent a year on some items,
particularly food other than bread, which is subsidized. Unofficial
estimates put unemployment in the cities above 40 percent and there
is no unemployment compensation.
   A government economic reform program has caused dramatic
increases in the prices of some staples. A pound of beef sells for
about $11.40 or more, and in some places drinking water is sold for
about $4 a gallon.
   Other parts of the country appeared calm Thursday.
   State-run television interrupted regular programs with this
appeal:
   ``All the inhabitants of Algiers and its surroundings are asked
to return to their homes immediately and to remain calm to allow
the normal course of life to be restored. Every citizen must
contribute to this.''
   It appealed to families to help calm the situation and asked the
entire population to help the military restore order.
   The Algiers military command established under the emergency
issued a ``Communique No. 1'' declaring the army would ensure
respect for law. It banned demonstrations or gatherings and said
looters would be arrested and tried.
   ``Young people manipulated by the enemies of the Algerian people
and its revolution have sacked public buildings, looted public and
private property, violated private homes and harmed the very
symbols of the national patrimony,'' the communique said.
   Public buildings were set afire by young rioters in several
districts of Algiers.
   Several government buildings, including the Ministry of
Education and a state-owned supermarket in the Ruisseau district,
were consumed by flames. Heavy black smoke hung over the city.
   Papers from official files littered the street outside the
Education Ministry.
   Soldiers and tanks surrounded the Bachjarrah housing complex in
eastern Algiers, where several hundred demonstrators built burning
barricades of cars, furniture and tires.
   As on previous days, the revolt did not have a single objective.
It began last week with strikes at industrial plants, postal and
communications facilities and the national airline Air Algerie.
   School children and university students went into the streets
Tuesday and riots began when organized gangs of Islamic
fundamentalists armed with iron bars joined the crowds, trying to
turn the protests in their favor.
</TEXT>
