<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCPrisons     10-06 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Prisons,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Justice Department Request To Reopen D.C. Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Thursday denied a Justice
Department request to force the District of Columbia to accept more
convicts into its crowded prisons, and ordered the federal
government to temporarily house newly sentenced D.C. inmates.
   The city closed its overcrowded penal system to new prisoners
Tuesday when a court order limiting the city jail's population took
effect. The Justice Department on Wednesday asked for a temporary
restraining order to delay imposition of the inmate cap, but U.S.
District Judge Thomas Hogan refused the request.
   Hogan's ruling requires the government to provide temporary
housing for the approximately 20 inmates who enter the city's penal
system daily. He scheduled a hearing for Oct. 17 on the larger
question of whether the D.C. Code makes the federal governmen
responsible for the district's prisoners.
   Prisoners sentenced since Tuesday's shutdown have been housed in
places ranging from a cellblock basement to traffic division
holding cells. Police department station houses were told to be
ready to accept prisoners Thursday.
   The judge expressed concern about the welfare of the inmates,
saying the city ``has apparently made these prisoners hostage to
its crisis situation.''
   ``We will not continue this for the duration, '' said
 also writes a nationally
syndicated political column called ``Inside Report,'' and two
newsletters.
   Shields is The Washington Post syndicated columnist, political
analyst for Public Broadcasting Service's ``McNeil-Lehrer News
Hour'' and does commentaries on ABC radio.
   Hunt joined The Wall Street Journal in 1965 and has been
Washington bureau chief since October 1983.
