<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KlanTrial     10-06 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Klan Trial,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Plaintiffs Dismissed From Klan Suit; Remaining 53 To Be Polled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge agreed Thursday to allow the
chief plaintiff and three others to drop out of a lawsuit seeking
$1.5 million in damages against the Ku Klux Klan.
   U.S. District Judge Charles A. Moye Jr. also ordered that the
verdict returned Wednesday remain sealed while he canvassed the
other 53 plaintiffs. They have until Oct. 25 to reach their
decision.
   The unusual turn of events began Wednesday while the jury was
still out, triggered by an announcement by Councilman Hosea
Williams that he wished to drop the complaint.
   The suit charged the defendants conspired to disrupt a
``brotherhood march'' and violate the marchers' civil rights in
Forsyth County on Jan. 17, 1987.
   In a rambling explanation to the court, Williams, a longtime
civil rights activist, said he had been losing sleep worrying about
the blue-collar defendants ``who have nothing but their homes,
their cars and their paychecks. ... I could not disrupt their
families.''
   State Rep. Billy McKinney of Atlanta, who joined the lawsuit in
July, objected to Williams' decision to withdraw, and that resulted
in a hectic day of legal maneuvering while jurors continued
deliberating.
   The suit seeks $500,000 each in damages against the Invisible
Empire Knights of the KKK and the Southern White Knights of the
KKK; $200,000 against Southern White Knights Grand Dragon David W.
Holland; and $100,000 each against Invisible Empire leaders Daniel
B. Carver and Edward Stephens, and Marion Franklin Shirley, an
associate of Holland.
   Participants in the 1987 march were pelted with rocks, bottles
and other debris thrown by people among a large group of
counterdemonstrators who gathered in the virtually all-white county
north of Atlanta.
   A week later, more than 20,000 people descended upon Forsyth
County in a huge civil rights march that drew worldwide attention.
   During the hearing Thursday, Moye rejected a bid by Williams to
have McKinney dismissed from the suit, but agreed to allow Williams
and plaintiffs Elizabeth W. Omilama, Terrie L. Randolph and Forrest
Sawyer Jr. to drop out.
   The judge and both sides agreed that if punitive damages were
awarded, the amount would be reduced to reflect the number of
plaintiffs remaining in the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
