<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BushEndorsements     10-06 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush Endorsements,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Endorsed By Lowell Newspaper, Worcester Police Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush racked up two more
endorsements in rival Michael Dukakis' home state of Massachusetts
on Thursday, gaining the support of a Worcester police union and
The Sun newspaper in Lowell.
   The 87-member Worcester Police Officials Association voted 21-1
on Wednesday to endorse Bush for president. The association
represents deputy chiefs, captains, lieutenants and sergeants.
   Sgt. Roger L. Steele said the union fears Dukakis would
liberalize the U.S. Supreme Court while in office. Police unions in
Boston, Lawrence and Springfield have also endorsed Bush.
   The 303-member Worcester Chapter of the International
Brotherhood of Police Officers ealier this month declined to make a
presidential endorsement.
   The Sun, which twice endorsed Ronald Reagan and supported Gerald
Ford in 1976, credited Dukakis for his help as governor in
rejuvenating Lowell but concluded that was not enough to support
him for president.
</TEXT>
