<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CadetsStricken     10-06 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer for Instructors Says Many Cadets Were Unfit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recruits who collapsed in the first
week of physical training at the state police academy were unfit
for the demanding work, said a lawyer representing the state
troopers who led the class.
   ``At least half of those tested did not meet state police
requirements,'' said Timothy M. Burke, counsel for the State Police
Association of Massachusetts.
   At least 16 recruits from the class of 50 were hospitalized with
dehydration and exhaustion by the end of the first week of
instruction. One is just coming out of a coma.
   Burke said he represents the two troopers who ran the academy's
physical training program because they are union members. He said
no formal complaints have been filed against them, but ``I
represent members in any type of situation, including allegations
of misconduct.''
   State probes of the academy's training by the governor's office,
the state attorney general and the speaker of the house have begun
in the wake of the reports of illness by cadets.
   Burke said he studied physical fitness test scores of Agawam
academy recruits who entered the 14-week class beginning Sept. 19.
   The cadets were from municipal police forces throughout western
Massachusetts, required by state law to attend the academy for
training.
   Burke acknowledged that state police requirements are more
stringent than those for municipal forces. He declined to specify
the state police physical requirements. ``I can't give you that in
25 words or less,'' he said.
   He said the cadets' test results were released to him by the
state Department of Public Safety and the Criminal Justice Training
Council, which runs the academy, in response to a freedom of
information request.
   A spokeswoman at the state Department of Public Safety said
municipal police cadets undergo the same pre-entrance tests as
state police cadets, but the tests are entrance requirements only
for state police cadets.
   Municipal cadets must pass only a doctor's examination and a
body fat test to be admitted to the police academy.
   Spokeswoman Barbara Kopans said the Criminal Justice Training
Council had been considering changing its fitness requirements when
several members of the Agawam class fell ill.
   Timothy Shepard, 25, of Pittsfield, who collapsed the first day
of class at the academy, emerged from his coma Thursday and
listened to the American League baseball championship series on the
radio, his family said Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
