<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InfantBurned     10-06 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Infant Burned,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infant Dies in Hospital Flash Fire During Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An operating room flash fire fatally burned a
15-day-old premature baby undergoing emergency heart surgery
Thursday, a hospital spokesman said.
   The 2-pound infant suffered second-degree burns over 60 percent
of his body in the 8 a.m. fire. He died two hours later, said Ron
Wise of Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   ``The baby was already in congestive heart failure and the burns
combined to cause death,'' Wise said.
   Wise said the cause of the flash fire wasn't known. ``Our
technicians are looking at everything. The equipment was all
working properly. It is very curious. We just don't know,'' said
Wise.
   None of the operating room surgeons or personnel was injured.
   Oxygen was being used during the procedure, Wise said, but
added, ``There was nothing unique about this. No one has ever heard
of this occurring.''
   The infant, born 16 weeks premature, was suffering heart failure
when the emergency procedure in the hospital's neonatal unit was
started by a team of three surgeons, a neonatalologist, a nurse and
an anesthesiologist.
   ``There were flames and the baby was lifted immediately up and
taken to the intensive care unit. The baby was immediately put on
life support, but died two hours later,'' said Wise.
   It wasn't known if the parents were in the hospital at the time,
said Wise, who didn't release the identity of the family or the
name of the infant.
   ``The staff and nurses up there are devastated by this,'' Wise
said.
   The surgery was meant to correct a congenital heart defect known
as patent ductus arteriosus. The defect occurs when a small duct
between the aorta, the artery leaving the left side of the heart,
and the pulmonary artery, which leaves the right side of the heart,
fails to close as it should soon after birth. As a result, blood
from both sides is pumped into the pulmonary artery and from there
into the lungs.
   ``Normally, medication is used, but 20 percent don't respond,''
Wise said. ``They went in surgically to try to correct it. We've
done this about 50 times earlier and there were no problems.
Nothing like this ever happened.''
   Firefighters responded to an automatic alarmed triggered by
activation of the sprinkler system, but the fire was out by the
time they arrived, said Jim Wells, spokesman for the Fire
Department.
   Cedars-Sinai, located in West Los Angeles near Beverly Hills and
other exclusive communities, is sometimes known as the ``hospital
to the stars'' because of the many celebrities who are treated
there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
