<DOCNO> AP881006-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brawley 2ndLd-Writethru a0770 10-06 1064</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0770,1089</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tawana Brawley Branded a Liar; Attorney General Attacks Her
Advisers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf, `They have ..., to UPDATE with
Cuomo quote; SUBS 21st graf, `Details of ..., with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with demonstration outside newspaper and Sharpton saying
Miss Brawley will appear in Chicago; SUBS last graf, `Under state .
.., to CORRECT that contempt charge was not, sted was, a felony.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tawana Brawley's tale of rape by a
gang of whites was a lie turned into a powder keg of racial tension
through the ``hucksterism and opportunism'' of her advisers, New
York's attorney general said Thursday.
   ``We have the facts. We have solved the case. The allegations
she had made are false,'' Robert Abrams said as he released copies
of an exhaustive, 170-page grand jury investigation of the black
teen-ager's story.
   The grand jury said it found no evidence of sexual assault and
said Miss Brawley herself was responsible for the degraded
condition in which she was found after a four-day disappearance
last November.
   The investigation received no cooperation from Miss Brawley or
her family, who with their advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton and
attorneys C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox _ had accused
authorities of a racially motivated cover-up.
   ``They have charged the atmosphere with incredible, incendiary
remarks and with extraordinary tension,'' Abrams said during a news
conference. He asked the state judicial discipline committee to
punish the lawyers.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, who appointed Abrams special prosecutor, was
asked later about Sharpton, Mason and Maddox. He replied: ``Is
there anyone left in America who believes them?''
   Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28, seemingly dazed, outside an
apartment that had recently been vacated by her family in
Wappingers Falls, 75 miles north of New York City. Her body was
smeared with feces and scrawled with racial slurs.
   She claimed she had been held captive for four days and raped by
several white men, and she implicated law enforcement officials in
the attack.
   The grand jury provided no reason for Miss Brawley to lie but
noted that she had been punished and beaten on previous occasions
by her mother and her mother's boyfriend, Ralph King, for leaving
home and staying out late.
   The report cleared Assistant District Attorney Stephen Pagones
and Harry Crist Jr., a policeman who committed suicide shortly
after Miss Brawley was found. Both were accused by her advisers of
taking part in the alleged attack.
   Abrams charged the Brawley lawyers lied repeatedly about the
case, urged their clients to break the law and ``made every effort
to prevent the criminal justice system from uncovering the truth of
what happened to Tawana Brawley.''
   The attorney general accused the advisers of ``opportunism and
hucksterism in presenting their personal agenda'' and added:
``Perhaps the greatest disservice done by the Brawley advisers is
the reckless manner in which they jeopardized the rights of future
victims of racial assaults.''
   Miss Brawley's advisers bitterly attacked the report.
   ``What should we expect from 21 whites from Dutchess County?''
Mason asked on New York City radio station WLIB, referring to 21
whites on the panel of 23. ``It is clear they never intended to
arrest and prosecute those people who did this to Tawana Brawley.''
   Sharpton said Abrams is ``not after people who rape black girls.
... They want to stop anybody who will stand up for the rights of
black people in this country.''
   ``It ain't over till she (Miss Brawley) sings,'' he said. ``You
don't know her story.''
   No charges were filed against Miss Brawley.
   ``First of all, it's got to be recognized and reasserted that
we're dealing with a young girl,'' said Abrams. ``But I think she
also must realize the kind of turmoil she set in place as a result
of her false allegations.
   ``I think she needs help and should get as much help as possible
so her life can be salvaged.''
   Miss Brawley's mother, Glenda, faces a 30-day jail term for
contempt after refusing to answer a grand jury subpoena at the
advisers' urging, but has so far escaped arrest, at one point
seeking sanctuary in a church.
   Her daughter also defied a subpoena but was not cited for
contempt. Miss Brawley left her new home in Virginia Beach, Va.,
Thursday without comment.
   Thursday night, Sharpton led about 200 people in a demonstration
outside the offices of The New York Times, which reported details
of the grand jury's report last week. Sharpton said events showed
the newspaper had illegal access to the grand jury's findings.
   Sharpton said he and Miss Brawley would be in Chicago on
Saturday to ``give our complete and official reaction.''
   The grand jury heard more than 180 witnesses. The probe cost
taxpayers at least $620,000, and the case was investigated
``perhaps in a more thorough way than any other case in the history
of the state,'' Abrams said.
   The report examined Miss Brawley's behavior down to a
microscopic level, including analyses of dog hairs found in feces,
burn marks on Miss Brawley's jeans, and carpet fibers found in her
former apartment.
   The report concluded Miss Brawley spent much of her time during
the four days at the apartment.
   The report said Miss Brawley apparently burned a hole in her
pants, scrawled ``nigger'' on her shoe, smeared dog feces on her
body and clothing, and stepped into a plastic garbage bag in front
of the apartment.
   The grand jury issued recommendations to the Legislature for
legal reforms, including a proposal that would allow the relative
of a dead person to bring a defamation case when the individual is
falsely accused of a felony.
   Abrams and the grand jury also recommended enactment of an
obstruction of justice law.
   New York has a law against obstruction of governmental
administration, but it cannot be used against Maddox and Mason
because it applies only when a threat of violence or a separate
criminal act is employed, the attorney general said.
   He also called for changes in a state law that prevented him
from moving against those who helped protect Mrs. Brawley from
arrest for contempt.
   Under state law, people can be charged with harboring a fugitive
only if the offense for which the fugitive is wanted is a felony,
Abrams said. The contempt charge was not a felony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
