<DOCNO> AP881006-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Reax     10-06 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Reax,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Watches, Applauds Chile After Pinochet Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television on Thursday celebrated the defeat of Chile's
right-wing President Augusto Pinochet, saying voters' rejection of
his bid to rule until 1997 proved ``power can be seized by
bayonets, but they cannot keep it.''
   Since 1973, Pinochet ``played the role of the firm but just
`father of the nation,' trying to make Chileans forget the bloody
history of his ascension to the throne, his betrayal of the
Constitution, the murder of Salvador Allende,'' Soviet political
observer I. Fesynenko said on the TV.
   But Fesynenko noted that: ``First of all, Pinochet will be in
power until March 1990, and only in December 1989 will presidential
elections be held in the country, if the dictatorship does not
abolish them first.''
   In Washington, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the people
of Chile ``have spoke eloquently, convincingly and courageously.
After 15 years of military rule, Chile has said `No' to
dictatorship and `Yes' to democracy.
   ``We congratulate the people of Chile for having given the world
such an impressive demonstration of the power of the ballot box,''
said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   The West German government called on Chile's military leaders to
abide by terms for the nation's democratization.
   ``We hope that the government will now hold to its own promised
timetable and continue on a course to allow open and free
elections,'' government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling said.
   George Foulkes, a foreign affairs spokesman for the British
opposition Labor Party and one of 500 foreigners who visited Chile
to view the balloting, said, ``It's a tremendous triumph for
democracy in Chile, a totally unique situation where a dictator has
been voted out in a plebiscite.''
   Foulkes added, ``It is absolutely crucial now to ensure that
Pinochet fully accepts the decision of the Chilean people.''
   Some Latin leaders reacted with restrained pleasure.
   InArgentina, President Raul Alfonsin said, ``The people of Chile
have expressed their inalienable right to decide their own future.
The results of plebiscite open the way toward the restoration of
democracy.''
   Foreign Minister Roberto de Abreu Sodre of Brazil said,
``Defeating a dictatorship is not easy, but when a government stays
a long time in office it becomes a heavy burden to the people.''
   Mexican Foreign Minister Bernardo Sepulveda Amor, in New York
for the U.N. General Assembly, said: ``We congratulate the Chilean
people for this proof of civic maturity, for this capacity to
transform their own political lives in an orderly manner.''
   The Mexican government, which broke relations with Chile after
the 1973 coup, gave asylum to many Chileans, including Hortensia
Bussi, President Allende's widow. Bussi recently returned to
Santiago after the military government allowed exiles to return.
   President Francois Mitterrand of France said he learned ``with a
profound joy of the results of the referendum in Chile and of the
perspectives opening up for the re-establishment of democracy,
suffocated 15 years ago in this country.''
   In Rome, legislators rose to their feet in Parliament to applaud
the news of Pinochet's defeat. The government immediately named a
new ambassador to Santiago, a post long vacant in a sign of protest.
   Britain's Foreign Office said, ``We hope that the plebiscite
result, which appears to reflect the will of the Chilean people,
will represent an important first step on the path back toward full
democracy.''
   Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez said ``the
people of Chile have given a great lesson of political maturity.''
   Added Laurent Fabius, speaker of the French National Assembly,
``It's a country that suffered terribly for 15 years ... and now,
all of a sudden, there is light and hope again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HitlerRoom     10-06 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hitler Room,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owner Apologizes for Hitler Parties; Nevada Governor Upset</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a Las Vegas resort who conducted
two parties marking the birth date of Adolf Hitler apologized for
his actions Thursday, saying the events were ``not only stupid, but
insensitive.''
   Ralph Engelstad told a news conference that the parties and
reports of a room full of Nazi memorabilia at his Imperial Palace
Hotel and Casino had resulted in a ``living nightmare'' for his
family, friends and employees.
   ``Let me say once again, for everyone to hear, I despise Hitler
and everything he stood for,'' Engelstad told a news conference.
``I can't tell you how much I regret my insensitivity on this point.
   ``It was innocent, but it was very, very bad judgment and it was
in very bad taste. I now realize that and I deeply regret it and
apologize for it.''
   Engelstad read a seven-page statement, then left without
answering questions.
   Reporters were then allowed to go in the room where the
memorabilia was stored. Included were 20 World War II-era vehicles,
including German staff cars, and murals picturing Hitler with his
staff, at the opening of the autobahn, and German soldiers marching
through the streets of Paris.
   Engelstad has one of the largest antique auto collections in the
world, which has been open to the public for years. The room of
Nazi memorabilia is adjacent to the antique cars, but has not been
opened to the public.
   The resort owner said he was preparing to open new exhibits,
including one featuring cars of former presidents, one on Rolls
Royces made in the U.S. and one focusing on the Axis powers during
the World War II era.
   Engelstad has been under fire for two weeks following reports of
the Nazi memorabilia room and the Hitler birthday parties. The
hotel owner said the reports were leaked by people who were out to
get him.
   Gaming Control Board Chairman Mike Rumbolz declined Thursday to
comment on Engelstad's admission that the parties were conducted.
   Gaming agents have visited the resort at least twice to check on
the displays. In one visit they found a printing plate for a bumper
stick which read ``Hitler Was Right.''
   Engelstad said Thursday that someone else ordered the bumper
sticker printed, and he ordered the stickers destroyed when he
learned about their existence.
   He declined to identify the person, saying ``enough people have
been pilloried by this whole mess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
