<1ST_LINE>r a AM-O'HareControllers     10-06 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Controllers,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA In Washington Will Help Monitor Traffic Flow Into O'Hare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic controllers in Washington will manage
the flow of planes into O'Hare International Airport, a move to
help local controllers and clear congested skies, the
Transportation Department announced Thursday.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley announced the change one
day after the Federal Aviation Administration reduced the number of
departures and arrivals at O'Hare.
   This year, controllers at O'Hare have made 30 errors, more than
twice the mistakes recorded in 1987. Four were made since last
Friday.
   Under the plan announced late Thursday, controllers at the FAA's
Central Flow Control headquarters in Washington will monitor air
traffic at O'Hare to enforce the limit of 155 departures and
landings during daily peak hours.
   ``It may be that they delay an airplane taking off at another
facility. It may be that they slow an airplane down,'' said
transportation Deputy Secretary Mimi Dawson.
   ``I don't see it as a reprimand,'' she said. ``Chicago is an
anomaly. We feel this is an appropriate action.''
   Chicago controllers, Ms. Dawson said, will still be responsible
for directing planes to runways once they enter O'Hare's air space.
   ``We're not managing the traffic in Chicago,'' she added.
``We're not managing approaches and departures from (Washington).
We just want to make sure that the amount of traffic stays within
the limits.''
   During peak periods _ between 4:45 p.m. and 9:15 p.m. _ the
maximum number of planes allowed to depart and land in good weather
now has been reduced to 155 per hour from 180 at O'Hare.
   The plan also affects some planes at Midway Airport on the
southwest side because the airports share air space.
   Burnley said his department will study whether those limits are
effective.
   ``I have ordered these actions because today's operating
environment in the Chicago area may require new traffic management
procedures in order to assure continued safety,'' Burnley said.
   Controllers at O'Hare, the nation's busiest airport, made two
errors Friday, one Sunday and one Tuesday, the FAA said. O'Hare
controllers' 30 errors this year compared to 12 in 1987, the FAA
has said.
   In comparison, Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport, the
nation's second busiest, has had just six errors this year, and
Washington's National Airport just two, officials said.
   The latest incident at O'Hare came just two months after the
National Transportation Safety Board issued a report saying that
chronic understaffing of controllers, mandatory overtime, outdated
equipment and inadequate training contributed to mistakes at O'Hare.
</TEXT>
