<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Humphrey'sBack     10-06 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humphrey's Back,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey The Wayward Whale Is Living Up to His Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SRO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BODEGA BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Humphrey, the wayward humpback whale
who wandered up the Sacramento River three years ago, was spotted
Thursday feeding closer to shore than other migrating leviathans.
   ``We don't think he's lost or sick, he could just be feeding on
near shore fish,'' said John Calambokidis, a research biologist for
Cascadia Research Collective, which spotted the whale Saturday
morning at Drake's Bay.
   Fishermen also reported seeing what they believed to be the
40-foot humpback whale on Sunday and Tuesday.
   Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer Scott Richardson said their
spotting was about 2.5 miles off Bodega Head, ``just lazying
around.''
   Cascadia's sighting marks the third consecutive year Humphrey
has been sighted officially off the Sonoma-Marin coast since the
fall of 1985, when he blundered into the tributary waters northeast
of San Francisco Bay.
   For 25 days, the 45-ton whale wandered up and down the
Sacramento River Delta, gaining national publicity, poking into
narrow sloughs and endangering his life because he was out of his
salt-water habitat.
   The scientists, part of a private nonprofit group conducting a
three-year study of humpback and blue whales, say they are sure
they spotted Humphrey. They previously spotted him in 1986 and last
year.
   Researcher Greg Falxa said that among other things the whale was
identified by multiple scarring on his dorsal fin. Humphrey also is
easily identifiable by the black and white color pattern and a
lateral scar on his 15-foot fluke.
   The only thing unusual about Humphrey's behavior is that he has
been feeding well inshore from the other migrating whales
congregating this time of the year near the Farallon Islands 26
miles off the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
   The researchers are photographing and monitoring Humphrey for
Cascadia and the Center for Whale Research.
   The Cascadia researchers are studying the populations of blue
and humpback whales and their migrations, and identifying
individual animals like Humphrey.
   ``We have found record numbers of blue whales so far and about
100 to 200 humpbacks in the area each year,'' Calambokidis said.
   After Humphrey failed to find his way to freedom in 1985, Coast
Guard and Navy vessels eventually got the whale headed in the right
direction and he cruised back into the Pacific Ocean, cheered by
hundreds of people.
</TEXT>
