<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Japan-Blacks     10-06 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan-Blacks,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Black Lawmakers Plan `Code of Conduct' for Corporate Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Afrikan is cq in 9th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Congressional Black Caucus plans to issue
a ``code of conduct'' for Japanese businesses expecting sell their
products to black Americans, the caucus chairman said Thursday.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., announced at a caucus hearing
that the code, to be issued in a few weeks, will aim to correct
what he called Japanese ``economic arrogance'' and insensitivity
toward Black America.
   He said the code would be along the lines of the former Sullivan
Principles, a code of conduct intended to help the black majority
in white-ruled South Africa through training and enlightened labor
standards to which U.S. companies operating in South Africa were
asked to adhere.
   The code was named for the Rev. Leon Sullivan, a Philadelphia
civil rights leader who later announced he has decided to press for
total disengagement of U.S. corporations from South Africa.
   The forthcoming code would be aimed at Japanese corporations and
their U.S. subsidiaries, said Dymally.
   It would seek an end to racial stereotypes and caricatures
offensive to blacks, such as the ``Black Sambo'' dolls exported by
Japan, and the hiring of more blacks as executives in U.S.
factories and distributorships of Japanese concerns.
   The efforts at persuasion would be backed by a ``Buy America''
campaign during the Christmas shopping season to demonstrate the
purchasing power of U.S. blacks who, in the 1980 census, numbered
more than 26 million, he said.
   The Black Caucus approach was described as too weak by some
speakers at the hearing and unrealistic by others.
   The Afrikan-American Committee Against Japanese Racism, a
Washington-based militant activist group, announced plans to smash
Japanese consumer products in a demonstration outside the Japanese
Embassy next Monday.
   The ``slap on the wrist that the Japanese received in the form
of a verbal protest from a handful of members of Congress is not
enough,'' said Elder Yehuda, chairman of the committee, which
describes itself as a coalition of black militant organizations.
``African-Americans will not buy any more products manufactured in
Japan, from trinkets to transistors, from toasters to Toyotas,''
said Yehuda, who also advocated an end to Japanese investment in
the United States.
   But Adonis E. Hoffman, a black attorney who once worked as a
registered lobbyist for the Japanese and South Korean governments,
criticized boycotts as ``the civil rights approach'' to the problem
and said it would not succeed with the Japanese and could isolate
black business interests.
   ``Moral pressure and outrage by African-Americans will not
motivate Japan to share the wealth,'' said Hoffman, who now
represents U.S. black firms in international trade matters.
   ``There must be a minimal quid pro quo to motivate Japan to buy
into black America's business objectives,'' Hoffman said, adding
that U.S. ``black business, as a whole, has yet to establish a
track record or demonstrate the wherewithal to seriously penetrate
international markets or attract foreign capital....''
   Two Japanese concerns _ Toyota Motor Sales, USA, and the Sony
Corp. _ testified on their efforts to recognize aspirations of the
black community and promote its interests.
   Toyota has nine Hispanic or black Toyota dealerships in the
United States plus an active recruiting program to find more
minority distributors, while financing live telecasts of black
college football games, said Pat Tobin, head of a public relations
firm representing Toyota Motor Sales.
   Sony said in a statement that it has shown social responsibility
that ``compares well with that of American-owned companies that
have been sensitized to minority issues over the past three
decades.''
   Both companies said they contribute regularly to the United
Negro College Fund and similar educational programs.
</TEXT>
