<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FreedHostage     10-06 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freed Hostage,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Learning Of Hostage Conditions In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly released hostage is
providing a U.S. debriefing team with ``a lot of raw information''
that could be helpful in learning about Americans still held in
Lebanon, a U.S. official said Thursday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, is close to a
State Department team that is interrogating Indian professor
Mithileshwar Singh.
   Singh said he and three Americans held with him _ Jesse Turner,
41, a native of Boise, Idaho; Alann Steen, 49, of Boston; and
Robert Polhill, 54, of New York City _ were moved frequently by
their abductors to thwart efforts to locate them, the source
disclosed.
   Singh, an Indian citizen and a resident alien of the United
States, was flown to Wiesbaden Wednesday for medical checks at a
U.S. military hospital. He told medical officials he plans to
return to the United States.
   The educator was released on Monday after 20 months of
captivity, but his three American colleagues are still held.
   According to the source, Singh has ``given no indications he was
abused'' while a captive and his comments indicated that Turner,
Steen and Polhill ``are not in a life-threatening situation.''
   The source said he could release few details about the
conditions of Singh's captivity.
   Six other Americans are also missing and believed held captive
in Lebanon, as are seven other foreigners.
   The source said Singh and the three Americans ``got moved
frequently.''
   ``He was moved around at least half a dozen times.''
   ``Wherever he was before he was released, the others would not
be there now,'' said the source.
   The State Department team questioned Singh for a second day
Thursday. The source told The Associated Press that Singh has been
speaking with the special team two to three times a day, for about
an hour and a half in each sitting.
   He said the interrogators are members of a ``standard debriefing
team'' used to question released hostages.
   Asked if they included FBI or CIA officials, the source said
only: ``You're not out of the ballpark.''
   He reiterated that Singh had no contact with American hostages
other than Turner, Steen and Polhill.
   All four taught at Beirut University College. Gunmen posing as
police abducted them on Jan. 24, 1987, on the campus in Moslem west
Beirut.
   A group calling itself Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of
Palestine claimed responsibility and said it freed Singh as a
goodwill gesture.
   According to the official, the four captives apparently had
little contact with the outside world.
   ``As far as they (the U.S. questioners) know, he had no
newspapers,'' said the official.
   Singh has not spoken with reporters since arriving in West
Germany.
   ``He's reticent to talk in public. He doesn't know how those
holding his friends would react,'' said the source.
   No sign has emerged from Singh's comments that other hostages
would be released soon, he added _ ``We had no indications anybody
else will be released soon or at all.''
   The source added: ``There are indications that they (the
hostage-takers) are backed by Iran, we assume financed by Iran.''
   Earlier Thursday, U.S. Air Force spokesman Master Sgt. Charles
Fick said Singh was receiving medical treatment.
   ``Mr. Singh says he feels much better today,'' Fick reported.
   On Wednesday, Air Force medical officials said Singh suffered
from ``tremendous fatigue'' following his captivity.
</TEXT>
