<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0713 10-06 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0713,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Provincial Party Leaders Dismissed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout, UPDATING number of injured, other detail.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party bosses of
Yugoslav's Vojvodina province were ousted Thursday night as a
stone-throwing crowd of 30,000 people attacked their headquarters.
   The provincial leaders had promised to resign after a meeting
with Serbian leaders earlier Thursday in the most dramatic
development in three months of mass street protests over ethnic
strife and an economic crisis.
   The development boosted a drive by Serbia, Yugoslavia's largest
republic, for tighter control over its two autonomous provinces,
Vojvodina and ethnically troubled Kosovo.
   At least 41 people, including 14 policemen, were injured when
the crowd outside the headquarters in this provincial capital of
Novi Sad surged toward riot police guarding the building, hurling
stones and breaking 20 windows.
   State-run news media said two policemen were seriously hurt and
six people were hospitalized. Four people were reported arrested.
   The protesters, who held vigil outside the headquarters for two
days, began to disperse after the leadership stepped down.
   Witnesses said police rebuffed an attempt by the crowds
overnight Wednesday to force their way into the provincial Central
Committee building.
   Tanjug, the official news agency, said the Vojvodina party
committee voted 87-10 to dismiss the 15-member Politburo, the
highest political body in the province. Two members abstained in a
meeting attended by 99 of the committee's 127 members.
   Provincial party leader Milovan Sogorov said a 10-member
provisional group would be established while new leaders were
chosen for Vojvodina, a flat, fertile area that produces most of
the nation's grain.
   Tanjug said the provincial leadership promised to resign after
meeting with Serbian party leaders in Belgrade, the nation's
capital 40 miles to the south.
   The agency quoted the Serbian party as saying: ``The Vojvodina
leadership has been deaf to the demands of the working class and
other citizens. A serious split has occurred between the Vojvodina
leadership and the people.''
   Outside the party headquarters in Novo Sad, protesters waved
Yugoslav flags and shouted complaints about low wages and declining
living standards. Strikes and worker protests have become
commonplace because of 217 percent annual inflation, 15 percent
unemployment and austerity plans imposed because of a $21 billion
foreign debt.
   Witnesses said demonstrators sang Serbian nationalist songs and
chanted ``Police Go Away!'' ``We Are Going To Smash Windows!''
``Thieves, Thieves!'' ``We Want Freedom!'' and ``We Are With You,
Slobodan!''
   Tens of thousands of Serbs have rallied almost daily for three
months in support of efforts by Serbian party leader Slobodan
Milosevic to assert more authority in the provinces.
   Mass protests in Novi Sad started in response to the provincial
party leadership's decision to discipline two members for
supporting Milosevic, Tanjug said.
   In Kosovo, Serbs, a largely Christian minority, claim harassment
by ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million
people and are predominantly Moslem. The southern province borders
on Albania.
   Gen. Nikola Ljubicic, a member of Yugoslavia's federal
presidency and a former defense minister, told Serbian party
leaders Thursday that ``emergency measures'' should be taken to
stop the unrest but was not specific.
   ``I am concerned about today's rally in Novi Sad,'' Tanjug
quoted him as saying. ``Will this rally be satisfied with the
decision to be taken (the resignation of Vojvodina's leadership)?
It can raise other demands. How can we control the situation?''
   Milosevic rejected the proposal and said no emergency action
should be taken ``since this involves a protest of workers,''
Tanjug said.
</TEXT>
