<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Drinking     10-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Drinking,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets To Produce More Wine, Beer, Cognac In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major change for President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's anti-drinking campaign, the Kremlin is planning to
increase production of beer, wine, cognac and champagne by up to 38
percent to meet popular demand, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   However, the Trud labor daily said the government crusade has
gone so far it will be difficult to significantly increase alcohol
production soon.
   The drive was launched two months after Gorbachev took power as
Communist Party chief in March 1985.
   ``We have to restore a significant part of production, and
that's complicated,'' Alexander S. Konobov, deputy chief of the
Ministry of Trade's food division, told the newspaper.
   Gorbachev in 1985 ordered a reduction in the production of vodka
and other alcoholic beverages, an increase in their price, an
increase in the minimum drinking age to 21 and cuts in the hours
and numbers of stores that could sell alcohol.
   He has since cited the campaign as a major reason in the
increased life expectancy for Soviet men. But the anti-drinking
drive has provoked nationwide grumbling, and even indignation,
because Soviets now must stand in long lines just to buy an
occassional bottle of wine or beer.
   Cuts in government alcohol production also have proved a bonanza
for the country's moonshiners. Sugar now must be rationed in many
cities because of shortages caused by the thousands of Soviets who
use it to produce ``samogon,'' or home brew.
   Konobov said the goal set by the 1985 anti-drinking drive was
``noble,'' but that it has been pursued by bureaucratic means.
   ``So it is obvious that corrections are necessary,'' he said.
   According to Trud, the Ministry of Trade has proposed for next
year to increase wine production by 38 percent, to 675 million
gallons; beer, by 12 percent, to 1.8 billion gallons; cognac, by 28
percent, to 33.2 million gallons, and champagne, by 9 percent, to
58 million gallons.
   The newspaper said vodka and other strong drinks would continue
to be manufactured in quantities laid down by a government decree
in 1985.
   Plans also call for more spirits to be imported from Cuba, one
of the world's biggest rum producers, and from Bulgaria, Hungary
and other countries, Konobov said.
   According to figures released by the official Tass news agency,
there are more than 4.5 million officially registered alcoholics in
the Soviet Union, and the total number is believed to be much more.
   As one of the new methods being tried to discourage alcohol
abuse, Soviet television on Tuesday night broadcast a U.S.
television movie titled ``Life of the Party,'' starring Carol
Burnett, which told the true-life story of an American woman who
joined Alcoholics Anonymous to beat the bottle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
