<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Sadat     10-06 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Sadat,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sadat Slaying Marked With Call for Israeli Talks With PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A peace group founded in memory of Anwar Sadat
marked the seventh anniversary of the Egyptian president's
assassination Thursday by calling on Israel to hold direct talks
with Palestinians, including the PLO.
   The New York-based Sadat Peace Foundation also urged Israel to
permit municipal elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
for the first time in 12 years.
   Foundation President James George accused right-wing Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of violating agreements reached by Sadat
and Israel's then-Prime Minister Menachem Begin in a 1979 peace
treaty.
   Speaking at a news conference, George cited from a letter signed
by both Begin and Sadat providing for withdrawal of Israeli troops
from the territories and guaranteed elections of ``a self-governing
authority'' there.
   ``How can you expect another Arab leader to place his trust and
to negotiate with Israel, when Israel under (Shamir's) leadership
has violated its guarantees to President Sadat?'' asked George, a
former Canadian ambassador to Iran from 1977 to 1979.
   The Sadat Peace Foundation was founded in 1984 by Sadat's widow
Jihan and American admirers of the Egyptian leader, who was gunned
down by Moslem extremists on Oct. 6, 1981. It includes members from
Israel, Egypt, other Arab countries, North America and Europe.
   On Thursday, the group called on Israel to hold immediate talks
without preconditions with Palestinian representatives, including
members of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``We should accept any delegaton the Palestinians give to us.
Both sides should accept any delegaton and if it's the PLO, so be
it,'' said Rustum Hussein Bastuni, an Israeli Arab and former
Israeli legislator.
   George said Israel should convene municipal elections in the
occupied territories as soon as possible to permit the emergence of
a grassroots Palestinian leadership with whom Israel can talk peace.
   The occupied territories, where 283 Palestinians have died in a
10-month-old rebellion against Israel's 21-year occupation, have
not held municipal elections since 1976.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the prospects for Palestinian elections in the
territories ``depended on the situation there next year.''
   The territories, the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, were taken by
Israel from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   END (dh@ms)
</TEXT>
