<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Africa 1stLd-Writethru a0676 10-06 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Leader Calls for Conference On African Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with toasts.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recently elected chairman of the
Organization of African Unity called for an international
conference on African debt during a meeting with President Reagan
Thursday, a U.S. official said.
   Kenneth Brown, deputy assistant secretary of state for African
Affairs, said Moussa Traore, the president of Mali, told Reagan
that he ``wants to avoid a confrontation between debtors and
creditors.''
   Brown referred enquiries about the details of Traore's proposal
to officials of Mali. At the Embassy of Mali, an aide said all of
the officials familiar with the proposal were with Traore and could
not be reached.
   ``His party would have to speak primarily for him, but he would
like to see an international conference on African debt and made
that known during the meeting,'' Brown said. ``He wants to avoid a
confrontation between debtors and creditors and that's why he was
stressing this global approach.''
   Brown said Reagan and other U.S. officials at the meeting
``discussed the U.S. approach in terms of dealing with individual
cases, case by case, and our interest in trying to encourage those
who are serious about reforming their economy and not necessarily
rewarding the worst performers.''
   Brown said Reagan expressed concern that Libya, which has been
involved in war with Chad in the Western Sahara, is developing the
capacity to produce chemical weapons. He said the president
emphasized ``the need for all of us to be vigilant in that regard.''
   The United States has previously expressed concern that Libya
has a plant that may be approaching capability to produce such
weapons.
   ``We have an interest therefore in an international approach to
take mesures against the use of such weapons,'' Brown said.
   The president proposed an international conference on the
subject during his speech to the United Nations General Assembly
last week.
   In remarks at a welcoming ceremony on the South Lawn of the
White House, Reagan praised Mali's economic reform program, which
has made the impoverished West African nation a major African
recipient of U.S. economic aid.
   Since becoming chairman of the OAU at the African summit in May,
he told Traore, ``You have already demonstrated your interest in
helping to promote regional settlements in Southern Africa and the
Western Sahara.''
   ``We hope the OAU can play an even more active role in solving
those regional problems and play a key role in promoting
development in Africa by encouraging economic reform and
cooperation,'' he said.
   Traore, in his response, said he was ``convinced ... that our
discussions will enable us to make progress in the search for a
solution to the problems which are of concern to both our sides.''
   As he posed for photographs with Traore before their closed
meeting, Reagan responded to a question about human rights in
Africa by saying, ``I think we are sitting beside a man in whose
country that is a major goal.''
   Brown said the two leaders met privately for half an hour and
then met in a larger group for an additional half hour.
   At a state dinner for Traore on Thursday night, Reagan said he
was ``gratified that you share our concern about regional stability
and economic development in Africa'' and added that the United
States would ``continue to work with you and be as supportive as we
can in these areas.''
   Responding to the president's toast, Traore, speaking in French,
said through an interpreter that the OAU would continue to seek
``the taking down of the intolerable system of apartheid'' in South
Africa. He said also that it was ``urgent to find a just and
lasting solution to the problem of the African debt.''
</TEXT>
