<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq     10-06 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Says ``Modest Progress'' Made In Peace Talks With Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's foreign minister said Thursday
progress was made in recent Iran-Iraq peace talks, but he still
accused Iraq of balking on some issues and declined to comment on
whether a compromise was near.
   ``The Iraqi delegation entered into substantive talks and modest
progress has been made,'' said Ali Akbar Velayati after separate
meetings in New York with the Iraqi side and with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``I cannot go into details, but I can tell you the situation is
better now than in the beginning,'' he told a news conference.
   Asked about the release of U.S. hostages held by pro-Iranian
extremists in Lebanon, he said, ``I categorically deny there are
any talks between the United States and Iran and no talks on the
hostage issue.''
   Velayati said he was willing to resume talks in Geneva with
Perez de Cuellar's representative and with Iraq on Oct. 26 or Oct
27, if requested by the U.N. chief. Iraq agreed to only one
negotiating session in New York.
   Iraq and Iran renewed peace talks Saturday at U.N. headquarters
in New York after a session in Geneva from Aug. 25 to Sept. 13. The
talks followed a cease-fire Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old war, which
left at least 1 million killed or wounded.
   
   Velyati emphasized he was not fully satisfied with the outcome
of meetings with Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz and blamed Iraq
for introducing what he called extraneous issues.
   ``I am not altogether pleased or greatly encouraged in the pace
of the talks,'' Velayati said. He added that both sides have not
yet ``been able to achieve the goals that the secretary-general had
set.''
   These goals are formalization of the cease-fire, withdrawal by
both sides to international boundaries and repatriation of
prisoners of war, under terms of U.N. Security Council Resolution
598.
   Velayati avoided a direct answer when asked if a compomise deal
had been struck, in which Iran would halt searching neutral
shipping in the gulf, as reported by U.N. sources.
   In turn, the sources said, Iraq would postpone discussion of
sovereignty over the disputed Shatt al-Arab waterway between the
two nations.
   U.N. sources have reported that such a deal, arranged by the
secretary-general, was virtually in place and could break the
deadlock between the two sides over clearing of the Shatt al-Arab,
sovereignty over the channel and other issues.
   Velayati did not deny a deal in the future but emphasized that
for the time being Iran would not give up its right to search
suspect ships in time of war.
</TEXT>
