<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonTrial     10-06 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Myerson Case: What the Law Clerk Heard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While a state judge was ruling favorably in the
divorce case of Bess Myerson's lover, the former Miss America was
calling the judge on an unlisted, private line, the judge's former
law clerk testified Thursday.
   Miss Myerson called more than a dozen times and gave an assumed
name to court personnel, the law clerk also testified at the
divorce-fixing trial of the two women and Miss Myerson's lover,
Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   The Capasso case was one of the few handled personally by the
judge, law clerk Howard Leventhal testified.
   Miss Myerson, Capasso and state Supreme Court Justice Hortense
Gabel each face five counts of conspiracy, mail fraud and
bribe-related charges in an alleged 1983 scheme to slash Capasso's
child support and alimony payments.
   In his second day of federal court testimony, Leventhal said
that of more than 3,000 requests to change alimony and child
support payments, the Capasso case was one of the few Mrs. Gabel
handled personally.
   ``I think I'll do this one myself, Howie,'' Leventhal said the
judge told him in July 1983 after Capasso's lawyer sought to delay
weekly alimony and child support payments of $1,850 a week to
Capasso's wife, Nancy.
   Asked if Mrs. Gabel had given similar personal attention to
other support requests, Leventhal, who was her law secretary from
1981 until her resignation last year, said: ``Maybe one or two.''
   Prosecutors charge that Miss Myerson, the city's former cultural
affairs commissioner, gave a $19,000 city job to Mrs. Gabel's
unemployed daughter, Sukhreet, in order to influence the outcome of
the judge's decision.
   Leventhal, the prosecution's second witness, testified that in
the summer of 1983, Miss Myerson began calling the judge on a
private, unlisted phone.
   Prosecutors contend that even though Miss Myerson and Mrs. Gabel
knew each other, their contacts were limited until the judge began
handling interim decisions in the Capasso divorce.
   Leventhal also said Miss Myerson often called identifying
herself either as ``Barbara Goodman or Robinson.''
   Leventhal said he didn't recognize the voice although the woman
called ``a fairly large number (of times) between a dozen and two
dozen.''
   The clerk said he asked Mrs. Gabel ``who is this Barbara
Goodman, Robinson person?'' He said the judge replied: ``Oh, that's
Bess Myerson. She's just being so Byzantine.''
   On Sept. 14, 1983, about a month after Sukhreet Gabel was made a
special assistant to Miss Myerson, the judge cut Capasso's
temporary alimony and child support payments from $1,850 to $680 a
week.
   When an Oct. 18, 1983 New York Post story reported the
``coincidence'' of Ms. Gabel's hiring by the Cultural Affairs
Department, Mrs. Gabel asked Leventhal if she should withdraw from
the Capasso case.
   ``I think it would be a good idea,'' Leventhal said he told the
judge.
   He said that Mrs. Gabel had excused herself from other cases in
the past where there had been a possible conflict of interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
