<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarveyTrial     10-06 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvey Trial,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Confronted Gunmen, Witnesses Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy and a Christian
school's headmaster testified Thursday that a woman who teaches
third grade came to the defense of her youngsters by attacking a
gunman with a book.
   ``This is a .357 Magnum,'' headmaster Dan Carden quoted
defendant James L. Harvey as telling teacher Mary Alice Blanton.
   ``I don't care what it is _ get out of here,'' Carden quoted her
as replying.
   Harvey is charged with kidnapping 110 people at the West End
Christian School in Tuscaloosa on Feb. 2. Defending himself in
state court here as a crusader for people's constitutional rights,
Harvey has called Mrs. Blanton ``a fiesty lady.''
   Ten-year-old Marty Vice said he saw Mrs. Blanton encounter
Harvey and another gunman in a hallway, where she began hitting
Harvey with a book.
   The other man, described by police as an unwilling accomplice,
testified Thursday he was duped by Harvey into helping take over
the school and later was threatened with his life if he tried to
back out.
   Marty, then a fourth-grader, said he was coming out of the
bathroom when he saw two men walk in at the other end of the
hallway.
   After seeing the confrontation with Mrs. Blanton, Marty said, he
ducked into the nearest classroom. Asked why he did not return to
his own class, Marty said, ``I didn't want them to get me.''
   Carden told the jury that when he heard of the trouble, he and a
coach rushed to the elementary school building and saw Mrs. Blanton
struggling with Harvey, while he held a cocked pistol pointed
toward the ceiling.
   Carden said he and the coach then told Mrs. Blanton to do
whatever Harvey told her to do.
   John Rhodes Jr., 43, testified that he was picking up beer cans
near an unemployment office that day when Harvey offered him $50 to
help him move across town. Instead, Harvey drove him to the school,
gave him an empty gun and told him to put it in his coat pocket.
   ``He said this was something he had been planning for two or
three years,'' Rhodes said. ``What he planned I didn't know.''
Rhodes told the jury that when he and Harvey entered the school, he
told Harvey he wanted to leave.
   ``You ain't no more your own boss,'' he quoted Harvey as saying.
``You do it or die.''
   The two men entered the school at 8:30 a.m. and about 2:30 p.m.,
Rhodes said he surrendered to an officer who offered him more money
than Harvey promised. ``He asked me if $300 would do me any good. I
said yes. I gave him the gun and I walked out. I was wanting to go
anyway.''
   Kidnapping charges against Rhodes were dropped after authorities
decided he was an unwilling participant.
   Harvey surrendered after 12 hours when authorities produced a
videotape in which Gov. Guy Hunt, who is to testify Friday at
Harvey's insistence, offered a bogus pardon.
   Cross-examining six Tuscaloosa policemen who identified weapons
taken from the school, Harvey suggested the guns showed he ``was
very serious about what he believed.''
   ``I had a right to act as a steward for those children and their
future ... against pollution, deceit and people who are destroying
the Constitution of the United States,'' Harvey said while
questioning one officer.
</TEXT>
