<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Namibia     10-06 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Namibia,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Namibia-Angola Talks Set For Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba, Angola and South Africa will meet
Friday to discuss the implementation of the U.N. plan for Namibia's
independence, and Cuba's withdrawal of its soldiers from Angola,
the South Africans confirmed.
   The exact time and location for the talks were not determined
and it was not yet confirmed whether the U.S. State Department
would continue mediating the talks, as it has in previous meetings,
said Aubrey Dwyer, a spokesman for South Africa's U.N. Mission, on
Thursday.
   South Africa has told Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
it is ready to begin implementation on Nov. 1 of Security Council
Resolution 435 to give neighboring South-West Africa, or Namibia,
its freedom.
   Resolution 435, passed a decade ago, is a one-year plan for
national assembly elections under U.N. supervision.
   About 7,500 U.N. peacekeeping troops and 2,000 civilian support
staff are to be sent to Namibia in an operation estimated to cost
between $600 million and $700 million.
   South Africa has ruled the former German colony since World War
I. The United Nations revoked a mandate from its predecessor, the
League of Nations, and declared Pretoria's rule over Namibia
illegal.
   Complicating the plan is South Africa's insistence that about
50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola to protect that country's
Marxist government from the UNITA rebel movement should be
withdrawn in a year. UNITA stands for the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola.
   The Cubans have reportedly compromised their initial insistence
on a four-year withdrawal down to two years, with a phased
withdrawal away from southern Angola's border with northern Namibia.
   Officials involved in the talks among the United States, Angola,
Cuba and South Africa, including U.S. Secretary of State George
Shultz, have expressed confidence that a mutually acceptable
compromise will be reached on the withdrawal timetable.
</TEXT>
