<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NSF-Kingsbury     10-06 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NSF-Kingsbury,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Science Policy Maker Resigns Federal Position During Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Science Foundation official who
helped set Reagan Administration policies regulating biology
research said Thursday he is resigning to resume research, not
because the Justice Department is investigating him for possible
financial conflicts of interest.
   David T. Kingsbury, assistant director of the NSF for
biological, behavioral and social sciences for the last four years,
said he is resigning because ``I want to go back to the
laboratory.''
   He confirmed that a Justice Department investigation of his
financial interests is continuing, but said, ``That's not why I've
resigned.''
   Kingsbury formally leaves the NSF on Oct. 15, and assumes a new
position as a full professor at George Washington University on
Nov. 1. He said the university job will include continuation of a
research project that has been under way for several years and
``now is at a critical point.''
   In his letter of resignation, dated Sept. 23, Kingsbury said he
was making the move to return to research and because of ``the
stress on both the agency and me over the past year resulting from
publicity about my activities outside NSF.''
   He acknowledged that he has been accused of having improper
connections with biotechnology companies that could have been
affected by NSF policies, but denied that there is a conflict.
   Kingsbury said that shortly after his appointment to the NSF in
1984, he submitted a list of his holdings to the NSF general
counsel. He said the counsel advised him to sell only one
investment, stock in the Chiron Corp. of Emeryville, Calif., a
biotechnology company. The other holdings were not considered to be
a conflict of interest, he said.
   Some companies in which he holds stock have been incorrectly
identified as biotechnology companies, said Kingsbury, saying,
``Whether or not they are biotechnology companies is a matter of
interpretation.''
   He identified one of his holdings as New Brunswick Scientific, a
company that he said makes laboratory equipment, but does no
biotechnology research.
   Kingsbury said he has hired an attorney to assist him in the
continuing Justice Department probe, but that the investigation
started more than a year ago and nothing has come of it.
   ``I have not been charged with any conflict of interest,'' he
said.
   The NSF announced Kingsbury's resignation last week in a
two-paragraph statement from Erich Bloch, the NSF director.
   In the statement, Bloch said the NSF would not comment on an
investigation of Kingsbury, but did note that ``concerns have
arisen and have been under consideration by the Justice Department
concerning certain of Dr. Kingsbury's financial and business
relationships, especially with regard to financial disclosure.''
   Kingsbury is a former University of California at Berkeley
researcher and a specialist in the genetics of brain ailments, such
as Alzheimer's disease. At the NSF, he has been a major influence
on policies regulating the biotechnology industry during the Reagan
administration.
   Experts representing the Environmental Defense Fund have charged
that Kingsbury helped formulate regulations that favored the
biotechnology industry and genetic experiments.
   ``Kingsbury's past history has been pro-industry,'' said Rebecca
Goldburg, an EDF scientist. She said Kingsbury and the Reagan
administration were ineffective in setting policies regulating
experiments using organisms that have been altered genetically in
the laboratory.
</TEXT>
