<DOCNO> AP881006-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   10-06 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0622</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, Oct. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>Health Care Costs Are Soaring Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of health care is rising sharply again,
and among the reasons why, incredibly, is the success of past
cost-containment efforts.
   Yes, you read it correctly.
   This seemingly illogical, almost impossible state of affairs _
cost cutting leading to inflation _ illustrates the pernicious
financial nature of the health-care beast, which avoids the most
carefully laid anti-inflation traps.
   The origins of the latest price spurt go back to the early and
mid-1980s when, you might recall, health-care officials in every
area of the industry felt drastic measures were required.
   At that time, according to a consultant on corporate benefits,
the William M. Mercer-Meidinger-Hansen concern, many state Medicaid
programs, private-sector benefit plans and Medicare tackled costs
with a vengeance.
   Among other things, they implemented case-based hospital
reimbursement systems, set up hospital utilization review programs
and shifted costs from employers to employees. Dispensers and users
of services, therefore, would be put on the side of cost
containment. It would be in their financial interest.
   It worked. Hospital utilization and occupancy rates fell.
   While that might seem to be a positive result, it wasn't
entirely so. The reason: To hospitals, each dollar saved through
cost containment was a revenue dollar lost. To correct it, they had
to cut expenses _ or rebuild revenues.
   Cutting expenses can appear easier than it is. For example,
hospitals have many fixed costs for plant and equipment that do no
decline as occupancy rates fall. The situation can force
administrators to seek higher revenues.
   The most frustrating illustration of this, according to the
consulting firm's report, is in ambulatory surgery.
   In designing cost-containment strategies, many sponsors of
health insurance plans identified hospital surgical procedures that
could be performed safely in an outpatient surgical facility.
   These sponsors began to encourage workers to have certain types
of surgery performed on an outpatient basis, thus saving the cost
of a one-day or two-day hospital stay. Employees were offered
financial incentives to do so.
   Now, says Mercer-Meidinger-Hansen, these corporate sponsors are
finding that outpatient facility charges are as high as $3,000 for
as little as a few hours use.
   ``Ironically,'' it states, ``in many instances plan costs would
actually be reduced if these surgeries were again performed in the
hospital, since the cost of one day there can be less expensive
than the surgical facility charge.''
   This is just one illustration of the difficulties involved in
holding the line on health care costs. There are plenty of other
reasons, including the changing natures of health and illness
themselves.
   AIDS, for instance, was not a cost factor until relatively
recently. Now, the Centers for Disease Control estimates that total
expenses for one patient might be as high as $150,000 between
diagnosis and death.
   Other cost problems involve the increasing price of medical
education, an investment that must be recovered; the surging cost
of certain malpractice insurance, and the defensive medical tests
and procedures now being used.
   But much of the inflation problems lie within the nature of the
industry itself. Putting a dollar cost on life remains one of man's
most difficult challenges, one from which even the most hardnosed
executives retreat.
   Meanwhile, many companies and others who sponsor health
insurance plans are confronted with enormous increases in their
bills.
   While the economy in general worries about 4.5 percent
inflation, the consulting firm's report states that many plan
sponsors have seen their bills rise this year by 30 percent to 80
percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Oct. 7.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-SukarnoRemembered ADV13   10-06 0894</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sukarno Remembered, ADV 13,0919</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 13, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two New Books Praise and Assail Indonesia's Co-Founder Sukarno</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The President Sukarno who died in
disgrace 18 years ago is again stirring controversy in the nation
he led to independence from the Dutch after World War II.
   Two recently published books spotlight the leader whose vivid
personality has an almost mythic hold on many Indonesians who refer
to themselves as Sukarnoists.
   In the memoirs of Col. Bambang Widjanarko, his military aide
from 1960 to 1968, Sukarno is portrayed as helplessly buffeted by
political forces beyond his control during an aborted communist
coup Sept. 30, 1965.
   Some critics complained that Bambang's ``Eight Years Near
Sukarno'' glosses over Sukarno's shortcomings, but it is the less
controversial of the two books.
   The other book, in the view of Sukarnoists, should be banned for
blackening the reputation of the nation's co-founder.
   It is titled ``He Who Sows The Wind Will Reap The Storm'' and
says Sukarno was involved in the aborted coup and was a committed
Marxist since his student days in the 1920s.
   Written by Sugiarso Surojo, a former intelligence officer who
now edits a women's magazine, ``He Who Sows'' describes Sukarno as
``a conspirator adept at concealing his true identity.''
   Charges of complicity in the uprising in which six top army
generals were slain are not new. Several military tribunals heard
testimony years ago that Sukarno knew the coup was planned but did
nothing to prevent it.
   Earlier foes also denounced what they saw as his demogoguery,
hedonistic lifestyle and tilt toward the Communist Party, which is
now banned.
   Sukarno remained as president in name only after signing over
power on March 11, 1966, to Maj. Gen. Suharto, who foiled the
revolt five months earlier. Sukarno and Suharto, who is now 66, are
the only presidents this country has known.
   Sugiarso said he was inspired to write his book partly by the
revival of Sukarnoism during last year's general election campaign.
   Thousands of young Indonesians in red T-shirts and headbands
thronged rallies in support of the Indonesian Democratic Party, a
grouping of five political parties, one of which was founded by
Sukarno 61 years ago. The party had been faring poorly and its
leaders calculated correctly that the Sukarno magnetism would help
revive its fortunes.
   With Megawati Sukarno, one of Sukarno's daughters, among the
successful candidates last year, the party increased its
representation in the 500-seat Parliament from 24 to 40 members and
its proportion of the total vote from 7.9 to 11 percent.
   With Sukarnoism making a comeback among youth, Sugiarso said,
his book is intended to balance what he called a lopsided view of
history fostered by the country's founding generation.
   ``The time has come for our national history to be straightened,
written objectively, so as to be a mirror for our future leaders
and for the young generation who have not known their true national
history,'' he said.
   Attorney General Sukarton Marmosudjono described the book as
unethical but rejected calls to ban it. Home Affairs Minister
Rudini also objected to the book and Lt. Gen. Harsudiono Hartas,
chief of the armed forces social and political section, urged a
stop to the Sukarno ``polemic.''
   No sales figures were available but booksellers said it was
moving briskly.
   Sukarno was officially forgotten and rarely mentioned favorably
in ruling circles after his death at the age of 69 from a kidney
ailment June 21, 1970.
   Once hailed for his vision of a unified nation free of Dutch
colonial rule, his economic policies had virtually bankrupted
Indonesia.
   Popular interest in Sukarno was reignited after the government
decided in 1979 to build an elaborate tomb for his remains,
replacing a simple grave that was covered by a faded yellow parasol.
   Newspapers were allowed for the first time in years to mention
his name. Portraits of Sukarno went on sale and a two-week exhibit
of memorabilia attracted throngs. Books he wrote books came off the
banned list.
   Statues of Sukarno and the country's first vice president and
co-founder, Mohammad Hatta, were dedicated in 1980 at the site
where they declared independence on Aug. 17, 1945. Hatta resigned
in 1956, partly as a result of disenchantment with Sukarno's
leadership, and died in 1980.
   Jakarta's efficient new airport was renamed the SukarnoHatta
International Airport three years ago.
   The son of a schoolteacher and a Balinese dancer, Sukarno became
one of the best known nationalists in what then was the Netherlands
East Indies after forming a political party in 1927. The Dutch
sentenced him to four years in prison in 1929.
   Freed in 1931, he was arrested again the following year and
spent the next eight years in exile in the outer islands. His exile
ended when the Japanese invaded during World War II and freed him.
Some Indonesians accused him of collaborating with the Japanese.
   Following their declaration of independence in 1945, Sukarno and
Hatta raised an army and and took to the jungle for a four-year
struggle against the Dutch.
   Although the Dutch captured and again exiled Sukarno in 1948,
his battle for independence stirred world opinion, and the United
Nations urged freedom for the nation. Sukarno was freed in 1949 and
later that year the Dutch relinquished power.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs AMs Oct. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:London'sDaughter ADV11   10-06 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: London's Daughter, ADV 11,0831</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday AMs, Oct 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jack London's Daughter Basks In His Legacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Becky London never answered the call
of the wild and rarely got the attention she craved from her famous
father.
   But despite a somewhat sheltered childhood and unremarkable
life, she remains a striking link to Jack London, a man whose tales
of struggles for survival made him one of America's most beloved
authors.
   If London were alive today, he'd enjoy spinning yarns with his
only surviving child. Becky, 85, has a few of her own, many about
the man she still lovingly refers to as ``Daddy.''
   ``Talking with Becky is like having a chat with her father,''
says Russ Kingman, a London expert and a friend of the writer's
daughter. ``Even her letters read like a Jack London story.''
   Bess ``Becky'' London Fleming has never been one to take
advantage of her father's fame, she says. But recently she's
immersed herself in her roots.
   She began using her maiden name after her husband died in 1982.
Most of her life has been spent in Oakland, the author's home city
for years. Six years ago she moved north into an apartment annex of
the Jack London Bookstore in the Valley of the Moon.
   Occasionally, she visits the nearby ranch, now a state
historical park, where the writer was living when he died in 1916.
She also has made public appearances and lectures, and cheerfully
obliges with anecdotes about him for visitors to her home,
decorated with pictures of cats, dogs and her father, along with
his books _ ``The Call of the Wild,'' ``The Sea Wolf,'' ``White
Fang.''
   It is a fitting devotion for a woman who says proudly that her
paternal connection is still the greatest thing that ever happened
to her.
   With her round face and engaging personality, Becky is ``almost
a clone of her father,'' according to Kingman, who runs the
bookstore in this idyllic Sonoma County community.
   ``She has the same love for other people, the same knack for
making other people feel that they're important, the same bubbly
personality.''
   Both Becky and her sister, Joan, were products of London's first
marriage, to Bess Maddern. They were divorced when Becky was a year
old, and her jealous mother never allowed her to visit her father
at the ranch with his second wife, Charmian.
   Kingman says Joan, who wrote a biography of London and worked
for the AFL-CIO for 30 years before dying in 1972, was the author's
favorite daughter. Becky, who adored him, only had one full day
with him by herself, when Joan was sick. Becky was only 14 when he
died.
   ``Otherwise, Becky was the caboose,'' says Kingman. ``He never
had time for her. It's a tragedy.''
   Though she wishes they could have spent more time together,
there is no trace of bitterness to her voice.
   ``He still is my model of what a father ought to be,'' Becky
London says. ``Of course, he was human, he had his faults.''
   Among her memories are numerous outings the writer had with his
two daughters.
   ``He used to take us to an amusement park in Oakland,'' she
recalls. ``We went to San Francisco with him when we were older,
taking the train, the ferry boat and the cable cars. Oh, how Daddy
loved cable cars!''
   Her father didn't talk a lot about himself with his daughters,
preferring to focus on their lives, she says. It wasn't until she
was about 10, when she was dusting a bookcase and pulled out book
after book he'd written, that she discovered he was famous.
   ``I still remember how dumbfounded I was,'' she says, shaking
her head.
   But the public was aware of his fame. ``It was thrilling to go
out with Daddy because everybody knew him and he was always so
gracious to them,'' she said.
   ``Daddy bought us taffy candy and we'd walk up Market Street and
everybody in the city, it seemed, would stop and talk to him.
Sailors, hobos, businessmen wearing silk hats, ladies in carriages,
boxers _ he knew them all. I was so proud. Sometimes he'd shake
hands and leave them a $5 gold piece.''
   He also took personal charge of the girls' education, sending
them a trunkful of books to read every year. Stories about heroes
were a frequent choice, along with history books.
   Today, Becky London has lost her treasured ability to read
because of deteriorating eyesight. She spends much of her time
chatting with friends, listening to baseball games on the radio _
she's a big fan of the Oakland Athletics and San Francisco Giants _
and savoring positive memories.
   ``I was born an optimist,'' she says. ``I don't worry. I'm happy
all the time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
