<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board says his agency can no longer cover the cost of rescuing
ailing savings institutions without placing ``an exceedingly heavy
burden'' on the industry.
   M. Danny Wall, whose agency regulates the nation's 3,000 S&Ls,
told the Senate Budget Committee Wednesday it will cost $45 billion
to $50 billion to clean up the industry, boosting an earlier
projection by more than one-third.
   In July, Wall said it would cost $31 billion, an increase in
turn from a previous estimate of $22 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two-thirds of Americans surveyed want
to see the rich pay more taxes, while an increasing number of
people are growing disenchanted with the new tax law, according to
a new poll.
   The sixth annual Money magazine survey on Americans and their
money, released Wednesday, also found that many respondents expect
the economy to run into problems in the coming months. But those
surveyed don't expect to see their own financial situations worsen.
   The survey, conducted last spring, was the first taken after
taxpayers had their initial encounter with filing returns under the
new tax law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some food prices have climbed above levels
explainable by the summer drought but no widespread price gouging
of grocery shoppers has been found thus far, congressional
investigators say.
   ``Some price increases do appear higher than warranted by the
drought alone,'' Senate Agriculture Chairman Patrick J. Leahy,
D-Vt., said Wednesday after receiving the report from the General
Accounting Office.
   Retail pasta prices increased 10.4 percent, cereal 7.1 percent
and white bread 8.2 percent from January through June, GAO
officials told the Agriculture Committee.
