   Illinois farmers who received
controversial drought insurance coverage have begun to receive
payments, but for those involuntarily left without policies, the
legal fight continues, officials said.
   Richard Carlson, assistant director of the state Insurance
Department, said Wednesday the Chubb Group has mailed checks for
more than $5 million to Illinois farmers who received the insurance
coverage.
   Chubb, an insurance group, has estimated that 1,058 Illinois
farmers applied for coverage but only 263 of them received drought
insurance policies. Another 715 farmers accepted the company's
double-premium refund offer.
</TEXT>
