<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     10-06 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Tumble, Stocks Post Small Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have slipped further to new two year lows, and
takeover speculation has helped the stock market post a modest gain.
   Congressional investigators, meanwhile, report finding no
widespread price gouging at grocery stores in the wake of the
summer drought.
   In the oil futures market, reports of growing supplies and
speculation about friction among key producers were cited for
sending crude oil prices below $13 a barrel Wednesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate dropped 47 cents to settle at $12.60 a
barrel. The benchmark U.S. crude traded as low as a $12.28 barrel
during a hectic session.
   Over the past month, the near-term crude oil contract price has
fallen $2.19 a barrel to the lowest level since August 1986.
   Prices for refined products traded on the exchange, such as
wholesale unleaded gasoline and home heating oil, also fell.
   Among the rumors sparking fears in the market was talk that
Nigeria had decided to leave the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, and that OPEC Secretary General
Subroto, considered a stabilizing force, would step down. Both
rumors were denied, analysts said.
   Also contributing to the decline was an American Petroleum
Institute report, released after the close of trading Tuesday, that
showed a higher-than-expected increase in crude oil stocks and a
sharp increase in refinery production.
   Stock prices were supported by takeover speculation, analysts
said. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.45 points to
2,106.51 on Wednesday, while advancing issues outnumbered declines
by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks.
   In Washington, D.C., a report from the General Accounting Office
said pasta, cereal and white bread prices rose more between June
and August than they did in the same period last year.
   But Senate Agriculture Committeee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy,
D-Vt., said, ``in general, there do not seem to have been excessive
price increases across a broad range of products that use the
drought as an excuse.''
   In other economic news:
   _More than two-thirds of Americans surveyed want to see the rich
pay more taxes, while an increasing number of people are growing
disenchanted with the new tax law, according to a Money magazine
survey on Americans and their money.
   _The chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, M. Danny
Wall, said his agency can no longer cover the cost of rescuing
ailing savings institutions without placing ``an exceedingly heavy
burden'' on the industry. He told the Senate Budget Committee it
will cost $45 billion to $50 billion to clean up the industry,
boosting an earlier projection by more than one-third.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   10-06 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Chairman Agrees To A Friendly Bank of NY Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of corporate America's longest and most
bitterly contested takeover battles is nearing an end, with Irving
Bank Corp.'s top management accepting a sweetened $1.4 billion
offer from rival Bank of New York Co.
   The announcement Wednesday came one day after Irving lost a key
court battle on its anti-takeover ``poison pill'' defense.
   Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice said he would recommend the board
of directors approve the merger and drop all pending lawsuits and
anti-takeover defenses used to ward off Bank of New York's
year-long advances.
   He also promised to move up his retirement plans and leave after
the deal was completed.
   A special board meeting was set for Friday, although many
banking experts have called the vote a formality.
   ``We're 99 percent there. I believe the board will go along with
Rice,'' said Virginia Adair, a banking analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Under the revised bid, Bank of New York would pay $15 in cash
and 1.675 shares of its own stock for each of Irving's 18.9 million
common shares outstanding. It also included warrants valued at $5 a
share toward the purchase of Bank of New York stock.
   The entire deal would be worth about $76 a share, or around $1.4
billion, about $200 million higher than the hostile offer. The
previous bid had the same amount of cash but slightly less stock
and did not include the warrants.
   Irving shares jumped $3.75 to close at $73.50 on the New York
Stock Exchange, while Bank of New York fell 75 cents to $34.12{.
   Neither side would comment on the turn of events leading to the
tentative pact. But banking analysts agreed Irving was forced to
negotiate with its unwanted suitor after losing Tuesday's court
rulings and in the absence of any friendly ``white knight''
takeover partner.
   The appellate division of the New York State Supreme Court on
Tuesday struck down a key provision of Irving's ``poison pill''
anti-takeover defense.
   The defense would have allowed all Irving shareholders except a
hostile suitor to buy $400 worth of Irving shares for $200 if any
suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock without the
support of Irving's management. The plan was intended to make a
hostile takeover bids prohibitively expensive.
   Irving had vowed to appeal the ruling to the state's Court of
Appeals, but some legal experts questioned whether that court would
have considered the case since the appellate division's decision
was unanimous.
   ``The court ruling closed down one of their last possible escape
routes,'' said Mark Lynch, an analyst with Bear, Stearns & Co.
``They had very few options left.''
   Last spring, Milan-based Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, offered
to merge with Irving as part of a major restructuring of the New
York bank. But it recently withdrew its bid after the Federal
Reserve Board ruled the Italian government agency that owned most
of Banca Commerciale had to supply separate financial imformation.
   The Fed already has given conditional approval for an
Irving-Bank of New York merger.
   A merger would nearly double Bank of New York's size, vaulting
it close to the top 10 of the nation's largest banking companies.
The two had a combined $47.8 billion in assets as of June 30.
   Bank of New York, which owns 4.9 percent of Irving, had
maintained since unveiling its takeover proposal on Sept. 25, 1987,
that a merger would be a good fit because both banks have similar
markets and services. While many analysts agreed, they also
speculated Bank of New York might have feared it would become a
takeover target if a big West Coast or foreign bank decided to
enter the New York market.
   Drexel's Ms. Adair said she expected Bank of New York to proceed
with the strategy it proposed at the start. That includes selling
some of Irving's assets, reducing Irving's Third World debt
portfolio and consolidating facilities.
   Michael Starr, an analyst with Duff & Phelps, said, ``One thing
the Bank of New York is going to have to do is reaffirm client
relationships.
   ``They paid dearly for it (a merger) in both cost and disruption
both companies have incurred,'' Starr said.
   According to the merger proposal, all present directors of
Irving would be invited to join Bank of New York's board of
directors, and all key personnel decisions would be made by a
committee of directors made up of three directors of the Bank of
New York and two current Irving directors.
   If Irving's board backs Rice, Irving also would drop its poison
pill and waive a New York state anti-takeover law that prevents an
unfriendly merger for at least five years.
   When the bid was first made, it had the distinction of being the
first hostile takeover fight between major American banks. It then
became the lengthiest such battle among major U.S. corporations.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 0045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid-Chronology     10-06 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid-Chronology,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bank Bid Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the key events in the Bank of New York Co.'s
hostile takeover bid for control of Irving Bank Corp.:
   Sept. 25, 1987 _ Bank of New York makes an unsolicited $1.4
billion cash-stock bid for Irving.
   Oct. 9 _ Irving's board rejects the bid, activating the
company's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense.
   Nov. 20 _ Bank of New York lowers its offer to $1.2 billion,
citing the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   Dec. 15 _ Irving's board rejects the new bid.
   Jan. 25, 1988 _ Bank of New York lowers its bid to $1.08
billion, citing Irving's decision to increase its fourth-quarter
loan-loss reserve.
   Feb. 16 _ Irving's board rejects the $1.08 billion bid.
   Feb. 25 _ Bank of New York's takeover proposal gets approval
from the Federal Reserve and New York State Banking boards.
   March 15, 28 _ Irving strengthens its poison pill.
   April 14 _ Bank of New York's shareholders give their blessing
to a merger with Irving.
   April 18 _ Banca Commerciale Italiana enters the picture,
offering to buy 51 percent of Irving as part of a major financial
resturcturing announced by Irving that it values at about $1.1
billion-$1.2 billion. The two revise the proposed deal several
times in the following weeks, raising the estimated value to $1.4
billion.
   May 6 _ Irving's shareholders re-elect Irving's directors,
although Bank of New York later challenges the proxy results in
court.
   June 15 _ Bank of New York conditionally offers to raise the
stock portion of its bid, valuing the offer at $1.4 billion. Irving
later rejects the proposal. The previous offer, valued at about
$1.2 billion under current market conditions, stands.
   July 6 _ A New York state court strikes down a provision of
Irving's poison pill. Irving vows to appeal.
   Aug. 19 _ The Fed rules the Italian government agency that owns
most of Banca Commerciale has to supply financial information in
the Irving bid.
   Aug. 29 _ Banca Commerciale withdraws its bid.
   Sept. 7 _ The Fed grants Bank of New York another 90-day
extension to complete the Irving merger.
   Oct. 4 _ The New York State Supreme Court's appellate division
upholds the lower court ruling that struck down a part of Irving's
poison pill.
   Oct. 5 _ Irving announces its chairman now supports a revised
$1.5 billion merger proposal by the Bank of New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
