<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewNissans     10-06 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Nissans,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan: Sports Car, Sedan to Pull Up Sagging Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A. is pinning
hopes for a turnaround in a three-year sales slump on new vehicles
to debut in each of the 1989 and 1990 model years.
   Nissan introduced its 1989 model line on Wednesday with General
Manager Robert Thomas saying the Japanese automaker is looking
toward a restyled Maxima sedan and new 240SX to begin pulling the
company out of the sales doldrums.
   In the spring, Nissan plans to introduce a new version of the
300ZX and a small minivan, called the Axxess, he said.
   ``Our immediate success is riding on these new models,'' Thomas
said.
   Nissan's sales in the United States fell to 660,652 cars and
light trucks in the just-ended 1988 model year from 781,280
vehicles in the 1986 model year _ a 15.4 percent decline.
   ``Sales have not reached expectations for us or for others in
the industry,'' Thomas said. ``We can look to a lot of reasons for
a flat performance, like currency, intensifying competition or even
vacillating buyer moods.
   ``I'm optimistic about the future,'' he said. ``Right now, our
market share hovers around 4 percent. I think we can build that
share to more than 5 percent by the early 1990s, largely on the
strength of the four new models we'll be bringing out in the next
year.''
   But the sales turnaround won't take place immediately if
projections Thomas cited Wednesday are accurate. He said he expects
Nissan to sell about 660,000 vehicles in the 1989 model year, which
would continue the erosion of sales.
   Thomas said the low projections for 1989 stemmed from, among
other things, limited availability of 240SX models, the arrival
later this month of Maximas to dealer showrooms and the yen-dollar
exchange rate.
   ``We also recognize we've got to build up our image,'' he said.
   Thomas also said Wednesday:
   _Nissan's plant in Smyrna, Tenn., has the capacity for another
assembly line, but that no decision has been made about whether to
expand the plant or, if so, what vehicle would be produced there.
   _The joint venture between Nissan and Ford Motor Co. in Avon
Lake, Ohio, would produce a larger minivan than the Axxess. The
Nissan-Ford project is to begin production in 1991 for the 1992
model year.
   _The Axxess will have dual rear sliding doors, instead of the
conventional right side sliding door on other minivans. ``The
advantage (of the Axxess) is our product will have power,
performance and handling,'' Thomas said.
</TEXT>
