<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Aid     10-06 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Aid,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Provides $7.45 Billion In Development Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan provided a record $7.45 billion in
development assistance in 1987, up 32.3 percent from a year
earlier, the Foreign Ministry said Thursday.
   The ministry said in an annual report that Japan was the second
largest foreign aid donor in 1987 after the United States, which
extended $8.77 billion in assistance.
   But Japan's aid ranked 12th as an aid doner when the amount of
aid was compared to the nation's gross national product, the report
said. It said that ratio was 0.31 percent, up 0.01 percentage
points from 1986. Norway was first, having given 1.1 percent of its
gross national product in aid.
   Meanwhile, the government's Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund
said it had extended $3.9 billion in loans to developing nations in
fiscal 1987, up 8 percent from a year earlier. That fiscal year
ended March 31, 1988.
   An OECF official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
credits included: $757 million to Indonesia; $505 million to China;
$435 million to India; $284 million to the Philippines; $272
million to Thailand; and $213 million to South Korea.
</TEXT>
