<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-Trade     10-06 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Trade,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan's Trade Surplus Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan's trade surplus totaled $1.04
billion in September, down 27 percent from the previous month and
down 54 percent from the same month a year ago, the government
reported Thursday.
   The Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics
said exports in September totaled $4.47 billion, down 22 percent
from the previous month, while imports were $3.43 billion, a 20
percent decrease from August.
   The agency said Taiwan registered a total surplus of $7.82
billion for the first nine months of this year, down 48 percent
from the same period last year. Against the United States, Taiwan's
biggest trading partner, the surplus totaled $992.6 million in
September, down 22 percent from August.
   Trade officials attributed the decline of imports and exports
partly to the four-day Mid-Autumn Festival holiday in September.
</TEXT>
