<HEAD>Kuwaiti Newspapers Blast Thatcher Over BP Decision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, The $7.2 billion ..., with one graf to
CORRECT to $12 billion sted $7.2 billion</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-government newspapers Thursday denounced
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government for its
``short-sighted decision'' to slash Kuwait's holdings in the
British Petroleum Co. and warned it will damage relations.
   The newspapers urged Kuwait's government to take retaliatory
measures against Britain's request Tuesday that the Kuwait
Investment Office reduce its holding in BP from 21.68 percent to
9.9 percent over the next year.
   The Kuwait Investment Office, the oil-rich gulf state's
London-based investment arm, has bought up 1.316 billion BP shares
since the British government sold off its one-third stake in the
oil giant last year.
   Kuwait stands to lose nearly $680 million at current market
prices if it cuts its BP holdings to the level the British are
seeking.
   The radical Al-Rai Al-Aam daily newspaper said in an editorial:
``The British decision will inevitably endanger political as well
as trade relations between the two countries.
   ``Despite attempts by the British government to justify its
uncordial and unjust decision, the British step will endanger
British-Kuwaiti relations.''
   The English-language Kuwait Times called the British decision
``a short-sighted step.''
   The newspaper said: ``It scarcely behoves a country like Britain
and a government like Mrs. Thatcher's to make such titanic
intervention as the demand made of Kuwait.
   ``The plain truth is that Kuwait's purchase of the BP shares
was, in effect, a rescue operation by a sincere friend of Britain.''
   The $12 billion BP share sale was a flop with investors because
it coincided with the financial market crash last October. Kuwait
subsequently stepped in as a buyer.
   Kuwait bought 10 percent of BP shares last November and
gradually increased that to 21.68 percent.
</TEXT>
