<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0006 10-06 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0006,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Eroding Amid Supply, Rumors Of More OPEC Divisiveness</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 2nd graf pvs, On the ..., to UPDATE
with early prices today. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Crude futures ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation over burgeoning world oil supplies
and unsubstantiated rumors about further rifts within OPEC have
helped push oil futures below the $13-a-barrel level.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate plunged 47 cents to settle at $12.60 a
barrel Wednesday in heavy, hectic trading. Still, the benchmark
U.S. crude recovered from its intra-day low of $12.28 barrel.
   In early trading today, it was up another 22 cents at $12.82 a
barrel.
   Crude futures prices have not been this low since August 1986. A
month ago, the near-term WTI contract had settled at $14.79.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 1.67 cents to settle
at 39.44 cents a gallon, while home heating oil slipped 0.41 cent
to 37.76 cents a gallon.
   Much of the day's selling was technical in nature, analysts said.
   Oil prices fell sharply on early rumors that Nigeria had decided
to leave the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries and that OPEC General Secretary Subroto, known as a
crafter of compromises, would step down.
   Prices recovered somewhat when the rumors were denied.
   Nauman Barakat, vice president of energy investment at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said ``this market has become so
rumor-sensitive that even if a story doesn't sound credible, there
is a violent reaction.''
   Barakat said at least some of the rumors were being instigated
by floor traders seeking to benefit their own positions. He also
said Saudi Arabia was giving the market a dose of its own
``intensive shock therapy.''
   Saudi Arabia, the world's largest exporter, has voiced threats
that it will continue overproducing unless other OPEC members abide
by their production quotas.
   ``We're in a price war,'' said Peter Beutel, an assistant
director at Elders Futures Inc. Unless the Saudis change their
policy, the only way oil prices will rise is through technical
factors.
   ``There's no hope on the fundamental front,'' he said.
   Even before trading began, the market was poised for a selloff
with the latest statistics from the American Petroleum Institute.
The report, which was released after the close of trading Tuesday,
showed a higher-than-expected increase in crude oil stocks.
   The report also showed a sharp increase in refinery runs. ``It
just scares people to see the refineries looking like they are
going to increase the supply of refined products,'' Beutel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
