<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today in
another sluggish session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.24 to 2,107.75 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers and losers ran about even in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 549 up, 545 down and 547
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 49.44 million shares at
midmorning.
   Stocks have been drifting all week while traders await the Labor
Department report Friday morning on the employment situation for
September.
   Brokers say traders have been especially cautious because of
expectations that the figures will show job growth at a rate faster
than the Federal Reserve would like to see in its efforts to keep
inflation from reviving.
   A good many analysts doubt that the employment figures, however
they turn out, will end the market's recent period of lethargy.
   They note that Wall Street will still have to contend with
memories of last October's crash, whose approaching first
anniversary is getting a lot of publicity, and uncertainties about
the election in November.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Motors dropped \ to
74\; Sears Roebuck gained | to 40], and Union Carbide was unchanged
at 26[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.12 to 153.74. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .12 at 300.09.
