<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-06 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices declined today
in early trading at the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by
bearish crop estimates from an influential private analyst.
   Sparks Commodities' figures put the U.S. soybean crop at 1.543
billion bushels, about 70 million more than the U.S. Department of
Agriculture estimates last month, said Victor Lespinasse, a grains
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The corn crop estimate of 4.474 billion bushels, about 12
million more than USDA's estimate, also was considered bearish and
sparked a flurry of selling in the corn pit, Lespinasse said.
   The six-to-10 day forecast calling for dry weather and ideal
harvesting conditions in major growing regions, as well as
follow-through selling from Wednesday's weak close added additional
pressure to the market, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2} cents to 3{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.23 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents to 2 cents lower with December at $2.91} a bushel; oats were
} cents to 1} cents lower with with December at $2.45 a bushel; and
soybeans were 11 cents to 12 cents lower, with November at $8.11 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures prices were mixed, hogs were mostly lower and
frozen pork bellies were down in early trading at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle opened .02 cent lower to .12 cent higher, with
December at 72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to
.18 cent higher, with October at 81.80 cents a pound; hogs were .27
cent lower to .03 cent higher, with October at 40.02 cents a pound;
and pork bellies were .02 cent to .28 cent lower, with February at
49.17 cents a pound.
   Cattle prices were mixed, hogs were mostly lower and frozen pork
bellies declined in trading Wednesday.
</TEXT>
