<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Burlington-Relocation     10-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burlington-Relocation,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burlington Northern To Transfer Headquarters to Fort Worth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Northern Inc. says the
holding company will transfer its headquarters from Seattle, Wash.,
to Fort Worth by the end of this year, bringing about 20 new
executive-level jobs here.
   Gerald Grinstein, Burlington vice chairman, revealed the plans
Wednesday at the Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce's annual Economic
Outlook Conference.
   Burlington Northern already employs about 750 people in Fort
Worth in the executive offices of Burlington Northern Railroad and
Meridian Oil Co., subsidiaries of Burlington Northern Inc. Meridian
includes the former Southland Royalty Co., which Burlington
Northern bought in 1985.
   In June, Burlington Northern announced that it would spin off
its energy and natural resources companies to Burlington Northern
shareholders. The new company will be called Burlington Resources
Inc., and its headquarters will remain in Seattle.
   Burlington Northern Inc. will be left primarily with its
railroad subsidiary, which operates a 23,500-mile railroad system
in 19 western states and two Canadian provinces.
   The chairman of Burlington Northern Inc., Richard Bressler, is
expected to become the chairman of Burlington Northern Resources as
well and also is likely to remain in Seattle. Bressler has been
chief executive officer of Burlington Northern since 1980. He moved
holding company offices from St. Paul, Minn., to Seattle in 1981.
   Grinstein, through a Burlington Northern spokesman, said the
company ``would have further details later this month.''
   Burlington Northern Inc. officials said it is unclear which
holding company functions would be transferred to Fort Worth. The
Seattle operation has about 60 workers and includes the chief
executive's office.
   The railroad relocated its executive headquarters to Fort Worth
in mid-1984 from St. Paul. Grinstein, as vice chairman of the
holding company, is the ranking executive in Fort Worth. Darius
Gaskins is president of the railroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
