<DOCNO> AP881006-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Spain     10-06 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Spain,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain EEC Presidency Expected To Be Strong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European Commission President Jacques
Delors of France met Thursday with Spanish Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez to discuss Spain's upcoming presidency of the European
Economic Community, Spanish officials said.
   Gonzalez met for an hour with Delors, head of the EEC's
executive branch, and Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez
Ordonez at the prime minister's official Moncloa palace residence,
the officials said.
   Gonzalez then hosted a luncheon for Delors, whose 24-hour visit
was the first of a scheduled tour of the capitals of Portugal,
Greece and Italy.
   Earlier Thursday, Delors spoke with King Juan Carlos for an hour
on European issues, said a palace spokesman, not identified in
keeping with custom.
   Spain is expected to exercise a strong presidency when it takes
over the six-month rotating office next Jan. 1 for the first time
since joining the 12-member trade bloc in 1986, European Commission
member Abel Matutes of Spain told Spanish National Radio Thursday.
   ``The Commission and the Community in general expect a lot from
the Spanish presidency,'' Matutes said.
   ``(Spain) has clear ideas and for that reason there is a
possibility of agreement or at least noticeable progress on
important issues like `social space' and monetary unity,'' Matutes
said.
   Gonzalez led the fight to double economic development funds by
1992 for the EEC's poorer regions, mainly in Spain, Greece,
Portugal, Italy and Ireland.
   The ``social space'' concept, criticized by British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher as bureaucratic ``jargon,'' aims to
increase development funds for poor areas and guarantee basic
workers' rights and salary levels as the borderless economic market
imposes much expected pressure on labor.
   But government sources, who asked not to be named, said
Gonzalez, leader of the ruling Socialist party and a former labor
lawyer, intends to place the concept high on his list of priorities
during the Spanish presidency.
   Gonzalez also has said his government is studying the
possibility of making the peseta, the Spanish currency, a member of
the European Monetary System before late next year.
   The EMS sets limits on fluctuations of the value of several
European currencies to maintain monetary stability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
