<1ST_LINE>u f PM-S&LCrisis 1stLd-Writethru f0019 10-06 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Crisis, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Moving To Boost Resources To Rescue Thrift Institutions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole said today
the next president and Congress must find a solution to the
problems plaguing the savings and loan industry or they ``could
affect the entire U.S. economy.''
   Dole's comments, on the Senate floor, came a day after the
government's top thrift industry regulator raised the estimated
price tag for cleaning up the industry from $31 billion to $45
billion or more.
   Dole, of Kansas, told his fellow senators that the issue
transcends politics.
   ``The time has come to stop the political finger-pointing,'' he
said. ``There is plenty of blame to go around. Congress, the Carter
administration, the Reagan administration, a number of state
legislatures, federal regulators and industry management must all
share some of the responsibility for the thrift industry's
problems,'' Dole said.
   ``We should not let politics affect our better judgment. The
problems facing the thrift industry are serious. If unaddressed,
they could affect the entire U.S. economy,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board, which regulates federally chartered S&Ls, argued for
Congress to raise the ceiling on how much it can borrow to bail out
ailing thrifts.
   Just three months ago, Wall had raised his estimate from $22
billion to $31 billion. Now, he says, the bailout cost is in the
range of $45 billion to $50 billion.
   Some private analysts put the cost as high as $100 billion.
   But Dole said today that more money, by itself, is not the
answer.
   ``It's going to take time to come up with a responsible,
workable solution, and, unfortunately, the 100th Congress doesn't
have any left,'' the Republican leader said, urging President
Reagan's succesor and the Congress sworn in next January to make
finding a solution a top priority.
   The House Banking Committee voted 29-22 on Wednesday to expand
the board's borrowing limit from $10.8 billion in bonds to $15.8
billion. The move is opposed by the industry, which pays an
assessment to retire the 30-year bonds.
   The panel's chairman, Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, said the
Senate would be ``hard put'' to oppose an expansion of the bank
board's borrowing limit, since last summe, when Congress authorized
$10.8 billion in borrowing over three years, the Senate pushed for
a higher limit of $15 billion.
   The bank board already has issued $3.75 billion in bonds. The
Banking Committee bill would permit the bank board to float the
remaining amount as soon as needed rather than spreading it over
the next two years.
   So far this year, the bank board has committed $20 billion to
close or merge 122 troubled thrifts.
   Wall said his agency's resources could cover the newly estimated
cost, but only by placing ``an exceedingly heavy burden'' on the
industry. Thrift institutions currently pay more than twice as much
as their competitors, commercial banks, for deposit insurance and
Wall said that differential would have to continue over 30 years if
his agency did not get help.
   The head of the industry's largest trade group, the U.S. League
of Savings Institutions, said extending the differential for 30
years ``would be an intolerable burden.''
   ``The special assessment has made the difference between profit
and loss for 69 solvent savings institutions so far this year. In
other words, in the process of removing 122 insolvents,
(regulators) have been driving another 69 which are now healthy
closer to becoming problem cases,'' league Chairman Theo H. Pitt
Jr. said.
   Wall said taxpayers would not necessarily have to pay the bill
for boosting the bank board's resources. He listed alternatives,
without endorsing any, that included: requiring institutions to
place 1 percent of their deposits into the S&L insurance fund,
borrowing from the insurance fund for commercial banks or from the
Federal Reserve, and charging borrowers a fee for mortgages
provided by S&Ls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
