<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritainStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0037 10-06 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0037,0235</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange ended
higher, near the day's best levels, Thursday, as trading activity
continued at a relatively brisk pace for the second consecutive day.
   Dealers said the market repeated the pattern of Wednesday's
performance, when modest buying by institutions was more than
matched by aggressive short-covering by market makers.
Short-covering is the buying of shares to fulfill agreements to
sell them.
   ``Market makers have been caught a little bit on the hop here
and didn't have the stock to meet it,'' said one equity salesman.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchane 100-share index rose 12.6
points, or 0.7 percent, to close at 1,838.9, just 2 points below
its best level.
   Volume was 573 million shares, nearly matching Wednesday's
relatively healthy 574.5 million shares.
   Consumer-oriented issues were among the market's major gainers
as players turned to stocks that had suffered recently due to
worries that British interest rates could move yet higher in the
near term.
   Such fears have eased somewhat, with some players cautiously
hoping that interest rates might have peaked.
   Even should bank base lending rates go above their current 12
percent, many players anticipate a bit of a breathing space in the
meantime.
   ``There's no fear at the moment of a sudden hike,'' in rates, a
salesman said.
</TEXT>
