<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-DeLaurentiisTalks     10-06 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-DeLaurentiis Talks,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chapter 11 Movie Maker In Talks With Three Potential Buyers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   De Laurentiis Entertainment Group Inc., which
is in bankruptcy proceedings, said it had received preliminary
offers from three companies interested in buying a controlling
interest.
   The offers came from movie maker Cannon Group Inc., video disk
maker Image Entertainment Inc. and privately held movie company
Atlantic Entertainment Group, DEG announced late Wednesday.
   The production company founded by Italian film maker Dino De
Laurentiis faltered for lack of movie hits and in August filed for
protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
Bankruptcy Code. Under the voluntary bankruptcy proceeding, any
purchase of DEG would need the approval of the company's creditors
and the court.
   DEG assets excluded from the bankruptcy include an affiliated
film-financing company called DEG Film Partners, a newly formed
production arm called Onyx Entertainment and DEG's 32-acre studio
in North Carolina.
   DEG's productions include the movies ``Crimes of the Heart'' and
``Weeds'' and the TV mini series ``Noble House.''
   The company said it had hired Oppenheimer & Co. to evaluate the
offers.
</TEXT>
