<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Eastern-Icahn 2ndLd-Writethru   10-06 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Icahn, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Icahn in Talks to Acquire Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to UPDATE with TWA declining comment; picks up
8th graf pvs bg'ng, On Wednesday, ...; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. Chairman Carl Icahn
reportedly has held discussions with Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank
Lorenzo on the sale of ailing Eastern Airlines to TWA.
   The talks center on a friendly transaction that would be
acceptable to Icahn, Lorenzo and Eastern's unions, according to
sources close to the situation who requested anonymity. Miami-based
Eastern is a major subsidiary of Texas Air.
   The discussions with Icahn included representatives of Eastern's
unions, the sources told The Associated Press today.
   New York developer Donald Trump, meanwhile, said Wednesday that
he was close to agreement with Lorenzo on the sale of Eastern's
three-city air shuttle service to Trump, and that a contract could
be signed by next week. Trump reportedly would pay more than $300
million cash for the shuttle.
   Eastern declined comment on the developments concerning both
Icahn and Trump.
   ``Quite frankly, we're not commenting on either report. It's our
policy not to comment on rumors,'' said Eastern spokesman Robin
Matell in Miami.
   TWA had no comment on the situation, said Mark Buckstein, TWA's
senior vice president and general counsel who was acting as a
spokesman for the airline. Trump and his representatives were
unavailable for comment today.
   On Wednesday, unions at Eastern reacted angrily to a report that
Texas Air was discussing the possible sale of its East Coast
shuttle to Trump.
   The pilots union warned it would seek a court order to block any
such deal, and the head of the machinists union suggested his union
would do the same. The unions successfully blocked an attempt
earlier this year by Texas Air to transfer the shuttle operation
from Eastern to a new subsidiary.
   The unions appear to favor a sale of all of Eastern as a going
concern to a friendly acquirer, while they are opposed to the sale
or transfer of its assets such as the shuttle.
   Icahn was approached a few weeks ago by representatives of the
machinists union at Eastern about the possible sale of the carrier,
Dow Jones Professional Investor Report said today.
   Eastern lost $89.8 million in the second quarter of the year,
and recently laid off around 3,000 employees.
</TEXT>
