<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drexel     10-06 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Denies Defense Motion To Disqualify Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Thursday rejected an
unusual request by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to disqualify the
judge presiding over the government's fraud case against the Wall
Street firm.
   The U.S. 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan said in a
written ruling that the move by attorneys for Drexel and other
defendants in the case to remove U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack
was premature.
   Pollack previously scheduled his own hearing for next Tuesday to
hear arguments on the defense effort to remove him.
   The defense is seeking Pollack's removal on grounds his wife has
an interest in a corporate transaction financed by Drexel.
   Defense attorneys had said in an extraordinary petition to the
appeals court last week that Pollack's involvement created an
``appearance of impropriety.'' They apparently feared that if
Pollack issued a favorable ruling to their clients a higher court
might overturn it on appeal.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, which had sought Pollack
for the case when it sued Drexel Sept. 7 in U.S. District Court,
had challenged the defense effort to remove him in a filing with
the appeals court Wednesday. The SEC said the connection between
Pollack's wife and Drexel was extremely remote and was not grounds
for prejudice.
   Drexel, its high-yield bond financier Michael Milken and others
have been accused by the SEC of violating a range of securities
laws in alleged schemes with Ivan F. Boesky, the now-imprisoned
inside trader who has been cooperating in the government's
investigation of Wall Street corruption.
   The defendants have denied the accusations.
</TEXT>
