<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-U.S.Competition     10-06 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-U.S. Competition,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Current, Former Secretaries Offer Contrasting Views</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin
and one of her predecessors offered sharply contrasting opinions
Thursday on whether the United States has lost its competitive edge
in world trade.
   ``I'm not sure we're behind,'' Mrs. McLaughlin said at the third
annual Rhode Island Conference on Labor-Management Relations.
``Right now, exports are up and the trade deficit is falling.''
   But Ray Marshall, labor secretary during the Carter
administration, said that while some economic measures of
competitiveness may not indicate a decline, the United States has
fallen behind in productivity and real income levels.
   Marshall, in a speech to more than 300 business and academic
officials, said the next president will have to define a clear set
of goals before the country will again become competitive with
other countries.
   ``We have a passive trade policy. They have an active trade
policy,'' he said. ``The country with an active trade policy will
win because they know where they want to get and how they're going
to get there.''
   Mrs. McLaughlin, in an interview and an upbeat speech to the
group, disagreed and said the Labor Department's present programs
will get the job done.
   The United States, unlike Japan and some other Western
countries, does not have a centralized economy, so the government
cannot impose the goals that Marshall suggested, Mrs. McLaughlin
said.
   The speakers at the conference agreed that more attention should
be paid to improving management systems and the education and
services provided to workers.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said issues such as parental leave should be
negotiated between unions and management, rather than imposed by
the federal government.
   ``I'm saddened that they seem to want to push for federal
legislation,'' she said. ``If there's federal legislation, then
there's less incentive to negotiate.''
   Robert B. McKersie, an industrial relations professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said such issues give unions
a wedge to organize industries where workers have so far not been
interested.
   ``While unions have seen little recent organizing success, it
appears that employees do not appear to be satisfied with the
status quo,'' McKersie said. ``The workforce appears to have
unsatisfied demands in areas such as pay equity, career
development, day care, (and) maternity leave.''
   Marshall, now a professor at the University of Texas, said
productivity per worker, in and of itself, is not the reason the
country has declined relative to Korea, Japan and other economic
powers.
   ``We're four times as productive as the Koreans. The problem is
the wage differential is six to one,'' he said. ``So even if we're
more productive, they can undercut us with lower wages.''
   Marshall added that the United States will never be able to cut
wages to the point where they are competitive with the Koreans and
should not try to do so.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said she views education as the key to keeping
the workforce competitive.
   ``Simply put, we have to get serious, together, many of you in
this room, about public education,'' she said. ``The fact is that
the current pool of applicants for entry-level jobs lacks basic
skills such as reading, writing, problem-solving and
communication.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     10-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $182 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 453 money market mutual
funds rose $182 million in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $267.15 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $267.6 million drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 224 general purpose funds rose $445.7 million to $85.12
billion, assets of 103 broker-dealer funds dropped $916.2 million
to $112.47 billion, and assets of 126 institutional funds rose
$652.5 million to $69.56 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.48 percent from 7.43 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose, to 7.43 percent from 7.40
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
35 days, up from 34 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.03 percent as of Wednesday from 6.02 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.11 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.76
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.75 the
previous week. Yields were 8.09 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.04
percent; 8.33 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.31 percent; and
8.59 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
