<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0247</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices advanced on rumors of
purchases by the Soviet Union and China while soybeans declined in
trading Thursday at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices hit new contract highs amid talk that the Chinese
may be in the market for U.S. wheat and reports that the Common
Market plans to raise their wheat export prices, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``That would make theirs less competitive and ours more
competitive,'' he said.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union bought a million tons of corn
sparked a buying wave in the corn pit, and continued hope that the
U.S.-Soviet grain pact may be near added support to prices,
Lespinasse said.
   Soybean prices fell in all but one contract month, pressured by
bearish crop estimates from influential private analyst Sparks
Commodities, he said. Sparks' figures put the U.S. soybean crop at
1.543 billion bushels, about 70 million more than the U.S.
Department of Agriculture estimates last month.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 6\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.32{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 4{ cents higher, with December at $2.98 a bushel; oats were
1 cent lower to 1 cent higher, with December at $2.46{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 10 cents lower to 2{ cents higher, with November
at $8.13 a bushel.
