<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0503</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market struggled to a small gain
Thursday as traders awaited a new signal on the pace of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.24 to 2,107.75,
posting a single-digit change for the fifth consecutive session.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
782 up, 612 down and 530 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 153.57 million
shares, down from 175.13 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 182.58 million shares.
   Stocks have been drifting all week while traders await the Labor
Department report Friday morning on the employment situation for
September.
   Brokers say investors have been especially cautious because of
expectations that the figures will show job growth at a rate faster
than the Federal Reserve would like to see in its efforts to keep
inflation from reviving.
   A good many analysts doubt that the employment figures, however
they turn out, will end the market's recent period of lethargy.
   They note that Wall Street will still have to contend with
memories of last October's crash, whose approaching first
anniversary is getting a lot of publicity, and uncertainties about
the election in November.
   None of the 30 stocks that make up the Dow moved as much as a
point. Among actively traded blue chips, General Motors dropped ]
to 74[; Sears Roebuck lost \ to 39{, and Union Carbide was down \
at 25~.
   TW Services climbed 1} to 26|. The investment firm of Coniston
Partners offered $28 a share for the TW stock it doesn't already
own.
   Hospital Corp. of America rose 1\ to 43]. The company said a
committee of directors served notice that it would reject a
$47-a-share buyout proposal being considered by a management group.
Some traders evidently took that as a possible prelude to another
bid.
   Pillsbury led the active list, down \ at 57~. Grand Metropolitan
PLC said it completed a financing package for its $60-a-share offer
to acquire Pillsbury.
   Seagate Technology, which said late Wednesday it would post a
loss for its most recent quarter, dropped | to 7] in the
over-the-counter market.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $5.48 billion, or 0.20
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .31 to 153.93.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.76 to 312.66, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 0.53 at 272.39.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.63 to 385.15. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 301.14, up 1.17.
</TEXT>
