<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     10-06 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply fell in late September, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally
adjusted $3,032.5 billion in the week ended Sept. 26 from $3,037.4
billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, decreased to a seasonally adjusted
$3,851.3 billion from $3,856.9 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose to a
seasonally adjusted $784.9 billion from $784.8 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,030.7 billion, a 3.8
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks. M3 averaged $3,843.6 billion, up 5.7 percent, while M1
rose 5.6 percent to an average of $782.6 billion.
   The Fed said in mid 1988 that it reaffirmed its target for
annual growth in M2 and M3 at between 4 percent and 8 percent,
which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5
percent. The Fed has not set a specific target range for M1 since
early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $81 million in
the week ended Sept. 28, compared with a decline of $162 million a
week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $914 million in the
week ended Wednesday, up from $556 million in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves averaged $575
million in the two weeks ended Oct. 5, in contrast to average net
borrowed reserves of $117 million in the previous two-week period.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $282.8 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, down from $283.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
