<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-06 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rumored Chinese Purchase, Common Market Plans For Exports Spark
Wheat Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rumored Chinese plan to buy U.S. wheat and talk
that the Common Market plans to raise their wheat export prices
triggered a rally in wheat futures prices Thursday at the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Expectations that the Chinese may be in the market for wheat
also supported wheat prices, analysts said.
   In other markets, corn prices advanced, soybeans declined,
cattle prices were mostly higher, hog prices were mostly lower,
frozen pork bellies slid, gold gained, silver was lower and oil
prices dipped.
   Wheat prices hit new contract highs amid continued hope for a
Chinese purchase and the rumors of the Common Market's plans, said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Higher export prices of Common Market wheat ``would make theirs
less competitive and ours more competitive,'' he said.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union bought a million tons of corn
sparked a buying wave in the corn pit, Lespinasse said.
   Soybean prices were pressured by bearish crop estimates from
influential private analyst Sparks Commodities, he said.
   Wheat settled 3} cents to 6{ cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.32} a bushel; corn was { cent to 4{
cents higher, with December at $2.98 a bushel; oats were 2 cents
lower to { cent higher, with December at $2.46\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 10\ cents lower to 2} cents higher, with November at
$8.12} a bushel.
   Cattle prices surged at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, where
traders bought on ideas that supplies will tighten up in the fourth
quarter. They seemed to ignore near-term fundamentals of lackluster
boxed beef sales and slow feed-yard trade _ both indications that
demand is slight, said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago with
Thompson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   The hog market fell under the influence of lower cash hog
prices, while pork bellies were pressured because of large stocks
in storage, Stanley said.
   Cattle prices settled unchanged to .57 cent higher with October
at 72.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .43
cent higher, with October at 81.77 cents a pound; hogs were .38
cent lower to .10 cent higher, with October at 40.02 cents a pound;
and pork bellies were .20 cent to .78 cent lower, with February at
48.67 cents a pound.
   Gold prices at the New York Commodity Exchange rallied on
expectations that U.S. Labor Department figures to be released
Friday would show an improved job picture for September, said
analyst Jack Barbanel of Gruntal & Co. Inc. in New York.
   A slight stabilization in crude oil prices, which have plunged
lately, also was considered slightly bullish, he said.
   Gold was $2.70 to $3.10 higher, with the contract for delivery
in October at $403.80 a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent to 1.5 cents
lower, with October at $6.288 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures prices settled mostly lower after a rally on mostly
technical factors earlier in the session at the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate rose 6 cents
to settle at $12.66 a barrel, but other contract months settled as
much as 15 cents lower. The near-term contract had been up as much
as 30 cents during the session.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose .06 cent to settle at
39.50 cents a gallon, while home heating oil slipped 0.52 cent to
37.24 cents a gallon. Other contract months finished lower.
</TEXT>
