<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Icahn-Lorenzo     10-06 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Icahn-Lorenzo,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Eastern Sale to TWA Reunites Former Opponents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reported talks on Texas Air Corp. possibly
selling its troubled Eastern Airlines subsidiary to rival Trans
World Airlines Inc. bring two former bitter foes back together.
   Carl Icahn, head of TWA, and Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Texas
Air, are tenacious financiers who warred over control of TWA three
years ago.
   A lot has changed since then, for both men and for the wild
world of the deregulated airline business.
   Lorenzo, whose Texas Air empire went on to acquire Eastern for
$676 million after his TWA bid failed, apparently has decided that
running an unwieldy and fractious airline company is too much
trouble.
   He is believed to be looking to sell parts or all of Miami-based
Eastern, which has been frought with labor difficulty and
staggering losses before and since Lorenzo took over.
   For Icahn, a well-known takeover strategist who has chased
mammoth-sized companies ranging from USX Corp. to Texaco Inc. in
the past few years, the acquisition of Eastern would make his the
largest U.S. airline in terms of revenue passenger miles, an
industry measurement of capacity.
   According to figures of the Air Transport Association, a
Washington trade group, Eastern and TWA's combined capacity last
year totaled 68.9 billion revenue passenger miles. The leading U.S.
airline last year in capacity was United, with 66.2 billion revenue
passenger miles.
   Eastern's militant workers, who have persistently characterized
Lorenzo as a union buster, have been included in talks with Icahn
on the possible sale of the airline to him, sources familiar with
the situation said Thursday.
   In an ironic twist, that recalls the move by TWA's workers in
1985 to talk with Icahn about possibly buying that airline, which
Lorenzo was seeking in order to strengthen the operations of his
other carrier, Continental.
   At that time, TWA's pilots and machinists promised Icahn
hundreds of millions of dollars in labor concessions if he took
control, largely because they feared Lorenzo would gut TWA and
replace them with lower-paid workers, a strategy Lorenzo had used
at Continental earlier.
   After a seesaw struggle that lasted for several months, Icahn
acquired a controlling stake in TWA as part of a broader
arrangement to eventually take the airline private, which is
expected to be completed soon. Lorenzo's Texas Air got about $50
million for selling its interest in TWA to Icahn.
   Since the TWA takeover, Icahn has faced his own labor problems,
beginning with a bitter strike by flight attendants in 1986 that
left thousands out of work, replaced by new hires at lower pay.
   Although the strike failed, the flight attendants union has
continued to challenge Icahn and petitioned the Department of
Transportion to review his fitness to run the airline earlier this
year.
   More recently, Icahn has incurred the wrath of TWA's pilots, who
claim he broke promises to them when he initially acquired control
of the airline. The pilots have sued him on grounds he is borrowing
against the airline's properties without making crucial long-term
investments in equipment.
   ``The solvency of the airline is in question,'' TWA pilots union
chief Thomas Ashwood said in announcing the lawsuit last month.
   ``We won't stand idly by while Carl Icahn strips our airline of
assets and keeps it from growing financially stronger, from buying
airplanes and from improving service to our passengers because of
heavy debt.''
   Icahn has denied the charges of both unions, saying he was
``dismayed'' by their actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-06 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Quiet Trading; Gold Continues Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved narrowly higher Thursday as
traders awaited Friday's release of unemployment figures for
September.
   Gold prices also rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a late bid of $403.50 for a troy ounce of gold, up from $400.30
late Wednesday.
   Dollar trading was very quiet, but some investors adjusted their
positions in advance of the Labor Department's unemployment report,
said James T. McGroarty, a vice president at Discount Corp.
   Traders were waiting in particular to see what changes there
would be in non-farm payroll statistics to be issued with the
jobless report, McGroarty said.
   The market expected the non-farm payroll to have increased by
about 300,000 to 330,000 workers last month, analysts said.
   Robert Ryan, senior trader at Irving Trust Co., said the dollar
likely would slip if the payroll number fell short of expectations.
   Traders would interpret an increase in the non-farm payroll as a
sign of economic strength. Traders believe the Federal Reserve is
more likely to rein in credit _ moving interest rates higher _ when
the economy is robust.
   The dollar tends to rise along with interest rates.
   Once the unemployment report has been digested, the market will
look forward to next week's release of U.S. trade deficit figures,
Ryan said.
   Overseas trading in the dollar also was slow Thursday in
anticipation of Friday's jobless figures.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar slipped 0.18 yen to close at 133.30 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 133.45 yen and in New York, the dollar
rose to 133.645 yen from late Wednesday's 133.38.
   The dollar edged upward against the British pound. It cost
$1.6935 to buy one pound in London, cheaper than $1.6955 late
Wednesday. In New York, the pound was quoted at $1.6927, compared
with late Wednesday's $1.69385.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.86585 West German marks, up from
1.86475; 1.5847 Swiss francs, up from 1.5826; 6.3570 French francs,
up from 6.3440; 1,391.75 Italian lire, up from 1,3900.00; and
1.20995 Canadian dollars, up from 1.20945.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8641 West German marks, up from
1.8625; 1.5830 Swiss francs, down from 1.5865; 6.3475 French
francs, down from 6.3540; 2.1000 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1020;
1,388.75 Italian lire, down from 1,390.475; and 1.2116 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2075.
   Gold prices closed above $400 overseas, catching up to bullion's
performance in New York on Wednesday.
   Gold jumped in London to a late bid price of $403.35 a troy
ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $396.00, and it rose in
Zurich to a bid $403.90, compared with $395.40 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, bullion climbed $5.27 to close at a bid
$405.73.
   Gold continued to advance on the Commodity Exchange in New York,
closing at $403.80 a troy ounce, up from $400.80 on Wednesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.34 a troy ounce, compared
with Wednesday's $6.19.
   On the Commodity Exchange, silver closed at $6.288 a troy ounce,
down from $6.298 on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
