<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1820EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Deere-UAW     10-06 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deere-UAW,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere-UAW Contract Includes Pay Raise, Job Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union workers at Deere & Co. reportedly
would get their first general pay increases since 1981, as well as
boosts in retirement benefits and greater job security under terms
of a tentative contract agreement.
   The contract proposal between Deere and the United Auto Workers
calls for an average pay raise of 44 cents per hour in the first
year of the proposed three-year contract, according to Thursday's
edition of the Journal Star of Peoria.
   Currently, the 13,500 UAW workers at Deere earn an average
$15.47 per hour, or $32,177 per year based on a 40-hour week.
   The newspaper, citing unidentified sources within the company
and the union, reported that Deere workers would receive bonuses of
approximately 3 percent, paid in lump sums, in each of the next two
years of the contract.
   Deere's union work force has not received a general pay raise
since 1981. It has given cost-of-living increases using a formula
tied to the consumer price index.
   Besides wage hikes, the union won a three-step increase in early
retirement benefits, the paper reported.
   In the contract's first year, the monthly pension benefit for
those on early retirement would jump from $1,205 to $1,400. The
monthly benefit would reach $1,500 in the second year and $1,600 in
the final year of the pact.
   The union also claimed significant gains in the contract's job
security plan. The proposed contract would guarantee jobs for all
workers employed at the time the pact is ratified.
   The company would only be able to lay off protected employees in
times of high inventories, labor disputes, plant closings, sale of
a division of the company or ``an act of God.''
   Ratification votes are scheduled this weekend at Deere factories
and parts warehouses in Illinois, Iowa, Atlanta, Minneapolis and
Denver.
   The tentative agreement capped a marathon 20-hour bargaining
session. Deere and the UAW negotiated daily for nearly two months
before the settlement was announced at 5:08 a.m. Saturday, more
than five hours after the current labor contract expired.
   The new contract would take effect immediately upon ratification
and would run through midnight Sept. 30, 1991.
   If the contract is ratified, Deere and the union will have
avoided a repeat of the bitter five-month strike in 1986-87 that
ended after 163 days with employees' acceptance of a wage freeze
and other concessions.
   The union hopes to rekindle contract negotiations with
Caterpillar Inc. immediately upon ratification of the Deere
contract. The UAW has been meeting with the Peoria-based
Caterpillar for two months at a site in Bridgeton, Mo., outside St.
Louis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
