<DOCNO> AP881006-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ashland-Spill     10-06 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ashland-Spill,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland Claims Innocence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. Thursday entered a not guilty
plea and asked for a jury trial on criminal negligence charges in
the Jan. 2 tank collapse that fouled two major rivers with diesel
fuel.
   A spokesman for the Kentucky-based company, which publicly
admitted errors that figured in the collapse, declined to say
whether Ashland attorneys are attempting to negotiate a bargain
with prosecutors.
   ``We're having conversations with the U.S. Attorney. We're still
interested in doing that,'' said Ashland spokesman Dan Lacy.
   A federal grand jury on Sept. 15 returned a two-count indictment
accusing Ashland of violating the Clean Water Act and the 1899
Refuse Act. Prosecutors say neither law requires the government to
prove the pollution was intentional.
   If convicted on both counts, Ashland could be fined $400,000
plus double the damage caused by the spill.
   The spill occurred when a steel tank at the company's Floreffe
terminal burst as it was being filled for the first time since the
World War II-era structure was dismantled near Cleveland and
reassembled south of Pittsburgh.
   An independent study blamed the collapse on a dime-size flaw
near one of the welds used in reassembling the tank.
   Besides failing to obtain all the necessary local permits to
erect the tank, Ashland admitted violating industry standards by
not filling the vessel with water to test its strength.
   Ashland Chairman John Hall said Jan. 27 that employees
responsible for moving the tank were told more than a year earlier
about faulty welds in the vessel walls. A memo describing the
faults wasn't uncovered by senior management until nearly three
weeks after the tank collapsed, he said.
   Ashland maintains it is unfairly being prosecuted.
   ``We've spent $13 million in reimbursements and cleanup costs,''
Lacy said. ``We don't feel that any of our conduct justifies a
criminal penalty.''
   An estimated 3.8 million gallons of oil gushed from the tank as
it crumpled. Most of the oil was contained by a dike, but an
estimated 715,000 gallons entered the Monongahela River and flowed
into the Ohio.
   Tap water service was discontinued to 23,000 suburban Pittsburgh
residents for a week after the spill, and water supplies for nearly
a million other residents in three states along the Ohio River was
threatened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
