<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewMercedes     10-06 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Mercedes,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercedes Prices Heading Up Slightly For '89</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSE POINTE SHORES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The formidable price tags on
1989 Mercedes-Benz automobiles will rise a modest 1.7 percent over
1988, and the company is testing a new used-car warranty program,
officials said Thursday.
   Prices for the West German-made luxury cars will range from
$30,980 for the 190 diesel sedan, to $79,840 for the two-door
560SEC.
   The best-selling car in the United States is the Ford Escort,
with a base price of about $7,500, less than a tenth of the
560SEC's sticker.
   Erich Krampe, president and chief executive officer of
Mercedes-Benz of North America Inc., said he doesn't expect any
price fluctuations in 1989 because of the exchange rate between the
U.S. dollar and the West German mark.
   He said he was happy with the company's sales performance
despite slipping a little from last year's level of about 80,000
cars. He said during the past year, Mercedes had restructured
itself and it's paying off.
   The luxury car market, of which Mercedes holds a significant
share, will continue to grow, Krampe said, and competition in it
will increase as Toyota and Nissan introduce their Lexus and
Infiniti lines next year.
   ``The overall luxury market, there is a lot of steam in there,''
Krampe added.
   But along with holding its volume of new car sales about the
same level, Mercedes is looking at improving its used-car
operations through a pilot warranty program in 20 dealerships
nationwide.
   ``We want to test how it works on the dealer level, customers
and our own administration,'' Krampe said.
   For cars less than 8 years old and with less than 100,000 miles,
the program would offer a 12-month, bumper-to-bumper warranty. The
program started a few weeks ago and will be assessed in December,
Krampe said.
   Dealers would set the cost of the warranty.
   Officials said about 60 percent of the new Mercedes sold are
bought by former Mercedes owners. The cars retain 65 to 70 percent
of their original value in two years and 40 percent to 45 percent
after five years, they added.
   All of the new '89 Mercedes will be equipped with anti-lock
brake systems and driver-side air bags. Some cars will have
passenger-side air bags as standard equipment.
   The average new Mercedes buyer is 40 to 43 years old and comes
from a household with an income of about $100,000 annually, Krampe
said.
</TEXT>
