<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Scherer     10-06 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scherer,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vote For New Capsule Maker Board Members Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware court has upheld a proxy vote electing
new R.P. Scherer Corp. board members backed by dissident
shareholders who want to sell the gelatin capsule company, Scherer
said Thursday.
   Scherer attorneys were reviewing the ruling received late
Wednesday, and had not decided whether to appeal, company
spokeswoman Jayne A. Colombo said.
   The decision was hailed by Karla Scherer Fink and John S.
Scherer, both children of the company's late founder and members of
the board of directors, who lead the shareholder group pressing for
the sale of the company.
   ``Yesterday's decision in Delaware is the latest in a series of
victories for R.P. Scherer stockholders, who now are several steps
closer than they were a week ago to maximizing their investments
through sale of the corporation,'' John Scherer said in a news
release.
   The Delaware Chancery Court ruling that upheld the contested
election of dissident-backed Theodore Souris to the board.
   Karla Fink and John Scherer control a total of about 38 percent
of the company's outstanding shares. Mrs. Fink's estranged husband,
Peter Fink, Scherer's president and chief executive officer, and
management have opposed a sale of the company.
   Souris was elected in the Aug. 17 proxy vote to replace Peter
Dow, who opposes a sale of the company, on the 11-member board.
   The company did not contest the re-election of Peter Fink, who
ran unopposed, or the election of dissident backed Frederick Frank
to replace board member Richard Manoogian.
   Even before the outcome of the chancery court case, 10 members
of the Scherer board had voted last Friday to hire Goldman, Sachs &
Co. to consider possible moves that could include the sale of the
company.
