<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PanAm-Labor     10-06 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pan Am-Labor,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am Transport Workers Vote for Arbitration in Contract Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the largest union at Pan Am Corp.
have voted to submit their contract dispute with the financially
pressed airline to binding federal arbitration, union officials
said Thursday.
   In August, the Transport Workers membership rejected a new
cost-cutting contract that had been agreed to by its leadership and
Pan Am. The airline has already accepted arbitration in talks with
the Transport Workers.
   The union represents about 5,900 mechanics, aircraft service
personnel and flight dispatchers at New York-based Pan Am, the
nation's eighth-largest airline.
   Details of the vote weren't immediately available.
   In announcing the vote, Transport Workers officials said the
union will now sit down with Pan Am management to set up the ground
rules for the procedure and choose an arbitration panel.
   On Wednesday, Pan Am reached a tentative contract agreement with
leaders of its flight attendants union.
   Details of the new flight attendants' contract, which must be
ratified by the union's membership, were not disclosed. Pan Am said
in a statement that the contract provides for cost reductions
similar to those agreed on earlier this year with the two unions
representing pilots and flight engineers at the airline.
   The new agreement provides for labor concessions by the 4,500
flight attendants at Pan Am, according o a source close to the
negotiations. Pan Am has been seeking around $90 million in wage
reductions from its flight attendants.
   The ratification vote is expected to be completed in
mid-November.
   Pan Am, which lost $88.4 million in the first half of the year,
believes it needs about $540 million over three years in pay cuts
and other concessions to turn itself around. The contract with the
Transport Workers would have saved the airline about $81 million
over the next three years, according to both the union and Pan Am.
   The airline has imposed $35 million in cuts on employees
represented by the Teamsters union under federal labor rules. The
unions representing pilots and flight engineers agreed to cuts
totaling about $240 million over three years.
</TEXT>
