<HEAD>Panel Votes Against Pratt's Request to Block Trump Property Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Casino Control
Commission has rejected an attempt by Pratt Hotel Corp. to block
developer Donald Trump from bidding on a disputed piece of lan Division
of Gaming
Enforcement could take action if it wanted.
   At issue is land most recently controlled by Columbus Plaza
Associates, a partnership that declared bankruptcy more than a year
ago.
   Pratt, which owns the Sands Hotel & Casino, wants to acquire the
land for a parking garage to serve the proposed conversion of the
stalled Penthouse project into the Sands Hollywood Casino Hotel.
   Last month, Pratt bid $14 million for the property before a
federal bankruptcy court judge.
   Five days later, Trump bid $16 million for the same land.
   Pratt President William Weidner accused Trump of trying to block
the Sands project. Penthouse Ltd., supported by Pratt, asked the
commission to bar Trump from buying the land.
   Trump has opposed the Sands Hollywood project, saying that it
does not have sufficient on-site parking and that it would create
serious traffic problems in downtown Atlantic City. But he denies
trying to buy the land to block the rival's project.
   The DeMatteis Organization of New York has outbid both Pratt and
