<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-A&P-Delchamps     10-06 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-A&P-Delchamps,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A&P Ups Stakes, Making $30-A-Share Offer for Delchamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTVALE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co., spurned
by the management of Delchamps Inc., has taken its $210 million
offer for the supermarket company directly to shareholders.
   Michael J. Rourke, A&P's vice president of communications, said
Wednesday A&P decided to begin a $30-per-share tender offer after
three unsuccessful attempts in three years to convince Delchamps
executives that a merger was in the best interest of shareholders.
   Delchamps stock closed at $27 a share, up $2.50, in
over-the-counter trading Wednesday.
   In 1987, A&P withdrew an offer of $27 per share just after the
stock market crash. In October 1986, it bid $23 and was turned down
by Delchamps management.
   Delchamps Chairman Alfred Delchamps has said his Mobile,
Ala.-based company prefers to remain independent.
   A&P wants to acquire the 101 Delchamps supermarkets in Alabama,
Mississippi, Louisiana and along the Florida Gulf coast to
strengthen its presence in the South.
   ``We are very thin in our store coverage of that region,''
Rourke said.
   A&P, with 1987 sales of $9.6 billion, currently operates 1,170
stores, including Waldbaum's, Kohl's, Food Emporium and Super Fresh
stores in the U.S. and Dominion food stores in Canada.
   Delchamps had annual sales of about $700 million last year.
   A&P's offer is contingent on the company acquiring a majority of
Delchamps stock and will expire Nov. 4, according to Rourke.
</TEXT>
