<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-OPEC     10-06 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-OPEC,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Mexico To Protest OPEC Overproduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico plans to file an ``energetic protest''
with the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries over the
failure of some cartel members to stay within their production
quotas, according to a report here.
   The government oil monopoly Pemex on Tuesday blamed OPEC
overproduction for the glut on world markets that caused petroleum
prices to reach a two-year low this week.
   Oil prices also have been depressed by speculation that OPEC
overproduction would continue in the near-future, due to
disagreements among cartel members over output quotas.
   Mexico, the world's sixth-largest oil producer, does not belong
to OPEC but closely monitors the 13-member cartel's pricing and
production policies.
   The Excelsior news service on Thursday quoted an official with
the Energy, Mines and State-Owned Industries Department as saying
the government planned ``an energetic protest against OPEC members
for the lack of seriousness and responsibility in meeting their
fixed production platforms.''
   The department oversees Pemex's operations.
   Excelsior quoted the department official as saying Mexico had
lost $2 billion in anticipated revenue so far in 1988 because of
depressed market prices.
   A department spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
refused to confirm the Excelsior report but said the government
soon would decide what action, if any, it would take towards OPEC.
   Rogelio Sotomayor, chairman of the Chamber of Deputies' Treasury
Committee, said Wednesday that Mexico would maintain its oil
exports at current levels to generate necessary revenue and avoid
government cuts in social spending.
   Citing OPEC overproduction, Mexico on Tuesday announced it had
cut the price of its light crude exports to Asia from $13.50 to
$11.80 a barrel.
   Mexico produces about 2.5 million barrels of crude a day and
exports 1.35 million barrels a day _ about half of that to the
United States, according to Pemex.
   First quarter oil exports accounted for $1.8 billion in revenue,
according to the National Statistics Institute. Crude exports
generated $7.9 billion in all of 1987.
</TEXT>
