<2ND_LINE>AM-HCA Buyout,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HCA Board Committee Rejects Management-Led Leveraged Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special committee of Hospital
Corporation of America's board of directors rejected on Thursday a
$3.3 billion leveraged buyout proposal from a management group led
by Chairman Thomas F. Frist.
   The committee decided the offer of $47 cash per share from the
group was not ``in the best interest of the HCA shareholders,''
according to an HCA news release.
   ``The committee reconfirmed that it has not made any decision to
sell the company,'' the statement said. ``The committee is prepared
to consider any proposal which management or others may choose to
make.''
   Frist, an unnamed group of HCA managers and ``certain third
parties'' offered to buy the company's 70.6 million outstanding
shares in mid-September.
   In a leveraged buyout, an purchaser uses mostly borrowed money
to buy a company and repays it through cash flow or asset sales.
   HCA stock rose $1.62{ to $43.75 a share Thursday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   HCA, which owns or operates nearly 400 hospitals worldwide,
making it one of the world's biggest hospital chains, established
the special committee to review the proposal.
   The committee said the decision to reject the proposal from
Frist's group was made on the advice of its independent financial
advisor, Morgan Stanley & Co. Inc.
   The company reported in July that its profits for the quarter
ending June 30 increased by 15 percent, partly because of increased
inpatient and outpatient revenue.
   HCA sold 104 of its less profitable hospitals just over one year
ago to a new employee-owned company, HealthTrust Inc.
   Frist was unavailable for comment Thursday, and HCA spokesman
David McFadden would not comment on the committee's action.
</TEXT>
