<HEAD>Cooper Cos. Agrees To Sell Eye Surgery Business To Nestle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cooper Cos. Inc. has agreed to sell its
eye surgery business for $325 million to a subsidiary of Swiss
conglomerate Nestle SA, the company said Thursday.
   Cooper signed a letter of intent with Alcon Laboratories Inc.
for the sale of its Irvine, Calif. unit, Cooper Surgical, which
sells some $300 million in eye surgery equipment each year, said
company spokesman Gene Elsbree.
   Cooper Surgical is an operating unit of Palo Alto-based Cooper
Cos., and formerly was part of Coopervision, Cooper's eye care
subsidiary.
   ``Alcon is a major company in the vision industry, and
Coopervision has had a long relationship with the company,''
Elsbree said.
   In 1984, Nestle attempted to buy Coopervision, but the Federal
Trade Commission blocked the deal.
   Cooper Cos., a health care products concern, has cut operations
and intends to sell off all of its businesses. The company, which
has outstanding debt of about $700 million, has been selling off
businesses since it announced plans to liquidate last May.
   Earlier this year, Cooper sold Coopervision's U.S. contact lens
solutions business to Wesley-Jessen, a Chicago subsidiary of
Schering-Plough Corp., for $40 million. It also sold the
international segment of that business to Ciba-Geigy, a Swiss drug
company, for $50 million.
   Elsbree said Cooper is discussing the sale of its $500 million
medical diagnostic subsidiary, Cooper Technicon, the Coopervision
worldwide contact lens business, and a small plastic and
reconstructive surgery products unit.
</TEXT>
