<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MerrillLynch-Offices     10-06 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Merrill Lynch-Offices,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Closing Up To 10 Retail Offices Nationwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch & Co. Inc. is closing up to
10 offices nationwide due to slow business, the company said
Thursday.
   ``I've only been told of ten and they are not definite yet,''
said Fred Yager, a spokesman for the giant brokerage firm, said in
a telephone interview from Merrill's New York headquarters.
   If there are closures, they will not occur all at once, and will
only be smaller satellite offices, he said. Other than the Yakima
office, Yager declined to identify other offices that might shut
down.
   He said the October stock market crash was not the cause of the
closings, although the current market was ``soft.''
   Merrill Lynch, the nation's biggest brokerage firm, has about
500 U.S. offices, and the opening, closing or consolidation of
offices is not rare, Yager said.
   The closing of the Yakima office, which is expected ``sometime
before April,'' had not been disclosed officially yet to employees
or customers, Yager said.
   The business of the office in this central Washington city will
be consolidated into other offices in the state, Yager said.
   The fate of the approximately 20 employees of the Yakima office
is undecided. Yager said the 10 or 11 brokers will likely be
relocated, except for those who are not producing income for the
company. He did not say how many that could be.
</TEXT>
