<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     10-06 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AI Solicits Reorganization Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. is calling on its
investors to submit by Monday any plans they may have for
reorganizing the financially troubled consumer products company.
   Among those interested in controlling the company is Victor
Kiam, president and chief executive of the shaver manufacturer
Remington Products Inc. Kiam, who has a stake in the company, is
reviewing confidential financial information, Allegheny
International said.
   Management said it also held talks with Los Angeles
multimillionaire David H. Murdock, who first offered more than two
years ago to take over the company.
   Allegheny International has been operating under protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. bankruptcy code since
February. The company's management is willing to step aside if
required under an acceptable reorganization plan, although a
successful plan might keep the current management in place, said
company spokesman Edward M. Romonoff.
   A stockholders plan filed within the last week calls for
stockholders to keep 50 percent of the reorganized company and to
receive rights to buy another 30 percent for $30 million. The plan
would give an outside investor, such as Kiam, rights to the rest of
the company for $20 million. The management team under Chairman
Oliver S. Travers Jr. would be replaced.
   The shareholders' plan would pay creditors between 50 percent
and full value for their claims.
   Management's reorganization plan has been criticized by every
major creditor group. It calls for bankers and creditors of
Allegheny's Sunbeam Corp. subsidiary to be repaid in full, while
other creditors would get 60 cents to 85 cents on the dollar, and
shareholders interests would be diluted by 75 percent.
   Allegheny management has the exclusive right to submit a
reorganization plan through Oct. 27, although U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Joseph L. Cosetti last month said he would accept plan outlines
from committess representing shareholders, unsecured creditors and
Sunbeam's creditors.
   Meanwhile, Allegheny International sent letters to four former
officers, including former Chairman Robert J. Buckley, calling in
low-interest loans of more than $4.3 million made to them in the
early 1980s. The company said the loans would be due in full Oct.
22 unless the men begin making payments.
   All four claim in separate complaints filed with the court that
they should not have to repay the money until Allegheny
International restores benefits taken away by the board in March
1987.
</TEXT>
