<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chrysler-Fiat     10-06 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler-Fiat,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler, Fiat Form Joint Venture In North America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. and Fiat Auto SpA of
Italy have formed a joint venture to market Alfa Romeo cars in
North America, Chrysler announced Thursday.
   The still-unnamed joint venture will import Alfa Romeo's three
car lines _ the Spider, Milano and 164 _ to North America from
Italy during the coming year, Chrysler spokeswoman Karen Stewart
said.
   The cars will be offered through a limited network of what
eventually will be about 250 Chrysler-Plymouth and Alfa Romeo
dealerships, she said.
   The venture ``combines Fiat's recognized manufacturing,
production and design expertise with Chrysler's strong marketing
and distribution capabilities in the North American market,''
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said.
   ``We are confident our association with Chrysler will result in
increased market opportunities to help us to reach higher sales
volumes in North America,'' Fiat Group Chairman Giovanni Agnelli
said.
   Chrysler and Fiat will split the profits from the joint venture,
which Stewart said was to be legally executed within 60 days. She
would not disclose the amount of money either company is committing
to the project.
   Fiat bought Alfa Romeo less than two years ago.
</TEXT>
